1
00:00:14,014 --> 00:00:17,484
You're watching <i>Chef & My Fridge,</i>
a special Lunar New Year Episode.

2
00:00:17,550 --> 00:00:19,719
<i>In the previous episode,</i>
<i>we had a party for our chefs,</i>

3
00:00:19,786 --> 00:00:23,023
and today,
we're back with a banquet for them.

4
00:00:23,089 --> 00:00:27,460
-Happy Lunar New Year, everyone!
-Happy Lunar New Year!

5
00:00:27,527 --> 00:00:28,762
Happy Lunar New Year!

6
00:00:28,828 --> 00:00:30,663
-We wish you good health.
-Happy New Year!

7
00:00:30,730 --> 00:00:32,399
THE CHEFS CAME DRESSED IN BEAUTIFUL HANBOK

8
00:00:32,465 --> 00:00:34,334
I wish you great luck this year.

9
00:00:34,768 --> 00:00:36,069
WISHING YOU LONGEVITY

10
00:00:36,136 --> 00:00:39,773
During last year's Chuseok holiday,

11
00:00:39,839 --> 00:00:42,942
<i>we introduced many</i>
<i>domestic food ingredients to the world.</i>

12
00:00:43,009 --> 00:00:44,577
So for the New Year,

13
00:00:44,644 --> 00:00:47,580
we thought we could show them
our traditional attire.

14
00:00:47,647 --> 00:00:49,149
-That's why we're dressed up.
-How nice.

15
00:00:49,215 --> 00:00:50,817
-That's right.
-Everyone's looking great.

16
00:00:50,884 --> 00:00:52,652
Has it been a while
since you've worn <i>hanbok?</i>

17
00:00:52,719 --> 00:00:53,920
Doesn't he look like

18
00:00:53,987 --> 00:00:56,423
-a shaman named Young Napoli Boy?
-Young Napoli Boy?

19
00:00:56,489 --> 00:00:57,957
AHEM

20
00:00:58,425 --> 00:00:59,926
HE SEEMS SPIRITUAL

21
00:00:59,993 --> 00:01:01,127
A spiritual shaman.

22
00:01:01,194 --> 00:01:03,096
<i>Chef & My Fridge</i> will do well.

23
00:01:03,163 --> 00:01:05,398
-It'll do well in 2026.
-Really?

24
00:01:05,465 --> 00:01:07,634
Chef Eun-yeong also looks lovely today.

25
00:01:07,901 --> 00:01:08,935
LIKE A PRIM AND PROPER LADY

26
00:01:09,002 --> 00:01:10,870
She looks so normal.

27
00:01:12,038 --> 00:01:14,007
-As long as she isn't glaring at anyone.
-She seems ordinary,

28
00:01:14,074 --> 00:01:16,443
but she's someone
who has many different sides.

29
00:01:16,509 --> 00:01:18,411
-And look at Chef Jong-won.
-He looks great.

30
00:01:18,478 --> 00:01:20,080
-Look at you.
-So sophisticated.

31
00:01:20,146 --> 00:01:22,148
-That's his personal <i>hanbok.</i>
-Is it?

32
00:01:22,215 --> 00:01:24,451
-Really?
-That's what modern <i>hanbok</i> is like?

33
00:01:24,517 --> 00:01:27,020
I once went to an awards ceremony
with many international chefs,

34
00:01:27,087 --> 00:01:29,789
<i>-called Asia's 50 Best Restaurants.</i>
<i>-Asia's 50 Best Restaurants.</i>

35
00:01:29,856 --> 00:01:32,525
<i>As a chef in Korean cuisine,</i>
<i>I wanted to share our traditional beauty,</i>

36
00:01:33,159 --> 00:01:35,295
so I went out of my way
and got this tailored.

37
00:01:35,361 --> 00:01:37,897
-So I'm wearing it once again.
-You look great.

38
00:01:37,964 --> 00:01:39,833
Chef Hyun-suk,
you remind me of Song Chang-sik.

39
00:01:40,233 --> 00:01:42,168
HE EVEN LOOKS LIKE HIM

40
00:01:42,735 --> 00:01:43,937
I personally think

41
00:01:44,003 --> 00:01:46,106
it's because I'm sitting. Once I stand,

42
00:01:46,172 --> 00:01:49,409
-I'll look like a royal bodyguard.
-Can you stand up?

43
00:01:49,476 --> 00:01:50,310
ROYAL BODYGUARD STANDS

44
00:01:50,376 --> 00:01:51,444
I can see it.

45
00:01:52,045 --> 00:01:53,413
HI-YAH

46
00:01:53,480 --> 00:01:55,482
Right? You can see it.

47
00:01:57,717 --> 00:02:00,153
For the Lunar New Year Episode,
a banquet for our chefs,

48
00:02:00,220 --> 00:02:02,989
we prepared yet another special segment.

49
00:02:03,056 --> 00:02:04,657
It's called

50
00:02:04,724 --> 00:02:06,960
<i>Chef & My Fridge</i> Ask Us Anything.

51
00:02:07,026 --> 00:02:08,461
-Let us begin.
-AUA.

52
00:02:08,528 --> 00:02:11,764
Many viewers
have questions about the chefs,

53
00:02:11,831 --> 00:02:14,134
so we gathered the questions

54
00:02:14,200 --> 00:02:16,169
to open an Ask Us Anything session.

55
00:02:16,736 --> 00:02:18,905
This is the first question.

56
00:02:20,039 --> 00:02:22,976
What goes on behind the scenes
in the greenroom?

57
00:02:23,042 --> 00:02:24,477
-Ah, the greenroom.
-Yes.

58
00:02:24,544 --> 00:02:28,681
I need to take this one
for everyone's sake.

59
00:02:28,748 --> 00:02:30,216
One of the chefs

60
00:02:30,283 --> 00:02:33,453
keeps blasting the heater in there.

61
00:02:33,520 --> 00:02:34,988
-It feels like a sauna.
-It's so hot.

62
00:02:35,054 --> 00:02:39,125
When I open the window, they run to it,
closes it, and goes, "Who did this?"

63
00:02:39,192 --> 00:02:40,960
Because they're cold?

64
00:02:41,027 --> 00:02:43,396
So we can't go in the greenroom,
afraid we'd die of the heat.

65
00:02:43,463 --> 00:02:45,899
-I know he's old, but…
-He gets too cold.

66
00:02:45,965 --> 00:02:47,066
GUILTY

67
00:02:47,133 --> 00:02:49,235
-I have evidence.
-I wonder who it is. Show us.

68
00:02:49,302 --> 00:02:51,671
-This happened recently.
-It's from Chef Sung-jun.

69
00:02:54,040 --> 00:02:56,276
He's like, "Who opened this?"
Poong goes, "It's too hot!"

70
00:02:56,342 --> 00:02:57,710
Is that what's going on?

71
00:02:57,777 --> 00:03:00,613
Sung-jun and Eun-yeong
can't even say a word.

72
00:03:00,680 --> 00:03:01,915
No one would dare.

73
00:03:01,981 --> 00:03:04,150
-Can you explain the situation?
-What's going on?

74
00:03:04,217 --> 00:03:06,186
Let me share exactly what is going on.

75
00:03:06,252 --> 00:03:09,856
The chefs were having a hard time
coping with the heat.

76
00:03:09,923 --> 00:03:11,691
So I opened the window slightly.

77
00:03:11,758 --> 00:03:14,694
And then, he yelled,
"Who opened the window?"

78
00:03:14,761 --> 00:03:17,697
So I told him, "I did. Bite me!"

79
00:03:18,097 --> 00:03:19,399
THAT FELT SO GOOD

80
00:03:19,465 --> 00:03:21,234
Isn't that tyranny?

81
00:03:21,301 --> 00:03:23,336
<i>Hyun-suk loves to keep the window closed.</i>

82
00:03:23,403 --> 00:03:25,438
HYUN-SUK'S LOCKING UP

83
00:03:26,339 --> 00:03:27,941
Honestly speaking,

84
00:03:28,007 --> 00:03:30,443
-I'm easily affected by the cold.
-I see.

85
00:03:30,510 --> 00:03:33,246
But more importantly, Chef Eun-yeong

86
00:03:33,313 --> 00:03:35,782
-gets even colder than I do.
-I see.

87
00:03:35,848 --> 00:03:37,050
THAT'S NEWS TO US

88
00:03:37,116 --> 00:03:38,551
So even when I feel warm,

89
00:03:38,618 --> 00:03:40,620
-I keep it warm for her sake.
-That isn't the case.

90
00:03:40,687 --> 00:03:41,821
That's all.

91
00:03:41,888 --> 00:03:44,023
It was to protect Chef Eun-yeong?

92
00:03:44,090 --> 00:03:46,226
I do get easily affected by the cold,

93
00:03:46,292 --> 00:03:48,761
but by the time I return home
after a shoot here,

94
00:03:48,828 --> 00:03:50,096
I have heat rashes all over.

95
00:03:50,396 --> 00:03:52,031
WHY ARE YOU DOING THIS TO ME?

96
00:03:52,098 --> 00:03:53,433
You even get heat rashes?

97
00:03:53,866 --> 00:03:56,302
THE GREENROOM IS STEAMING HOT

98
00:03:56,703 --> 00:03:58,571
I NEVER WANTED THAT

99
00:03:58,638 --> 00:04:00,740
The world of culinary arts
is rotten to its core.

100
00:04:01,074 --> 00:04:01,941
AND THE GREENROOM IS HOT

101
00:04:02,008 --> 00:04:03,409
Show us the next question.

102
00:04:04,911 --> 00:04:07,981
What did the chefs look like
when they were children?

103
00:04:08,047 --> 00:04:10,717
We'll show you the pictures
without telling you who it is.

104
00:04:10,783 --> 00:04:12,318
Why don't we take a guess together?

105
00:04:12,385 --> 00:04:14,487
-That sounds fun.
-Whose childhood is this?

106
00:04:14,554 --> 00:04:15,755
Show us!

107
00:04:15,822 --> 00:04:18,324
TAKE A GUESS, VIEWERS

108
00:04:18,691 --> 00:04:19,792
<i>That's a very old picture.</i>

109
00:04:19,859 --> 00:04:21,527
<i>-That thing.</i>
<i>-That's from a long time ago.</i>

110
00:04:21,594 --> 00:04:24,030
<i>I see a 5,000-won bill on the floor.</i>

111
00:04:24,097 --> 00:04:25,465
<i>He wore headphones back then?</i>

112
00:04:25,531 --> 00:04:27,033
-Who is it?
-Back then?

113
00:04:27,100 --> 00:04:28,668
-His family must've been rich.
-So cute.

114
00:04:28,735 --> 00:04:29,802
-Chef Sam.
-Chef Sam?

115
00:04:29,869 --> 00:04:33,072
It's not me. I think his cheeks
look similar to this guy's.

116
00:04:33,139 --> 00:04:34,741
Ho-young?

117
00:04:34,807 --> 00:04:36,809
-Are those his cheeks?
-My cheeks came much later.

118
00:04:36,876 --> 00:04:39,312
You're almost 50,
and you still have baby fat?

119
00:04:39,379 --> 00:04:41,381
We have one more picture of this child.

120
00:04:41,447 --> 00:04:42,348
<i>Show us.</i>

121
00:04:43,616 --> 00:04:45,385
-It's Poong.
-Webtoon Artist Poong.

122
00:04:45,451 --> 00:04:46,886
It's Poong.

123
00:04:46,953 --> 00:04:49,389
-It's Poong.
-It's Webtoon Artist Poong.

124
00:04:49,455 --> 00:04:50,590
ADD GLASSES AND YOU GET POONG

125
00:04:50,657 --> 00:04:51,991
-You're right.
-I can see it now.

126
00:04:52,058 --> 00:04:53,960
-It was Webtoon Artist Poong.
-How cute.

127
00:04:54,027 --> 00:04:55,528
The next picture

128
00:04:55,595 --> 00:04:57,730
includes the chef's family,
so take a good look.

129
00:04:57,797 --> 00:04:58,631
Show us.

130
00:04:59,399 --> 00:05:00,900
HUH?! THIS CHILD…

131
00:05:00,967 --> 00:05:02,302
His parents are in the picture.

132
00:05:02,368 --> 00:05:03,202
Show us.

133
00:05:04,971 --> 00:05:05,905
<i>This is so old.</i>

134
00:05:05,972 --> 00:05:07,874
<i>-His parents are in the picture.</i>
<i>-You can see…</i>

135
00:05:07,940 --> 00:05:10,143
He looks similar to how he does now.
Look at his lips.

136
00:05:10,209 --> 00:05:12,478
-Does he look similar to now?
-You're right.

137
00:05:12,545 --> 00:05:14,347
-That's Jong-won's face.
-You're right.

138
00:05:14,547 --> 00:05:15,648
HIS LIPS!

139
00:05:15,715 --> 00:05:19,018
-Your father is a handsome man.
-He's good-looking.

140
00:05:19,085 --> 00:05:21,421
He brought one more picture.
Let me show it to you.

141
00:05:22,021 --> 00:05:22,922
Right here.

142
00:05:23,823 --> 00:05:24,857
<i>That's from so long ago.</i>

143
00:05:25,658 --> 00:05:26,592
<i>He's still the same.</i>

144
00:05:26,659 --> 00:05:28,628
The middle picture looks just like him.

145
00:05:28,695 --> 00:05:30,863
-You can see his current face.
-He's the same.

146
00:05:30,930 --> 00:05:33,433
I'm sorry, crew.
But can you get rid of the heart?

147
00:05:34,901 --> 00:05:36,502
-There's too much exposure.
-How cute.

148
00:05:36,569 --> 00:05:37,870
You're too exposed?

149
00:05:37,937 --> 00:05:40,606
This family had a bathtub.
We used a red plastic basin.

150
00:05:40,673 --> 00:05:42,475
<i>-A basin?</i>
<i>-The red basin?</i>

151
00:05:42,542 --> 00:05:44,577
-That was my bathtub.
-The one used to make kimchi?

152
00:05:44,644 --> 00:05:46,245
-And it's tiled!
-The kimchi basin.

153
00:05:46,312 --> 00:05:48,348
What is that? Italian tiles?

154
00:05:48,414 --> 00:05:49,849
He must be from a well-off family.

155
00:05:49,916 --> 00:05:52,452
He had cake on his birthday,
and there's a huge closet.

156
00:05:52,518 --> 00:05:55,521
Not many kids back then blew candles,
wearing a party hat and a bow tie.

157
00:05:55,588 --> 00:05:57,724
-You're right.
-Even a bow tie.

158
00:05:57,790 --> 00:05:59,325
-You were rich.
-Look at that couch.

159
00:05:59,392 --> 00:06:01,260
-The couch.
-Here's another important note.

160
00:06:01,327 --> 00:06:02,795
Do you see that closet?

161
00:06:02,862 --> 00:06:05,264
-Made from royal foxglove tree.
-Man.

162
00:06:05,331 --> 00:06:06,265
That's insane.

163
00:06:06,332 --> 00:06:08,167
-How can you tell?
-I knew he was rich.

164
00:06:08,234 --> 00:06:10,069
-He was well-off.
-He really was.

165
00:06:10,136 --> 00:06:12,505
-He grew up into a wonderful person.
-He looked rich.

166
00:06:12,572 --> 00:06:14,440
<i>That's why he's like this now.</i>

167
00:06:14,507 --> 00:06:15,375
<i>Next, please.</i>

168
00:06:15,641 --> 00:06:17,543
WHO'S THE NEXT KID?

169
00:06:18,244 --> 00:06:20,046
<i>-Wait a second.</i>
<i>-Look at his facial expression.</i>

170
00:06:20,113 --> 00:06:21,748
<i>-He's quite angry.</i>
<i>-That's Ho-young!</i>

171
00:06:21,814 --> 00:06:22,715
Is that you, Ho-young?

172
00:06:22,782 --> 00:06:24,684
-That's him.
-You can tell by his brows.

173
00:06:24,751 --> 00:06:25,718
He has the same tummy.

174
00:06:25,785 --> 00:06:28,221
-Even though you were skinny.
-The kid already has the same tummy.

175
00:06:28,287 --> 00:06:31,324
-Did you weigh 55 kg back then?
-Me? 55 kg?

176
00:06:31,391 --> 00:06:33,092
MY MASTER

177
00:06:33,159 --> 00:06:35,561
<i>He had the cooking sack even back then.</i>

178
00:06:35,628 --> 00:06:37,330
<i>-He did.</i>
<i>-A kid with a cooking sack.</i>

179
00:06:37,397 --> 00:06:38,331
Who's next?

180
00:06:40,166 --> 00:06:42,135
<i>The images look sharper, right?</i>

181
00:06:42,201 --> 00:06:43,469
<i>-I can see him.</i>
<i>-It's him.</i>

182
00:06:43,536 --> 00:06:44,971
-How cute.
-He looks mischievous.

183
00:06:45,037 --> 00:06:46,739
-How cute. Who's that?
-He does.

184
00:06:46,806 --> 00:06:48,775
He had that hair back then,

185
00:06:48,841 --> 00:06:52,378
something we used to call
"the cool factor."

186
00:06:52,445 --> 00:06:54,714
He didn't have too much dough back then.

187
00:06:54,781 --> 00:06:56,849
-"Dough"?
-He gained some dough now.

188
00:06:56,916 --> 00:06:58,885
His cheeks look so plump, How cute.

189
00:06:58,951 --> 00:07:00,686
-You have the same nose.
-I do.

190
00:07:00,753 --> 00:07:02,989
I can tell by his clothes
that he was well-off, too.

191
00:07:03,055 --> 00:07:04,390
The next one is tough to guess.

192
00:07:04,457 --> 00:07:05,291
TOUGH TO GUESS?

193
00:07:06,225 --> 00:07:07,660
We got black-and-white pictures.

194
00:07:09,595 --> 00:07:10,830
We got black-and-white pictures.

195
00:07:10,897 --> 00:07:12,698
<i>Is that during the Korean War?</i>

196
00:07:12,765 --> 00:07:15,067
AN IMPORTANT HISTORIC RECORD
REFLECTING LIFE IN THOSE DAYS

197
00:07:15,768 --> 00:07:17,503
ONE MORE LOOK, IT'S STILL FUNNY

198
00:07:17,904 --> 00:07:19,439
BORN DURING THE WAR(?) AND DROVE TANKS

199
00:07:19,505 --> 00:07:21,541
<i>Did you say this was hard to guess?</i>

200
00:07:21,607 --> 00:07:24,343
Was that during the famine?
Looks like times were tough.

201
00:07:24,410 --> 00:07:26,913
<i>-Was that during the 1950s?</i>
<i>-It looks like it.</i>

202
00:07:26,979 --> 00:07:29,015
My gosh. The homes in the background.

203
00:07:29,081 --> 00:07:30,716
Most people lived in shacks.

204
00:07:30,783 --> 00:07:32,351
-The houses…
-My place was like that too.

205
00:07:32,418 --> 00:07:34,620
The true meaning
of Black Spoons and White Spoons.

206
00:07:36,122 --> 00:07:38,724
He's not in color. It's black-and-white.

207
00:07:39,659 --> 00:07:41,627
Was he born in 1945,
the year of Liberation?

208
00:07:42,028 --> 00:07:42,962
HE'S THE EMOTIONAL TYPE

209
00:07:43,029 --> 00:07:46,199
Other chefs so far were well-off
during their childhood.

210
00:07:46,265 --> 00:07:47,767
CHUCKLE

211
00:07:47,834 --> 00:07:48,768
But here…

212
00:07:48,835 --> 00:07:50,036
SOBS

213
00:07:50,102 --> 00:07:53,072
<i>Shouldn't you have been well-off</i>
<i>if you had a tank back then?</i>

214
00:07:53,139 --> 00:07:55,808
Jong-won, are you crying
because it's sad, or funny?

215
00:07:55,875 --> 00:07:58,978
-I don't know.
-He wouldn't get it. He had a bathtub.

216
00:07:59,045 --> 00:08:00,179
The tiled tub.

217
00:08:00,246 --> 00:08:02,215
-You're right.
-Tile Son.

218
00:08:02,281 --> 00:08:03,483
Tile Son, come on.

219
00:08:03,549 --> 00:08:06,719
I finally understand
why he keeps sprinkling salt like that.

220
00:08:06,786 --> 00:08:09,222
<i>-Back then, it was a precious commodity.</i>
<i>-It was precious.</i>

221
00:08:09,288 --> 00:08:11,023
<i>He gets to sprinkle</i>
<i>as much as he wants to now.</i>

222
00:08:11,090 --> 00:08:14,060
<i>Let's try to understand.</i>
<i>I'm done teasing him.</i>

223
00:08:14,126 --> 00:08:16,062
-I won't tease him for that anymore.
-Please don't.

224
00:08:16,128 --> 00:08:17,296
He had a reason.

225
00:08:17,363 --> 00:08:19,398
-It was too precious back then.
-It's a sob story.

226
00:08:19,465 --> 00:08:21,701
-You're right.
-Back then,

227
00:08:21,767 --> 00:08:24,303
color cameras were more expensive.

228
00:08:25,304 --> 00:08:28,307
We just needed these pictures,
but he provided color photos too.

229
00:08:28,374 --> 00:08:30,676
-He had those?
-He insisted we show them too.

230
00:08:30,743 --> 00:08:32,078
"I have color pictures too."

231
00:08:32,144 --> 00:08:34,647
Yes, "We took pictures in color too."

232
00:08:34,714 --> 00:08:36,616
-Hyun-suk's color photos.
-The color photos.

233
00:08:38,484 --> 00:08:39,418
TALL AND WELL-BUILT

234
00:08:39,485 --> 00:08:41,420
<i>He was built different.</i>

235
00:08:41,487 --> 00:08:42,722
<i>His limbs are so long.</i>

236
00:08:42,788 --> 00:08:45,091
Did your family's fortune
turn around in a few years?

237
00:08:45,157 --> 00:08:46,826
HE'S LOOKING MUCH BETTER

238
00:08:46,893 --> 00:08:49,595
<i>-He's dressed more sharp.</i>
<i>-He's looking sharp.</i>

239
00:08:49,662 --> 00:08:52,031
<i>-He was different.</i>
<i>-I'm happy for him.</i>

240
00:08:52,098 --> 00:08:53,199
<i>-That's the kind of guy he was.</i>

241
00:08:53,266 --> 00:08:54,667
The next one is a photo

242
00:08:54,734 --> 00:08:56,469
-from their first birthday.
-First birthday?

243
00:08:56,536 --> 00:08:58,104
Who do you think this is?

244
00:08:58,671 --> 00:09:00,339
WAIT A SECOND

245
00:09:02,675 --> 00:09:03,509
The one in the middle?

246
00:09:03,576 --> 00:09:05,378
ANYONE CAN TELL WHO HE IS

247
00:09:05,444 --> 00:09:06,379
<i>-Man.</i>
<i>-I know who he is.</i>

248
00:09:06,445 --> 00:09:09,215
You were always blessed with food.

249
00:09:09,782 --> 00:09:12,318
A BOY BORN BLESSED WITH FOOD

250
00:09:12,385 --> 00:09:14,720
-That's your first birthday?
-Why is there so much food?

251
00:09:14,787 --> 00:09:17,623
-It's piled up.
-That much is a feast for the town.

252
00:09:17,690 --> 00:09:19,225
Look at that pineapple.

253
00:09:19,292 --> 00:09:20,593
MOUNTAINS OF FOOD

254
00:09:20,660 --> 00:09:22,328
<i>Pineapples, grapes…</i>

255
00:09:22,395 --> 00:09:23,462
<i>Look at the rice cakes.</i>

256
00:09:23,529 --> 00:09:25,231
<i>-And the 10,000-won bills.</i>
<i>-Apples.</i>

257
00:09:25,298 --> 00:09:27,199
<i>Bananas were pretty rare back then.</i>

258
00:09:27,266 --> 00:09:29,168
<i>-There's even a pineapple.</i>
<i>-Right?</i>

259
00:09:29,235 --> 00:09:31,938
Why is there so much food?
Why did I eat so much?

260
00:09:32,004 --> 00:09:33,406
<i>Do you remember</i>

261
00:09:33,472 --> 00:09:35,908
<i>-Chef Jong-won's first birthday photo?</i>
<i>-They're different.</i>

262
00:09:35,975 --> 00:09:37,343
<i>Quite the contrast.</i>

263
00:09:37,410 --> 00:09:38,644
He was well-off too.

264
00:09:38,711 --> 00:09:40,112
-Who do we have left?
-Two.

265
00:09:40,179 --> 00:09:41,714
-Two people.
-Eun-yeong and Sam.

266
00:09:41,781 --> 00:09:45,117
And now, we'll show you a picture
that'll also be a quiz.

267
00:09:45,184 --> 00:09:47,420
-Try to guess who Eun-yeong is.
-Right, she's a twin.

268
00:09:47,486 --> 00:09:48,788
Now, show us.

269
00:09:49,589 --> 00:09:51,424
-She's a baby.
-Who's Eun-yeong?

270
00:09:51,490 --> 00:09:52,458
<i>They look the same.</i>

271
00:09:52,525 --> 00:09:54,226
<i>-The left side.</i>
<i>-The left girl.</i>

272
00:09:54,293 --> 00:09:56,028
<i>Don't say anything, Eun-yeong.</i>

273
00:09:56,095 --> 00:09:58,631
-The girl in blue.
-It's blue.

274
00:09:58,698 --> 00:10:00,499
-I say green.
-Team Blue, raise your hand.

275
00:10:00,566 --> 00:10:02,134
TEAM BLUE

276
00:10:02,201 --> 00:10:03,235
TEAM GREEN

277
00:10:03,302 --> 00:10:04,670
She's a bit less cute.

278
00:10:04,737 --> 00:10:07,073
-You're so annoying.
-What's your reason, Team Blue?

279
00:10:07,139 --> 00:10:10,376
She has the same eyes as her
when she dances.

280
00:10:10,443 --> 00:10:12,211
<i>You're right.</i>
<i>That's the "Queencard" dance.</i>

281
00:10:12,278 --> 00:10:13,346
What's your reason for green?

282
00:10:13,412 --> 00:10:16,015
She has that younger sister vibe,

283
00:10:16,082 --> 00:10:17,984
-She looks small.
-with a low energy level.

284
00:10:18,050 --> 00:10:19,218
<i>They may be minutes apart,</i>

285
00:10:19,285 --> 00:10:21,420
<i>-but the vibes are different.</i>
<i>-She's in green.</i>

286
00:10:21,487 --> 00:10:23,389
-Which one are you?
-You're in green.

287
00:10:23,456 --> 00:10:25,558
-I'm on the left.
-You are?

288
00:10:25,625 --> 00:10:27,893
EUN-YEONG, EUN-YEONG'S SISTER

289
00:10:27,960 --> 00:10:30,029
-In blue.
-Really?

290
00:10:30,096 --> 00:10:32,465
I've always had
a stronger personality than my sister.

291
00:10:32,531 --> 00:10:35,167
THE QUEEN HAS ALWAYS OVERPOWERED
HER OLDER SISTER

292
00:10:35,234 --> 00:10:37,336
Look at your sister.
She dropped her plushie too.

293
00:10:37,403 --> 00:10:39,705
DROPPED HER PLUSHIE…
AND LOW ON ENERGY…

294
00:10:39,772 --> 00:10:42,775
<i>-But you're holding yours tightly.</i>
<i>-She has scary eyes.</i>

295
00:10:42,842 --> 00:10:46,812
You can see the home environment
when you look at old pictures, right?

296
00:10:46,879 --> 00:10:48,214
<i>We don't use this anymore,</i>

297
00:10:48,280 --> 00:10:50,983
<i>-but she had a stereo system.</i>
<i>-You're right.</i>

298
00:10:51,050 --> 00:10:53,252
<i>She had a stereo system in the back.</i>

299
00:10:53,319 --> 00:10:54,687
You were well-off.

300
00:10:54,754 --> 00:10:56,722
Lastly, Chef Sam's pictures.

301
00:10:56,789 --> 00:10:57,757
Let's take a look.

302
00:11:00,459 --> 00:11:01,927
-He must've been well-off too.
-He was.

303
00:11:01,994 --> 00:11:03,896
-He had a phone.
-That phone.

304
00:11:03,963 --> 00:11:05,731
YOU WERE WELL-OFF!

305
00:11:05,798 --> 00:11:08,634
-You were well-off.
-You were. You even had a phone.

306
00:11:08,701 --> 00:11:09,735
On your graduation day,

307
00:11:09,802 --> 00:11:12,805
you got a present wrapped with gold paper.
You were well-off.

308
00:11:12,872 --> 00:11:15,274
Is he wearing Adidas?

309
00:11:15,341 --> 00:11:17,843
-Whoa, back in those days?
-A brand-name product.

310
00:11:17,910 --> 00:11:19,345
RUMORS OF HIS AFFLUENT CHILDHOOD SPREADS

311
00:11:19,412 --> 00:11:20,913
-Lucky you.
-And he's barefoot.

312
00:11:20,980 --> 00:11:22,848
Everyone was well-off
except for you, Hyun-suk.

313
00:11:23,783 --> 00:11:25,718
-I want to see his picture again.
-It's because

314
00:11:25,785 --> 00:11:26,886
it was right after the war.

315
00:11:28,287 --> 00:11:29,588
HE GIVES IN

316
00:11:29,655 --> 00:11:31,557
Can we see his pictures again?

317
00:11:31,624 --> 00:11:33,826
-Can we see them again?
-Chef Hyun-suk.

318
00:11:33,893 --> 00:11:35,294
That's enough.

319
00:11:36,495 --> 00:11:38,497
-I want to see them again.
-Hyun-suk and the tank.

320
00:11:38,564 --> 00:11:40,700
I have a confession to make.
Can you show them?

321
00:11:42,535 --> 00:11:44,170
LAUGHTER TRIGGER

322
00:11:44,236 --> 00:11:46,572
-Remember photo studios?
-You're only five years older than me.

323
00:11:46,639 --> 00:11:49,108
Everyone, to be honest,
the tank I was seen in

324
00:11:49,175 --> 00:11:50,609
was a painting.

325
00:11:51,377 --> 00:11:53,512
You were born in the same year as I was,

326
00:11:53,579 --> 00:11:56,982
but none of my pictures are like that.

327
00:11:57,049 --> 00:11:58,317
That screams the Korean War.

328
00:11:59,418 --> 00:12:01,053
LIKE A GROWN-UP

329
00:12:01,120 --> 00:12:02,221
Stop laughing at him!

330
00:12:02,288 --> 00:12:03,122
What's really sad is

331
00:12:03,189 --> 00:12:06,025
that these are pictures
he picked out for the occasion.

332
00:12:06,726 --> 00:12:08,027
-His best pictures.
-The best.

333
00:12:08,094 --> 00:12:10,563
-You're the worst.
-His most prosperous days.

334
00:12:10,629 --> 00:12:13,065
He's dressed properly, though.

335
00:12:13,132 --> 00:12:15,167
-And he has shoes on.
-He does.

336
00:12:15,234 --> 00:12:17,503
-He needs a haircut, though.
-I'm getting dizzy.

337
00:12:17,570 --> 00:12:19,004
-All right.
-That was funny.

338
00:12:19,071 --> 00:12:20,840
-This is <i>Chef & My Fridge</i> Ask Us Anything.
-That was fun.

339
00:12:20,906 --> 00:12:22,575
It's the last question.

340
00:12:23,142 --> 00:12:25,644
Who do you think would win
if the chefs fought each other?

341
00:12:25,711 --> 00:12:27,847
That question is way too juvenile.

342
00:12:27,913 --> 00:12:29,548
Was it sent by an elementary school kid?

343
00:12:29,615 --> 00:12:31,884
It must be
Chef Sam's elementary school fan.

344
00:12:32,218 --> 00:12:33,319
THOSE WHO ARE DESPERATE FOR VICTORY

345
00:12:33,385 --> 00:12:35,287
-They're wild.
-So combative.

346
00:12:35,354 --> 00:12:38,657
Our chefs have done
a few physical matches on the show.

347
00:12:38,724 --> 00:12:40,559
<i>Hyun-suk won the arm wrestling match</i>

348
00:12:40,626 --> 00:12:42,394
<i>and Jong-won was the punching king.</i>

349
00:12:42,461 --> 00:12:45,431
-But one of you couldn't accept that.
-Who is it?

350
00:12:45,498 --> 00:12:48,167
This person claims,
"True power comes from the thighs."

351
00:12:49,201 --> 00:12:50,803
It's anonymous, but I think I know.

352
00:12:50,870 --> 00:12:52,805
Was it the year 2019?

353
00:12:52,872 --> 00:12:54,406
THE MAN WITH HUGE THIGHS

354
00:12:54,874 --> 00:12:56,475
KIM POONG

355
00:12:56,542 --> 00:12:59,578
<i>Webtoon Artist Kim Poong</i>
<i>had risen victorious in thigh wrestling.</i>

356
00:12:59,645 --> 00:13:02,982
-He's unbelievably strong.
-That was back in 2019.

357
00:13:03,048 --> 00:13:04,583
It's a question from a young child,

358
00:13:04,650 --> 00:13:06,552
-but let's not turn it into a real fight.
-No.

359
00:13:06,619 --> 00:13:08,554
We do <i>ssireum</i>, traditional wrestling,
during the holidays,

360
00:13:08,621 --> 00:13:11,624
so let's find out who's the strongest
through a thigh wrestling match.

361
00:13:11,690 --> 00:13:13,926
I might have a better chance
if it were an actual fight.

362
00:13:13,993 --> 00:13:15,461
THE SPIRIT OF THE 54-YEAR-OLD

363
00:13:15,528 --> 00:13:19,532
If people my age strain too hard,
we may end up dislocating our hip joints.

364
00:13:19,598 --> 00:13:21,367
OH, GOSH

365
00:13:21,433 --> 00:13:23,669
-Why are you so sad today?
-That could happen.

366
00:13:23,736 --> 00:13:24,804
My doctor told me

367
00:13:24,870 --> 00:13:27,907
that I must change my ways
from how I had lived until now.

368
00:13:29,041 --> 00:13:31,076
Poong will be ready for you
in the final round.

369
00:13:31,143 --> 00:13:33,679
<i>So the first round</i>
<i>is between Sam and Ho-young,</i>

370
00:13:33,746 --> 00:13:35,581
<i>followed by Nam-no versus Sung-jun.</i>

371
00:13:35,648 --> 00:13:37,116
<i>Then, the winners will compete,</i>

372
00:13:37,183 --> 00:13:39,919
<i>and the winner will fight</i>
<i>either Jong-won or Hyun-suk.</i>

373
00:13:39,985 --> 00:13:42,054
<i>The winner of that round</i>
<i>gets to fight Poong.</i>

374
00:13:42,121 --> 00:13:44,123
Eun-yeong will sit this one out.

375
00:13:44,190 --> 00:13:46,292
She's the only opponent I could beat.

376
00:13:46,358 --> 00:13:47,760
Sam and Ho-young, you're up.

377
00:13:47,827 --> 00:13:49,695
-You never know.
-How do you do it?

378
00:13:49,762 --> 00:13:52,264
Chef Ho-young
definitely has the upper hand.

379
00:13:52,331 --> 00:13:54,300
The shorter your legs are,
the easier it is to flex.

380
00:13:54,366 --> 00:13:56,368
My legs are too short for this.

381
00:13:56,435 --> 00:13:57,937
His thighs really are short.

382
00:13:58,304 --> 00:13:59,605
SHOW US THE POWER OF SHORT LEGS

383
00:13:59,672 --> 00:14:01,373
You'll each take a turn
to attack and defend.

384
00:14:01,440 --> 00:14:03,075
First, Ho-young defends,

385
00:14:03,142 --> 00:14:04,977
and Sam attacks.

386
00:14:05,044 --> 00:14:07,112
You lose if his legs spread
more than a fist's width.

387
00:14:07,179 --> 00:14:09,281
-This is intense.
-Get ready.

388
00:14:09,348 --> 00:14:10,382
And begin!

389
00:14:10,983 --> 00:14:12,585
SAM BEGINS TO OPEN HIS LEGS FIERCELY

390
00:14:12,818 --> 00:14:14,320
GROAN

391
00:14:14,386 --> 00:14:15,754
Hey, Sam!

392
00:14:15,821 --> 00:14:17,857
Sam wins!

393
00:14:17,923 --> 00:14:19,758
SAM ATTACKS SUCCESSFULLY

394
00:14:20,226 --> 00:14:21,694
SWITCHING POSITIONS

395
00:14:21,760 --> 00:14:22,661
It's his turn to defend.

396
00:14:22,728 --> 00:14:24,630
I thought Ho-young
would have the advantage.

397
00:14:24,697 --> 00:14:25,931
-Did I lose my muscles?
-Get ready.

398
00:14:25,998 --> 00:14:27,066
And begin.

399
00:14:27,733 --> 00:14:29,335
Wait, it ripped.

400
00:14:29,401 --> 00:14:30,469
And begin.

401
00:14:30,536 --> 00:14:32,204
Wait, it ripped.

402
00:14:32,504 --> 00:14:34,173
HIS PANTS RIPPED

403
00:14:34,240 --> 00:14:35,107
His pants ripped!

404
00:14:35,574 --> 00:14:36,809
GIGGLE

405
00:14:36,876 --> 00:14:37,943
Your pants…

406
00:14:38,010 --> 00:14:38,878
SPOTS THE RIP

407
00:14:39,411 --> 00:14:40,679
JOY

408
00:14:41,180 --> 00:14:43,582
QUICKLY COVERS IT

409
00:14:43,916 --> 00:14:45,384
PRIMITIVE SLAPSTICK COMEDY

410
00:14:45,451 --> 00:14:47,219
I heard something rip.

411
00:14:47,286 --> 00:14:50,756
<i>Ho-young can't go on.</i>
<i>He needs to stitch his pants.</i>

412
00:14:51,156 --> 00:14:52,691
THIS GUY IS CRYING MANY TIMES TODAY

413
00:14:52,758 --> 00:14:55,527
-Sung-jun versus Nam-no.
-The young guns.

414
00:14:55,594 --> 00:14:57,396
-Nam-no is probably stronger.
-Will he win?

415
00:14:57,463 --> 00:14:58,464
Ready, begin.

416
00:14:58,530 --> 00:14:59,999
SPLIT

417
00:15:00,065 --> 00:15:01,066
Ready, begin.

418
00:15:01,133 --> 00:15:02,301
OH, GOSH

419
00:15:02,368 --> 00:15:04,837
KWON SUNG-JUN WINS

420
00:15:04,904 --> 00:15:07,506
-Sam defends first.
-Sam will end up doing splits.

421
00:15:07,573 --> 00:15:08,674
Ready, begin.

422
00:15:10,542 --> 00:15:12,511
THE YOUNGEST CHEF IS ON FIRE

423
00:15:12,578 --> 00:15:14,313
-Short legs must be the reason.
-Sung-jun.

424
00:15:14,380 --> 00:15:16,315
-He's the dark horse.
-You need short limbs.

425
00:15:16,715 --> 00:15:18,918
A STRONG CONTENDER

426
00:15:18,984 --> 00:15:21,086
Next, Jong-won versus Hyun-suk.

427
00:15:21,153 --> 00:15:24,056
These are the two chefs who work out.

428
00:15:24,123 --> 00:15:25,658
Born in the year of Liberation, Hyun-suk.

429
00:15:25,724 --> 00:15:27,426
BORN IN THE YEAR OF LIBERATION?

430
00:15:27,493 --> 00:15:29,028
Born in the year of Liberation, Hyun-suk,

431
00:15:29,094 --> 00:15:30,496
versus the well-off Jong-won.

432
00:15:30,562 --> 00:15:32,831
-The tank boy!
-The tank boy…

433
00:15:32,898 --> 00:15:35,801
-The tank boy versus the tub boy.
-He can't contain his laughter.

434
00:15:35,868 --> 00:15:36,802
"Tank boy."

435
00:15:36,869 --> 00:15:38,037
SAM'S LAUGHTER TRIGGER

436
00:15:38,103 --> 00:15:40,773
The boy who was stricken with poverty.

437
00:15:42,574 --> 00:15:44,410
STRICKEN WITH POVERTY

438
00:15:45,010 --> 00:15:47,646
Black-and-white photo versus color photo.

439
00:15:47,713 --> 00:15:50,482
-Black-and-white versus colors.
-The Color Spoon.

440
00:15:50,549 --> 00:15:52,351
Hyun-suk the famine survivor.

441
00:15:52,418 --> 00:15:53,752
Barley rice versus white rice.

442
00:15:53,819 --> 00:15:55,521
BARLEY RICE VS. WHITE RICE

443
00:15:56,088 --> 00:15:57,489
I'm out of energy from laughing.

444
00:15:57,556 --> 00:15:58,991
Ready, begin.

445
00:16:00,059 --> 00:16:01,927
JONG-WON OPENS HIS LEGS EASILY

446
00:16:01,994 --> 00:16:03,362
Look at him go!

447
00:16:03,963 --> 00:16:06,098
JONG-WON WINS WITH THE POWER OF WHITE RICE

448
00:16:06,165 --> 00:16:07,266
Barley rice loses!

449
00:16:07,333 --> 00:16:09,134
-White rice is stronger.
-White rice it is.

450
00:16:09,201 --> 00:16:10,102
Barley can't win.

451
00:16:10,169 --> 00:16:11,904
I didn't eat barley rice.

452
00:16:11,971 --> 00:16:13,973
-It was barley porridge.
-Porridge?

453
00:16:14,039 --> 00:16:15,107
Barley porridge, rice porridge.

454
00:16:15,174 --> 00:16:17,943
-Jong-won.
-The man who's jealous of him, Sung-jun.

455
00:16:18,010 --> 00:16:20,713
That's right. Will Sung-jun get a chance

456
00:16:20,779 --> 00:16:22,848
-to win against him today?
-This is interesting.

457
00:16:23,282 --> 00:16:24,783
THE MAN WHO WAS ALWAYS JEALOUS OF HIM

458
00:16:24,850 --> 00:16:27,820
<i>Sung-jun finally gets a chance</i>
<i>to win against Jong-won.</i>

459
00:16:27,886 --> 00:16:29,421
This is the only way I can win.

460
00:16:29,488 --> 00:16:32,591
Now, Jong-won versus Sung-jun.

461
00:16:32,658 --> 00:16:33,592
Get ready.

462
00:16:33,659 --> 00:16:34,927
And begin!

463
00:16:35,728 --> 00:16:36,862
Sung-jun attacks!

464
00:16:36,929 --> 00:16:38,297
And begin!

465
00:16:38,364 --> 00:16:40,132
A NECK-AND-NECK BATTLE

466
00:16:40,199 --> 00:16:42,801
But Jong-won stands strong.

467
00:16:42,868 --> 00:16:44,837
That's not enough.
You need to open your legs wider.

468
00:16:45,204 --> 00:16:46,672
INTRIGUED

469
00:16:47,139 --> 00:16:48,374
I WANT TO WIN!

470
00:16:48,440 --> 00:16:49,641
Five.

471
00:16:49,708 --> 00:16:50,876
Four.

472
00:16:50,943 --> 00:16:51,977
Three.

473
00:16:52,044 --> 00:16:52,945
-Two.
-No.

474
00:16:53,012 --> 00:16:54,213
One!

475
00:16:55,781 --> 00:16:58,083
-Did he win?
-He did. That's time.

476
00:16:59,118 --> 00:17:02,688
He managed to keep it open
by a fist's width, so he won.

477
00:17:02,755 --> 00:17:07,626
But if Jong-won manages
to open his legs wider, he wins.

478
00:17:07,693 --> 00:17:10,529
The man who got blinded by jealousy,
Kwon Sung-jun.

479
00:17:10,596 --> 00:17:13,265
Can Jong-won beat him?

480
00:17:13,832 --> 00:17:15,501
Ready, begin.

481
00:17:15,567 --> 00:17:17,970
He tries to open his legs.

482
00:17:18,037 --> 00:17:19,872
-He tries to open his legs.
-He's strong.

483
00:17:19,938 --> 00:17:21,206
I CAN'T LOSE

484
00:17:21,273 --> 00:17:23,075
But he holds out!

485
00:17:23,142 --> 00:17:25,210
He's keeping it open by a fist,
just like Sung-jun.

486
00:17:25,277 --> 00:17:27,079
It's the same width!
It has to open up wider!

487
00:17:27,146 --> 00:17:28,547
It's getting wider!

488
00:17:28,614 --> 00:17:30,382
-It is!
-Five.

489
00:17:30,449 --> 00:17:32,384
-Four. Three.
-Please!

490
00:17:32,451 --> 00:17:33,752
Two.

491
00:17:33,819 --> 00:17:34,987
One.

492
00:17:35,454 --> 00:17:37,356
GAME OVER

493
00:17:37,423 --> 00:17:39,091
-Two of my fists fit in.
-Two fists.

494
00:17:39,158 --> 00:17:40,893
Jong-won wins!

495
00:17:41,627 --> 00:17:43,562
And now,
please get ready for the final round.

496
00:17:43,629 --> 00:17:47,232
<i>The two who had won the Best Couple Award</i>

497
00:17:47,299 --> 00:17:48,634
are now in the final round.

498
00:17:48,700 --> 00:17:50,803
Poong's thighs are huge.

499
00:17:50,869 --> 00:17:52,371
-They look sturdy.
-Yes.

500
00:17:52,971 --> 00:17:55,541
Man, look at his thighs.

501
00:17:55,607 --> 00:17:58,544
Poong defends first,

502
00:17:58,610 --> 00:17:59,745
and Jong-won attacks.

503
00:17:59,812 --> 00:18:00,879
He's sitting too close!

504
00:18:01,447 --> 00:18:04,049
THE BEST COUPLE IS TOO CLOSE

505
00:18:04,116 --> 00:18:07,086
Do you have anything to say
to your opponent?

506
00:18:07,152 --> 00:18:09,021
Well, don't strain yourself.

507
00:18:09,088 --> 00:18:11,156
Don't try too hard, Chef Jong-won.

508
00:18:11,223 --> 00:18:12,691
Let's take it easy, okay?

509
00:18:12,758 --> 00:18:15,761
Jong-won may be smiling,
but he doesn't plan to lose.

510
00:18:16,395 --> 00:18:17,696
This is the final round.

511
00:18:17,763 --> 00:18:20,532
Jong-won versus Poong.
Jong-won is the first to attack.

512
00:18:20,599 --> 00:18:21,600
Get ready.

513
00:18:21,667 --> 00:18:23,035
And begin!

514
00:18:23,102 --> 00:18:24,536
Wait, he's too strong.

515
00:18:24,603 --> 00:18:26,004
And begin!

516
00:18:26,071 --> 00:18:27,873
WILL NOT BUDGE

517
00:18:27,940 --> 00:18:28,907
Is he too strong?

518
00:18:28,974 --> 00:18:30,609
I was already in pain before we began!

519
00:18:30,676 --> 00:18:32,277
-Are you in pain?
-Wait, what?

520
00:18:32,344 --> 00:18:34,113
-I'm sorry.
-He's in pain.

521
00:18:34,179 --> 00:18:36,281
-Goodness, Poong.
-I'm sorry.

522
00:18:36,348 --> 00:18:38,217
-I'm so sorry.
-Poong just hurt him.

523
00:18:38,283 --> 00:18:40,285
GLARE

524
00:18:40,953 --> 00:18:42,654
He's way too strong.

525
00:18:42,721 --> 00:18:44,790
-His power isn't human.
-It's not?

526
00:18:44,857 --> 00:18:46,258
He's built different.

527
00:18:46,325 --> 00:18:48,327
-It hurts a lot.
-What do I do now?

528
00:18:48,393 --> 00:18:49,561
It's your turn to attack.

529
00:18:49,628 --> 00:18:51,296
-Jong-won's legs will split.
-I'm sorry.

530
00:18:51,563 --> 00:18:53,298
GETS READY TO FIGHT AGAIN

531
00:18:53,866 --> 00:18:55,100
Get ready.

532
00:18:55,167 --> 00:18:56,135
Poong's attack.

533
00:18:56,201 --> 00:18:57,369
And begin.

534
00:18:58,237 --> 00:18:59,671
LAUGHING

535
00:18:59,738 --> 00:19:00,572
Begin.

536
00:19:02,774 --> 00:19:05,144
Goodness, he's rather strong.

537
00:19:05,210 --> 00:19:06,979
-Why don't you open up a little?
-Shall I?

538
00:19:07,913 --> 00:19:10,249
HELPLESS

539
00:19:10,315 --> 00:19:12,050
Poong wins.

540
00:19:12,117 --> 00:19:14,386
-This is his game.
-You flung like a revolving door.

541
00:19:14,453 --> 00:19:16,255
It's his game.

542
00:19:16,321 --> 00:19:17,723
I would've won against all of you

543
00:19:17,789 --> 00:19:20,526
if only I had white rice in my childhood.

544
00:19:21,093 --> 00:19:23,695
EAT WELL AS YOU GROW, CHILDREN
FROM THE PRODUCTION CREW

545
00:19:23,762 --> 00:19:26,632
I could've beaten everyone.

546
00:19:26,698 --> 00:19:28,934
That was all
for <i>Chef & My Fridge</i> Cup Thigh Wrestling.

547
00:19:29,001 --> 00:19:30,903
The winner is Webtoon Artist Kim Poong!

548
00:19:30,969 --> 00:19:32,538
KIM POONG, THE CHAMPION

549
00:19:32,604 --> 00:19:36,175
We're about to look at his fridge today,
and the competition was for him too.

550
00:19:36,241 --> 00:19:38,777
So now, it's time
to go through Poong's fridge

551
00:19:38,844 --> 00:19:41,680
before we begin the cook-offs
for the Lunar New Year Episode.

552
00:19:41,747 --> 00:19:44,449
<i>This is the season</i>
<i>where the entire family gathers,</i>

553
00:19:44,516 --> 00:19:48,420
so I'm not sure if it's proper
to go through his fridge today.

554
00:19:48,487 --> 00:19:51,423
-But he's been the hottest issue lately…
-He has been.

555
00:19:51,490 --> 00:19:54,359
…so a lot of people may wonder
what he keeps in the fridge.

556
00:19:54,426 --> 00:19:57,229
Look at the things stuck on the doors.

557
00:19:57,296 --> 00:19:59,431
You see traces of parenting.

558
00:19:59,498 --> 00:20:01,567
-Look.
-"Well done" stamps.

559
00:20:01,633 --> 00:20:04,036
-Do you give your son "well done" stamps?
-Yes.

560
00:20:04,102 --> 00:20:05,003
How old is he?

561
00:20:05,070 --> 00:20:06,738
-He just turned five.
-Five.

562
00:20:06,805 --> 00:20:08,407
Do you do it or does your wife do it?

563
00:20:08,473 --> 00:20:09,741
He does it himself.

564
00:20:09,808 --> 00:20:12,544
Your son stamps it himself?

565
00:20:12,611 --> 00:20:14,479
He knows where the stamp is,

566
00:20:14,546 --> 00:20:15,681
so he keeps doing it.

567
00:20:15,914 --> 00:20:16,915
HOW ADORABLE

568
00:20:16,982 --> 00:20:18,684
He'd say, "I didn't cry today,"

569
00:20:18,750 --> 00:20:20,419
then stamps one on the sheet.

570
00:20:20,485 --> 00:20:22,454
-It's his son's personal sheet.
-It is.

571
00:20:22,521 --> 00:20:23,722
That's right.

572
00:20:24,323 --> 00:20:28,227
We once looked through his fridge
11 years ago.

573
00:20:28,794 --> 00:20:31,897
Let us present
Webtoon Artist Kim Poong's fridge!

574
00:20:31,964 --> 00:20:33,732
FULL OF INGREDIENTS

575
00:20:33,799 --> 00:20:35,000
Hey, not bad.

576
00:20:35,067 --> 00:20:38,904
FULL OF GERMS TOO

577
00:20:39,404 --> 00:20:42,774
A FULL FRIDGE FULL OF GERMS

578
00:20:42,841 --> 00:20:45,010
-Back then, it was a literal mess.
-It was.

579
00:20:45,077 --> 00:20:47,646
I wonder how far he has come.

580
00:20:47,713 --> 00:20:49,615
Are you looking forward to this,
Chef Jong-won?

581
00:20:49,681 --> 00:20:51,750
I'm probably the most excited.

582
00:20:51,817 --> 00:20:53,151
MORE EXCITED THAN ANYONE

583
00:20:53,218 --> 00:20:54,753
He has a strong sense of curiosity,

584
00:20:54,820 --> 00:20:57,522
-so he may have many peculiar items.
-Something peculiar.

585
00:20:57,589 --> 00:21:00,225
-I'm excited to find out.
-He's a man of passion.

586
00:21:00,292 --> 00:21:03,762
-We present Poong's fridge!
-Fridge!

587
00:21:04,563 --> 00:21:06,865
EVERYONE LOOKS AMAZED

588
00:21:06,932 --> 00:21:08,367
-Fridge!
-Fridge!

589
00:21:08,433 --> 00:21:10,135
-He has lots of stuff.
-That's a lot.

590
00:21:10,802 --> 00:21:13,272
-Look at the condiments.
-And lots of sauces.

591
00:21:13,338 --> 00:21:15,641
Everything looks neatly organized.

592
00:21:15,707 --> 00:21:19,077
Look at the labels.
He labeled these just like Jong-won.

593
00:21:19,144 --> 00:21:22,814
My gosh. You became a different man
after you got married.

594
00:21:22,881 --> 00:21:24,449
Those are pure lies.

595
00:21:24,516 --> 00:21:26,151
-What is?
-The labels

596
00:21:26,218 --> 00:21:27,886
-and the containers.
-Why?

597
00:21:27,953 --> 00:21:29,521
I told my wife I had to take the fridge,

598
00:21:29,588 --> 00:21:31,757
and she quickly began

599
00:21:31,823 --> 00:21:33,959
to label everything inside.

600
00:21:34,026 --> 00:21:37,496
I'm mostly in charge
of what's in the fridge,

601
00:21:37,562 --> 00:21:39,264
so everything was messy before.

602
00:21:39,331 --> 00:21:42,200
-Your wife must've been worried.
-I guess so.

603
00:21:42,267 --> 00:21:46,505
Anyway, do you use the fridge
the most often?

604
00:21:46,571 --> 00:21:48,907
I hold ownership of over 80%
of what's inside.

605
00:21:48,974 --> 00:21:50,342
-Is that so?
-Yes.

606
00:21:50,409 --> 00:21:52,144
He has a lot of stuff. Look at the sauces.

607
00:21:52,210 --> 00:21:53,779
First, the top shelf.

608
00:21:53,845 --> 00:21:55,847
What's in here?

609
00:21:55,914 --> 00:21:57,416
-What's that?
-I know.

610
00:21:57,482 --> 00:21:59,818
That's puréed carrot.

611
00:21:59,885 --> 00:22:01,586
-Puréed carrot?
-Yes.

612
00:22:01,653 --> 00:22:02,988
Is that for your son?

613
00:22:03,055 --> 00:22:05,490
After I shoot an episode,

614
00:22:05,557 --> 00:22:08,260
I always go home and try to recreate
the most memorable dish.

615
00:22:08,327 --> 00:22:09,695
-Really?
-Last time,

616
00:22:09,761 --> 00:22:13,432
Chef Hyun-suk made puréed carrots,

617
00:22:13,498 --> 00:22:15,334
<i>-and it was delicious.</i>
<i>-No wonder.</i>

618
00:22:15,400 --> 00:22:17,636
That was why he suddenly got
much better at cooking.

619
00:22:18,103 --> 00:22:19,371
THE RECIPE BLACK HOLE

620
00:22:19,438 --> 00:22:21,907
He had been going home
and reviewing the dishes.

621
00:22:21,973 --> 00:22:24,142
-He's putting in work.
-I guess so.

622
00:22:24,209 --> 00:22:26,278
-All these are condiments.
-Tell me about it.

623
00:22:26,345 --> 00:22:29,114
We're pretty much in China down here.

624
00:22:29,181 --> 00:22:30,215
THE SOURCE OF HIS MAGIC

625
00:22:30,282 --> 00:22:31,983
Look at these Chinese sauces.

626
00:22:32,050 --> 00:22:34,319
Starting with <i>doubanjiang</i> and more.

627
00:22:34,686 --> 00:22:36,588
HE HAS EVERY TYPE OF SAUCE
YOU CAN IMAGINE

628
00:22:36,655 --> 00:22:39,758
It looks like a chef's fridge.

629
00:22:39,825 --> 00:22:41,693
What's this?

630
00:22:41,760 --> 00:22:42,894
Sichuan pepper.

631
00:22:42,961 --> 00:22:44,663
-Sichuan pepper?
-He has Sichuan pepper?

632
00:22:44,730 --> 00:22:46,531
It's Sichuan pepper, the strong kind.

633
00:22:46,598 --> 00:22:48,367
MADE WITH DRIED CHOPI,
ADDS A NUMBING SENSATION

634
00:22:48,433 --> 00:22:49,668
Do you use this?

635
00:22:49,735 --> 00:22:52,571
-Yes, to make hot pot or a stir-fry.
-For Sichuan dishes.

636
00:22:52,637 --> 00:22:54,039
You make hot pot at home?

637
00:22:54,106 --> 00:22:55,006
What's this?

638
00:22:55,073 --> 00:22:57,042
That's an Indonesian sauce called sambal,

639
00:22:57,109 --> 00:22:58,877
like gochujang of Indonesia.

640
00:22:58,944 --> 00:23:00,479
It mixes nicely with rice.

641
00:23:00,545 --> 00:23:02,180
He keeps those at home?

642
00:23:02,247 --> 00:23:05,550
What's this powder?

643
00:23:05,617 --> 00:23:08,653
That's pizza sauce powder.

644
00:23:08,720 --> 00:23:09,855
Pizza sauce powder?

645
00:23:09,921 --> 00:23:11,857
I can whip it up
and plaster it on a dough in a rush.

646
00:23:11,923 --> 00:23:13,091
Is this a thing?

647
00:23:13,158 --> 00:23:14,960
-Apparently so.
-He has lots of fascinating stuff.

648
00:23:15,026 --> 00:23:18,630
Honestly, I began to buy more sauces
after the show started again.

649
00:23:19,264 --> 00:23:22,200
I had to conduct a deeper study
for food ingredients.

650
00:23:22,267 --> 00:23:25,504
-He's like a professional cook.
-Are these veggies?

651
00:23:25,570 --> 00:23:27,539
-He has greens here.
-Apple mint?

652
00:23:27,606 --> 00:23:30,475
Most of the veggies and greens
are for me and my son.

653
00:23:30,542 --> 00:23:32,511
My wife mostly eats meat,

654
00:23:32,577 --> 00:23:34,379
while my son and I love veggies.

655
00:23:34,446 --> 00:23:36,081
Is your son not a picky eater?

656
00:23:36,148 --> 00:23:37,249
Not at all.

657
00:23:37,315 --> 00:23:38,683
-Can he eat anything?
-Even <i>yukhoe.</i>

658
00:23:38,750 --> 00:23:39,718
-What?
-Raw beef?

659
00:23:39,785 --> 00:23:40,986
You said he was five.

660
00:23:41,052 --> 00:23:42,354
He eats <i>gwamegi</i> too.

661
00:23:42,421 --> 00:23:44,322
-Half-dried Pacific saury?
-Yes.

662
00:23:44,389 --> 00:23:47,125
-He can eat everything.
-He must have a unique appetite.

663
00:23:47,192 --> 00:23:50,462
There are lots of cheese and butter
on the second shelf.

664
00:23:50,529 --> 00:23:53,665
He has more cheese
than most Western chefs would.

665
00:23:53,732 --> 00:23:54,966
-It's a variety.
-That's a lot.

666
00:23:55,033 --> 00:23:56,868
I like pasta,

667
00:23:56,935 --> 00:23:58,570
-and I make it for my son too.
-For your son.

668
00:23:58,637 --> 00:24:00,472
You cook a lot at home.

669
00:24:00,539 --> 00:24:03,074
And there are other condiments
on this side.

670
00:24:03,141 --> 00:24:04,643
What's this?

671
00:24:04,709 --> 00:24:06,111
That one?

672
00:24:06,178 --> 00:24:07,379
It's my personal creation.

673
00:24:07,446 --> 00:24:09,080
-Your personal creation?
-Yes, it is.

674
00:24:09,147 --> 00:24:10,749
It's like my personal mayonnaise.

675
00:24:10,816 --> 00:24:12,083
-He even made that?
-I made it

676
00:24:12,150 --> 00:24:14,619
by using the usual mayonnaise recipe.

677
00:24:14,686 --> 00:24:16,254
So can the chefs guess

678
00:24:16,321 --> 00:24:18,356
what's inside?

679
00:24:18,423 --> 00:24:20,992
-Our pride is at stake.
-All right.

680
00:24:21,059 --> 00:24:22,227
-Our pride.
-Give them some.

681
00:24:22,294 --> 00:24:24,062
Let me give some to you.

682
00:24:24,129 --> 00:24:26,465
Poong made this sauce.

683
00:24:27,165 --> 00:24:29,167
First, I mixed

684
00:24:29,234 --> 00:24:31,837
an egg yolk with olive oil
and avocado oil.

685
00:24:31,903 --> 00:24:34,606
-This is…
-Dill.

686
00:24:35,273 --> 00:24:36,575
-Correct.
-Sam got dill correct.

687
00:24:36,641 --> 00:24:37,742
I can taste fruit.

688
00:24:37,809 --> 00:24:39,411
-Anyone else?
-Apples? Are these apples?

689
00:24:39,478 --> 00:24:41,079
-Apples? Eliminated.
-Eliminated.

690
00:24:41,146 --> 00:24:42,514
A bit of lemon juice.

691
00:24:42,581 --> 00:24:43,815
-And…
-Correct.

692
00:24:43,882 --> 00:24:45,350
-There's a chew to it.
-Anything else?

693
00:24:45,417 --> 00:24:46,818
-Three more.
-Three?

694
00:24:46,885 --> 00:24:48,286
-Three more?
-There's more?

695
00:24:48,353 --> 00:24:49,688
Three important ingredients.

696
00:24:49,754 --> 00:24:50,755
Onion.

697
00:24:50,822 --> 00:24:51,957
-Yes?
-Onion, but…

698
00:24:52,023 --> 00:24:53,558
-Onion juice.
-Onion powder.

699
00:24:53,625 --> 00:24:55,460
-Correct.
-Onion powder.

700
00:24:55,527 --> 00:24:57,662
-It was onion powder.
-I added onion powder.

701
00:24:57,729 --> 00:24:58,930
Two more to go.

702
00:24:58,997 --> 00:25:00,332
One of them is unfamiliar,

703
00:25:00,398 --> 00:25:03,368
and the other one is something
Poong would definitely throw in.

704
00:25:03,435 --> 00:25:04,336
MSG?

705
00:25:04,402 --> 00:25:06,271
MSG? Correct.

706
00:25:06,338 --> 00:25:09,207
Yes, I added a tad bit of MSG.

707
00:25:09,274 --> 00:25:10,842
-I thought so.
-There's a chew to it.

708
00:25:11,776 --> 00:25:13,512
What is this?

709
00:25:13,578 --> 00:25:15,347
I think we got everything.

710
00:25:15,413 --> 00:25:17,082
The last ingredient is

711
00:25:17,682 --> 00:25:18,783
-nutmeg?
-Yes.

712
00:25:18,850 --> 00:25:20,285
-Nutmeg.
-Nutmeg.

713
00:25:20,352 --> 00:25:22,988
-I can't taste it at all.
-He used something called nutmeg.

714
00:25:23,054 --> 00:25:27,526
I got curious, wondering why people
loved using that ingredient.

715
00:25:27,592 --> 00:25:29,828
So I've been putting it in everything.

716
00:25:29,895 --> 00:25:30,729
His personal sauce.

717
00:25:30,795 --> 00:25:33,331
Let's move on to the freezer.

718
00:25:33,398 --> 00:25:35,967
He keeps both beef and pork.

719
00:25:36,034 --> 00:25:38,036
What's down here?

720
00:25:38,103 --> 00:25:39,771
-Seafood.
-Seafood.

721
00:25:39,838 --> 00:25:41,439
-That's a lot.
-He has mackerel

722
00:25:41,506 --> 00:25:42,674
-and tilefish.
-Tilefish.

723
00:25:42,741 --> 00:25:45,277
Scallops and abalones.

724
00:25:45,343 --> 00:25:47,846
-He has lots of seafood too.
-There's a lot to work with.

725
00:25:47,913 --> 00:25:49,681
And the room temperature ingredients.

726
00:25:50,315 --> 00:25:51,650
-Of course, <i>ramyeon.</i>
<i>-Ramyeon.</i>

727
00:25:51,716 --> 00:25:55,120
-Yes.
-Chef Jong-won didn't have any of these.

728
00:25:55,186 --> 00:25:57,722
-Is this pasta?
-Yes.

729
00:25:57,789 --> 00:26:01,726
You can use angel hair to make

730
00:26:01,793 --> 00:26:03,695
<i>naengmyeon</i> or <i>bibim-myeon.</i>

731
00:26:03,762 --> 00:26:06,264
Cook the pasta, wash with cold water,

732
00:26:06,331 --> 00:26:10,268
and mix <i>chogochujang</i>
and tomato pasta sauce.

733
00:26:10,335 --> 00:26:12,871
It's delicious with a drip of sesame oil.

734
00:26:12,938 --> 00:26:14,739
-It's amazing.
-Really?

735
00:26:14,806 --> 00:26:16,107
-It's amazing.
-He was so focused

736
00:26:16,174 --> 00:26:18,710
as Poong continued to talk.

737
00:26:19,210 --> 00:26:20,178
KEEPS NODDING

738
00:26:20,245 --> 00:26:21,112
He listened like this.

739
00:26:21,580 --> 00:26:23,348
HIS CULINARY WORLD IS SO INTERESTING

740
00:26:23,415 --> 00:26:25,917
That was all for Poong's fridge!

741
00:26:25,984 --> 00:26:28,219
DONE CHECKING OUT POONG'S FRIDGE

742
00:26:28,286 --> 00:26:30,422
Let's find out what he wants to eat.

743
00:26:30,488 --> 00:26:33,592
He's an extraordinary man,
so it's a nerve-racking moment.

744
00:26:33,658 --> 00:26:36,328
What kind of dishes is he looking for?

745
00:26:36,394 --> 00:26:38,897
Show us his orders!

746
00:26:38,964 --> 00:26:40,398
What is it? The first…

747
00:26:40,465 --> 00:26:42,434
-What?
-What?

748
00:26:42,500 --> 00:26:43,868
What is it? The first…

749
00:26:43,935 --> 00:26:45,437
-What?
-What?

750
00:26:45,503 --> 00:26:47,205
What? I haven't volunteered yet.

751
00:26:47,272 --> 00:26:48,573
Has it been decided?

752
00:26:48,640 --> 00:26:50,442
Culinary Darkness Wars: Genre Hell.

753
00:26:50,508 --> 00:26:52,043
Sam Kim versus Park Eun-yeong.

754
00:26:52,110 --> 00:26:54,079
Culinary Darkness Wars:
Kim Poong Paradise.

755
00:26:54,145 --> 00:26:55,847
Choi Hyun-suk versus Son Jong-won.

756
00:26:55,914 --> 00:26:57,415
-You've decided the contenders?
-Yes.

757
00:26:57,482 --> 00:27:01,586
I've already decided
on the orders and contenders.

758
00:27:01,653 --> 00:27:03,488
-Is he allowed to do this?
-He just did this?

759
00:27:03,555 --> 00:27:05,023
You won't even let them choose.

760
00:27:05,090 --> 00:27:07,726
They don't get to choose.
They have to do this.

761
00:27:07,792 --> 00:27:08,893
Let's hear why, though.

762
00:27:08,960 --> 00:27:11,463
First, Culinary Darkness Wars: Genre Hell.

763
00:27:11,529 --> 00:27:15,634
In the end, most of the chefs
end up resorting to their own practices,

764
00:27:15,700 --> 00:27:16,935
even on the show.

765
00:27:17,002 --> 00:27:18,837
They remain within their food genre.

766
00:27:18,903 --> 00:27:22,540
This time, I want them
to exchange each other's cuisines.

767
00:27:22,607 --> 00:27:24,876
I especially want that from Eun-yeong.

768
00:27:24,943 --> 00:27:27,445
-You have to make Western food?
-She only makes Chinese food.

769
00:27:27,512 --> 00:27:29,648
-The Chinese food lover.
-So I wanted to put her

770
00:27:29,714 --> 00:27:32,550
-up against Chef Sam.
-I see.

771
00:27:32,617 --> 00:27:35,553
Chef Eun-yeong will make Western food,
and Chef Sam, Chinese.

772
00:27:35,620 --> 00:27:36,554
It's hard to imagine.

773
00:27:36,621 --> 00:27:40,058
I really want to see
Chef Sam make Chinese food.

774
00:27:40,125 --> 00:27:42,093
Next, Culinary Darkness Wars:
Kim Poong Paradise.

775
00:27:42,160 --> 00:27:44,529
I have made numerous dishes on this show.

776
00:27:45,196 --> 00:27:49,100
THE DISHES THAT LEFT
MANY IN TERROR AND SHOCK

777
00:27:49,167 --> 00:27:50,101
I want the chefs

778
00:27:50,168 --> 00:27:53,038
-to reinterpret those…
-No way.

779
00:27:53,104 --> 00:27:55,507
…with their personal intentions.

780
00:27:56,474 --> 00:27:58,143
-That's tough.
-That's a hard one.

781
00:27:58,209 --> 00:28:00,712
The most important aspect
is their intention behind the dishes.

782
00:28:01,846 --> 00:28:02,981
Poong Sung-jae.

783
00:28:03,048 --> 00:28:05,583
Their intention
must be reflected in the dish.

784
00:28:05,650 --> 00:28:07,018
That's hard.

785
00:28:07,085 --> 00:28:10,021
Do you reflect your intentions
into your dishes?

786
00:28:10,088 --> 00:28:11,956
-I always do.
-You do?

787
00:28:12,023 --> 00:28:13,692
It just never comes out right.

788
00:28:13,758 --> 00:28:15,727
You try to reflect it,
but it doesn't go well?

789
00:28:15,794 --> 00:28:17,996
Tank Boy seems upset.

790
00:28:18,196 --> 00:28:20,598
TANK BOY SEEMS QUITE UPSET

791
00:28:20,665 --> 00:28:22,367
I would like to disobey the order.

792
00:28:23,134 --> 00:28:26,438
It's our first time
getting drafted and forced to make

793
00:28:26,504 --> 00:28:28,173
-something in particular.
-"Drafted"?

794
00:28:28,239 --> 00:28:31,242
"Draft" is yet more military jargon.

795
00:28:31,309 --> 00:28:32,844
He developed his language there.

796
00:28:32,911 --> 00:28:34,979
-That's his age.
-He lived through it all.

797
00:28:35,046 --> 00:28:36,614
He lived through difficult years.

798
00:28:36,681 --> 00:28:38,016
Let me know if it's inconvenient.

799
00:28:38,083 --> 00:28:39,918
From time to time,

800
00:28:39,984 --> 00:28:41,619
he seems to have a wonderful idea,

801
00:28:41,686 --> 00:28:44,656
but he lacks the cooking skills
to make it come true.

802
00:28:44,723 --> 00:28:48,126
At times, I find myself wondering
if it would be interesting to add wings

803
00:28:48,193 --> 00:28:50,161
to the idea he came up with.

804
00:28:50,228 --> 00:28:53,498
-Please show your creativity.
-It won't be easy.

805
00:28:53,565 --> 00:28:56,634
Now, the first round,
Culinary Darkness Wars: Genre Hell.

806
00:28:56,701 --> 00:28:59,604
Let's begin the cook-off
between Sam and Eun-yeong!

807
00:28:59,671 --> 00:29:01,406
THE CUISINE SWITCH ROUND BEGINS

808
00:29:01,906 --> 00:29:06,277
<i>We're about to begin the first round</i>
<i>with Poong's ingredients.</i>

809
00:29:06,344 --> 00:29:08,847
The Chinese cuisine lover, Chef Eun-yeong,

810
00:29:08,913 --> 00:29:12,517
versus the pasta lover, Chef Sam.

811
00:29:12,584 --> 00:29:14,552
You cannot go to your usual practice.

812
00:29:14,619 --> 00:29:16,855
Chef Sam must cook Chinese food,

813
00:29:16,921 --> 00:29:20,125
while Chef Eun-yeong makes Italian food.

814
00:29:20,191 --> 00:29:22,293
Does this mean we'll see Sam

815
00:29:22,360 --> 00:29:25,630
tossing the wok
and setting things on fire?

816
00:29:25,697 --> 00:29:28,700
And Chef Eun-yeong will be
doing <i>mantecare</i> next to him.

817
00:29:28,767 --> 00:29:29,934
I want to see that.

818
00:29:30,001 --> 00:29:32,003
-Yes.
-Will you use a Chinese knife, Sam?

819
00:29:32,070 --> 00:29:33,138
-A Chinese knife.
-He has it.

820
00:29:33,204 --> 00:29:35,173
-I borrowed it.
-You'll use it?

821
00:29:35,240 --> 00:29:36,107
CHOPPING

822
00:29:36,174 --> 00:29:37,942
That's mine.

823
00:29:38,009 --> 00:29:39,844
-I prepared Western kitchen knives.
-Western knives.

824
00:29:39,911 --> 00:29:42,380
-It doesn't suit her.
-It really doesn't suit you.

825
00:29:42,447 --> 00:29:44,549
Will you use butter and olive oil today?

826
00:29:44,616 --> 00:29:46,818
I won't use any Chinese ingredients today.

827
00:29:46,885 --> 00:29:48,853
Everything will be Italian.

828
00:29:48,920 --> 00:29:50,421
I'm pleased.

829
00:29:50,488 --> 00:29:52,524
But I see cooking wine and <i>doenjang.</i>

830
00:29:52,590 --> 00:29:53,825
Just let me use those.

831
00:29:54,392 --> 00:29:57,328
And Sam, you'll be fighting against her

832
00:29:57,395 --> 00:29:59,798
as Kim Hui-tae, not Sam Kim.

833
00:29:59,864 --> 00:30:00,965
Hui-tae!

834
00:30:01,032 --> 00:30:03,802
Use lots of MSG today!

835
00:30:03,868 --> 00:30:05,937
Chicken stock, oyster sauce,

836
00:30:06,004 --> 00:30:07,906
<i>doubanjiang</i>, Sichuan pepper.
He's got everything.

837
00:30:07,972 --> 00:30:09,541
I grabbed everything.

838
00:30:09,607 --> 00:30:10,809
He came ready.

839
00:30:10,875 --> 00:30:13,578
-She's jealous.
-And even Poong's personal sauce.

840
00:30:13,645 --> 00:30:15,580
You'd be on a roll with those.

841
00:30:15,647 --> 00:30:16,781
I'd destroy everyone.

842
00:30:16,848 --> 00:30:18,750
YEAH, YOU WOULD

843
00:30:18,817 --> 00:30:20,218
Destroy everyone?

844
00:30:20,285 --> 00:30:22,954
Over my time in <i>Chef & My Fridge,</i>

845
00:30:23,021 --> 00:30:26,291
I was the most excited
to see Poong's fridge.

846
00:30:26,357 --> 00:30:27,826
Really?

847
00:30:27,892 --> 00:30:29,861
I always imagined making oil

848
00:30:29,928 --> 00:30:31,996
with some Sichuan pepper,

849
00:30:32,063 --> 00:30:36,234
-and I finally saw it in someone's fridge.
-But she can't use it.

850
00:30:36,301 --> 00:30:37,869
-You can't use it.
-A pipe dream.

851
00:30:37,936 --> 00:30:38,970
It's a pipe dream.

852
00:30:39,037 --> 00:30:43,274
Chef Eun-yeong, did you have
an English name you went by in Hong Kong?

853
00:30:43,341 --> 00:30:45,109
I was called Amy in Hong Kong.

854
00:30:45,176 --> 00:30:46,244
-Amy?
-Amy?

855
00:30:46,311 --> 00:30:47,745
-Amy Park?
-Amy Park?

856
00:30:47,812 --> 00:30:50,748
There's something else
to look forward to in this round.

857
00:30:50,815 --> 00:30:54,052
Chef Hui-tae and Chef Amy

858
00:30:54,118 --> 00:30:55,887
have never fought each other before.

859
00:30:55,954 --> 00:30:56,955
It's their first round?

860
00:30:57,021 --> 00:30:58,389
This is their first round ever.

861
00:30:58,456 --> 00:30:59,791
I knew this was unfamiliar.

862
00:30:59,858 --> 00:31:00,959
Why don't we do this?

863
00:31:01,025 --> 00:31:04,329
Tell each other tips
on how to make Chinese food

864
00:31:04,395 --> 00:31:06,531
-and Italian food.
-To each other.

865
00:31:06,598 --> 00:31:08,333
-It's the holiday, so let's be nice.
-That's great.

866
00:31:08,399 --> 00:31:10,068
-Don't be too competitive.
-How nice.

867
00:31:10,134 --> 00:31:12,103
In order to win with Chinese food,

868
00:31:12,170 --> 00:31:13,671
you must deep-fry everything,

869
00:31:13,738 --> 00:31:15,039
and make it salty, sweet, and sour.

870
00:31:15,106 --> 00:31:17,208
-That's what you need to do.
-Salty, sweet, and sour.

871
00:31:17,275 --> 00:31:18,877
SSS.

872
00:31:18,943 --> 00:31:20,445
Yes, she's right.

873
00:31:20,511 --> 00:31:22,347
When it comes to Italian food,

874
00:31:22,413 --> 00:31:25,516
the original flavor of the ingredients
must be strong.

875
00:31:25,583 --> 00:31:27,151
So you shouldn't use cooking wine.

876
00:31:27,218 --> 00:31:29,187
-I shouldn't?
-You shouldn't.

877
00:31:29,254 --> 00:31:31,456
-You can't.
-There are things you can't use.

878
00:31:31,522 --> 00:31:33,191
And no <i>doenjang.</i>

879
00:31:33,258 --> 00:31:35,226
-The flavor of the ingredients.
-That's tough.

880
00:31:35,293 --> 00:31:37,161
WHO'LL SURVIVE THIS FOOD GENRE HELL?

881
00:31:38,096 --> 00:31:40,365
CHEF AMY PARK'S INGREDIENTS:
TOMATO SAUCE, OLIVE OIL, BALSAMIC,

882
00:31:40,431 --> 00:31:42,166
PARMESAN, BLACK OLIVE, CAPER,
JALAPEÑO, AND MORE

883
00:31:42,233 --> 00:31:44,802
What are you making, Chef Amy Park?

884
00:31:44,869 --> 00:31:46,738
Here's the name of my dish.

885
00:31:46,938 --> 00:31:48,806
EXPECTATIONS ARE HIGH

886
00:31:48,873 --> 00:31:51,376
Western Food Queen? Got-Ragu Be Me.

887
00:31:52,744 --> 00:31:53,578
Hmm?

888
00:31:53,645 --> 00:31:55,580
We got too used to intense performances.

889
00:31:55,647 --> 00:31:56,681
That was too plain.

890
00:31:56,748 --> 00:31:58,816
-I was excited for this.
-That was too ordinary.

891
00:31:58,883 --> 00:32:00,251
I thought she'd do another dance.

892
00:32:00,318 --> 00:32:01,185
She's a naturalist now.

893
00:32:01,252 --> 00:32:04,822
I have to make something
that is outside of my practice,

894
00:32:04,889 --> 00:32:06,758
so I'm a bit nervous right now.

895
00:32:06,824 --> 00:32:09,794
-You're nervous. I understand.
-All right.

896
00:32:09,861 --> 00:32:11,796
I'm going to make ragu pasta.

897
00:32:11,863 --> 00:32:13,064
-Ragu?
-Ragu pasta?

898
00:32:13,131 --> 00:32:17,368
I believe the sauce is made
by stir-frying ground meat.

899
00:32:17,435 --> 00:32:20,038
I'll add my own little kick

900
00:32:20,104 --> 00:32:23,641
and present the ragu pasta
with a dash of my aroma.

901
00:32:23,708 --> 00:32:26,110
Also, Italy is famous for sole,

902
00:32:26,177 --> 00:32:27,512
so I'll make grilled sole

903
00:32:27,578 --> 00:32:31,582
and top it with sauce
by mixing ingredients I've noticed

904
00:32:31,649 --> 00:32:33,251
Western chefs have been using.

905
00:32:33,318 --> 00:32:35,353
-She mixed it in her head.
-Will you make the pasta?

906
00:32:35,420 --> 00:32:37,322
-I will.
-You'll make fresh pasta?

907
00:32:37,388 --> 00:32:38,523
But I have pasta.

908
00:32:39,958 --> 00:32:41,859
CHEF KIM HUI-TAE'S INGREDIENTS:
OYSTER SAUCE, DOUBANJIANG

909
00:32:41,926 --> 00:32:44,128
SICHUAN PEPPER, SQUID, ABALONE,
SCALLOP, SNOW CRAB MEAT, AND MORE

910
00:32:44,195 --> 00:32:46,864
Chef Kim Hui-tae,
what are you making to fight Chef Amy?

911
00:32:46,931 --> 00:32:48,666
I named my dish

912
00:32:48,733 --> 00:32:50,568
Darkness Restaurant.

913
00:32:50,635 --> 00:32:51,970
-Darkness Restaurant.
-Darkness Restaurant.

914
00:32:52,036 --> 00:32:54,138
-Not a Chinese restaurant.
-I like the name.

915
00:32:54,205 --> 00:32:56,040
-Darkness Restaurant.
-It already sounds good.

916
00:32:56,107 --> 00:32:58,409
I'm going to make chili shrimp

917
00:32:58,476 --> 00:33:01,245
-and use shrimps with other seafood…
-Chili shrimp?

918
00:33:01,312 --> 00:33:04,182
-…to make scorched rice soup.
-Sounds good.

919
00:33:04,248 --> 00:33:07,285
I intend to make something
for the entire family to enjoy,

920
00:33:07,352 --> 00:33:09,053
that kind of Chinese food.

921
00:33:09,120 --> 00:33:10,655
-It won't be easy.
-All right.

922
00:33:10,722 --> 00:33:15,159
And now, let us begin the round,
"Culinary Darkness Wars: Genre Hell."

923
00:33:15,226 --> 00:33:19,964
He's here to give a lesson to Amy Park,
who fearlessly dares to defy him.

924
00:33:20,031 --> 00:33:21,733
Chef Kim Hui-tae.

925
00:33:21,799 --> 00:33:25,403
But she responds by saying
she'll put Hui-tae in a pit of fire.

926
00:33:25,470 --> 00:33:27,805
Amy Park is ready to go.

927
00:33:27,872 --> 00:33:30,742
Which one of them will survive
this genre hell?

928
00:33:30,808 --> 00:33:33,945
Let the 15-minute cook-off begin!

929
00:33:36,914 --> 00:33:38,116
Begin!

930
00:33:38,182 --> 00:33:39,584
GET READY TO LEAVE INFERNO

931
00:33:40,051 --> 00:33:42,186
HUI-TAE WITH A CHINESE KNIFE

932
00:33:42,253 --> 00:33:43,855
The Chinese knife.

933
00:33:43,921 --> 00:33:45,890
-He's using a Chinese knife.
-Something's odd.

934
00:33:45,957 --> 00:33:48,326
-Something's…
-Something doesn't seem right.

935
00:33:48,393 --> 00:33:50,228
-It's awkward.
-He can't cut as well.

936
00:33:50,695 --> 00:33:52,130
CLUMSILY MAKING CHILI OIL

937
00:33:52,196 --> 00:33:53,564
Those aren't even.

938
00:33:53,631 --> 00:33:54,665
A BOWL FULL OF OIL

939
00:33:54,732 --> 00:33:55,600
Isn't that too much?

940
00:33:55,666 --> 00:33:57,702
He poured too much oil. Is that okay?

941
00:33:57,769 --> 00:34:00,438
I've never seen Chef Sam make chili oil.

942
00:34:00,505 --> 00:34:02,240
That was too much oil.

943
00:34:02,306 --> 00:34:05,610
Chef Amy preps the vegetables.

944
00:34:06,544 --> 00:34:07,412
Dang it.

945
00:34:08,479 --> 00:34:09,747
Why is this knife so weak?

946
00:34:10,481 --> 00:34:11,816
Her cuts look weird.

947
00:34:11,883 --> 00:34:13,418
-Her cuts look odd.
-Her cuts.

948
00:34:13,484 --> 00:34:14,619
It's the knife.

949
00:34:15,186 --> 00:34:17,488
SHE GOES BACK AND TRIES AGAIN!

950
00:34:17,955 --> 00:34:20,191
IT'S BECOMING A MUSH

951
00:34:20,258 --> 00:34:22,693
-She's using Western kitchen knives!
-She's acting weird too.

952
00:34:23,094 --> 00:34:24,362
THEY'RE BOTH A MESS

953
00:34:24,429 --> 00:34:26,497
They're cutting just like I would.

954
00:34:26,564 --> 00:34:29,200
How does anyone use this?
It has zero weight.

955
00:34:30,101 --> 00:34:32,236
She's wondering how people use
a light knife like that.

956
00:34:32,303 --> 00:34:34,672
-She cuts them in Chinese style.
-That's Chinese style.

957
00:34:34,739 --> 00:34:36,240
-That's Chinese style.
-The Chinese style.

958
00:34:36,307 --> 00:34:39,444
-The ingredients look Chinese.
-But it's for Western food.

959
00:34:39,510 --> 00:34:41,412
They're too thick.
That's how it's done in Chinese.

960
00:34:41,479 --> 00:34:42,780
They'll get smaller when boiled.

961
00:34:42,847 --> 00:34:44,882
-They'll get smaller when boiled.
-When boiled?

962
00:34:44,949 --> 00:34:47,819
She should be chopping them finely,
but they're chunky.

963
00:34:47,885 --> 00:34:49,320
-They're big.
-They are.

964
00:34:49,387 --> 00:34:51,389
She's chopping those like I would.

965
00:34:51,456 --> 00:34:52,690
TRYING TO MOVE THE INGREDIENTS

966
00:34:53,691 --> 00:34:54,525
FALLING

967
00:34:54,592 --> 00:34:57,762
-It's too narrow to move these.
-It doesn't work.

968
00:34:57,829 --> 00:34:58,796
Make multiple trips.

969
00:34:58,863 --> 00:35:03,034
She could move everything at once
with her Chinese knife.

970
00:35:03,101 --> 00:35:05,503
It's as if she ended up
with a tiny shovel to do her job.

971
00:35:05,570 --> 00:35:07,605
She began to chop like I did
with a different knife.

972
00:35:08,072 --> 00:35:09,807
HE'S HAVING TROUBLE TOO

973
00:35:09,874 --> 00:35:12,343
-He can't use the Chinese knife well.
-No.

974
00:35:12,410 --> 00:35:14,378
The green onion pieces
are flying everywhere.

975
00:35:14,445 --> 00:35:16,047
It must feel unfamiliar.

976
00:35:16,114 --> 00:35:16,948
OIL

977
00:35:17,915 --> 00:35:19,016
MINCED GARLIC, MINCED GINGER

978
00:35:19,584 --> 00:35:22,920
Chef Hui-tae prepares seafood.

979
00:35:23,287 --> 00:35:25,323
SHRIMP, SNOW CRAB MEAT

980
00:35:25,389 --> 00:35:26,457
MAKING SCORCHED RICE SOUP

981
00:35:26,524 --> 00:35:29,527
In Chinese cuisine, don't you use
extremely high heat to stir-fry?

982
00:35:29,594 --> 00:35:31,195
-Yes.
-He's frying them over medium heat.

983
00:35:33,131 --> 00:35:34,632
Is he starting with low heat?

984
00:35:34,699 --> 00:35:37,335
-Hui-tae, don't use low heat.
-I've never seen anyone do that.

985
00:35:37,401 --> 00:35:41,272
And he should've slammed the garlic,
but he's using garlic slices.

986
00:35:41,339 --> 00:35:43,141
Did he just slice it nicely?

987
00:35:43,207 --> 00:35:44,642
-Wait, he's…
-That's it!

988
00:35:44,709 --> 00:35:46,444
I CAN SLAM GARLIC CLOVES TOO!

989
00:35:46,511 --> 00:35:47,778
Wait, he's…

990
00:35:48,379 --> 00:35:49,213
BOING

991
00:35:49,881 --> 00:35:50,815
That's it!

992
00:35:51,382 --> 00:35:52,850
TAPPING ON THE GARLIC CLOVES

993
00:35:52,917 --> 00:35:54,385
Who does that?

994
00:35:54,452 --> 00:35:56,387
That was too cautious. Go harder!

995
00:35:56,454 --> 00:35:57,722
Beat it!

996
00:35:58,289 --> 00:36:00,158
THE SOFT GUY
CAN'T EVEN SLAM GARLIC

997
00:36:00,224 --> 00:36:02,360
Yes, you have to do that.

998
00:36:03,327 --> 00:36:04,262
This is too funny.

999
00:36:04,328 --> 00:36:07,265
She's grinding the meat to make ragu.

1000
00:36:07,331 --> 00:36:09,800
Ragu takes a long time to make.

1001
00:36:09,867 --> 00:36:11,369
You don't have much time.

1002
00:36:11,435 --> 00:36:12,370
I don't.

1003
00:36:12,436 --> 00:36:13,504
What about pasta?

1004
00:36:13,571 --> 00:36:15,006
Wait, I need to do this first.

1005
00:36:15,339 --> 00:36:16,807
1. STIR-FRY PREPPED ONION AND MUSHROOM

1006
00:36:16,874 --> 00:36:19,343
Wait, she's using higher heat.

1007
00:36:19,410 --> 00:36:22,613
-The heat is too low on Hui-tae's side.
-It's too low.

1008
00:36:23,080 --> 00:36:24,248
THE TOUGH WOMAN'S NEXT STEP

1009
00:36:24,315 --> 00:36:26,350
Hey, wait!

1010
00:36:26,417 --> 00:36:29,086
-You have to stir-fry that first.
-What are you doing?

1011
00:36:29,153 --> 00:36:32,256
The original recipe requires that
she cook the meat and veggies separately.

1012
00:36:32,323 --> 00:36:33,758
But she's cooking them together.

1013
00:36:33,824 --> 00:36:35,493
She's doing everything in one pan.

1014
00:36:36,427 --> 00:36:37,261
AND ADD A FIRE SHOW

1015
00:36:37,328 --> 00:36:39,030
I thought she was making Chinese!

1016
00:36:39,096 --> 00:36:40,198
Or is she?

1017
00:36:40,264 --> 00:36:42,099
Is she making <i>jjajangmyeon,</i>
black bean noodles?

1018
00:36:42,166 --> 00:36:43,401
That's beef <i>jjajangmyeon.</i>

1019
00:36:46,070 --> 00:36:47,205
THE TOUGH WOMAN WON'T LISTEN

1020
00:36:47,271 --> 00:36:48,806
-<i>Doenjang.</i>
-It looks like…

1021
00:36:48,873 --> 00:36:50,841
She's making mapo tofu!

1022
00:36:51,742 --> 00:36:53,144
THE ITALIAN CHEF IS IN DISBELIEF

1023
00:36:53,945 --> 00:36:54,912
What? <i>Doenjang?</i>

1024
00:36:58,816 --> 00:37:01,652
I'm using tomato sauce, so it's pasta.

1025
00:37:02,486 --> 00:37:04,288
It's pasta since she's using tomato sauce.

1026
00:37:04,755 --> 00:37:06,324
USING HER VIGOR TO MAKE HER CASE

1027
00:37:06,390 --> 00:37:07,458
So are you making pasta?

1028
00:37:07,525 --> 00:37:08,993
-I need more.
-We don't want <i>jjajangmyeon.</i>

1029
00:37:09,994 --> 00:37:11,562
-I just need to add this.
-Milk?

1030
00:37:11,629 --> 00:37:13,030
Once I add this, it'll be pasta.

1031
00:37:13,097 --> 00:37:14,498
Is she making <i>dan dan</i> noodles?

1032
00:37:14,999 --> 00:37:15,900
WHAT'S SHE DOING?

1033
00:37:15,967 --> 00:37:18,469
-It's <i>dan dan</i> noodles.
-It's pasta.

1034
00:37:18,936 --> 00:37:20,037
I SAY IT'S PASTA, SO IT'S PASTA

1035
00:37:20,104 --> 00:37:21,672
-It already looks Chinese.
-It's pasta.

1036
00:37:21,739 --> 00:37:23,574
It'll taste like pasta.

1037
00:37:23,641 --> 00:37:26,677
That's not the ragu pasta that I know.

1038
00:37:27,245 --> 00:37:29,213
CHOPPING ONION
WITH A CHINESE KITCHEN KNIFE!

1039
00:37:29,714 --> 00:37:31,616
2. ADD CHOPPED ONION AND MUSHROOM
TO THE STIR-FRY

1040
00:37:31,682 --> 00:37:33,251
You have to put in oyster sauce.

1041
00:37:33,317 --> 00:37:34,852
Oyster sauce.

1042
00:37:35,253 --> 00:37:36,287
FOLLOWS HER ADVICE

1043
00:37:36,354 --> 00:37:37,488
You need to put in more.

1044
00:37:37,955 --> 00:37:38,789
CHICKEN STOCK

1045
00:37:38,856 --> 00:37:40,258
-Do I need more?
-Much more.

1046
00:37:40,324 --> 00:37:41,559
He poured chicken stock in.

1047
00:37:42,360 --> 00:37:44,562
I'm feeling at ease now.

1048
00:37:44,629 --> 00:37:45,730
Ten minutes.

1049
00:37:45,796 --> 00:37:47,465
I only have ten minutes? Already?

1050
00:37:47,865 --> 00:37:51,702
3. ADD CHOPPED NAPA CABBAGE
INTO THE SEAFOOD STIR-FRY

1051
00:37:51,769 --> 00:37:53,170
-Chef Hui-tae.
-Yes?

1052
00:37:53,237 --> 00:37:54,872
Are you making seafood pasta?

1053
00:37:54,939 --> 00:37:56,874
-I'm not.
-The heat is too low.

1054
00:37:56,941 --> 00:37:58,476
-Or seafood soup.
-No.

1055
00:37:58,542 --> 00:38:00,745
We need to see it cook over high heat
for some smoky flavor.

1056
00:38:00,811 --> 00:38:01,679
She's making pasta.

1057
00:38:01,746 --> 00:38:02,913
MAKING PASTA DOUGH!

1058
00:38:03,281 --> 00:38:04,682
2. MIX FLOUR, EGG, AND WATER

1059
00:38:04,749 --> 00:38:06,484
-The pasta dough.
-The pasta dough?

1060
00:38:06,550 --> 00:38:08,119
Yes, she's making fresh pasta.

1061
00:38:08,185 --> 00:38:10,421
I hope she doesn't make Chinese noodles.

1062
00:38:10,488 --> 00:38:13,024
She probably hasn't had much experience
with egg in the dough.

1063
00:38:13,090 --> 00:38:15,993
It's much harder
than a mix of water and flour.

1064
00:38:16,060 --> 00:38:17,461
She needs to knead with more strength.

1065
00:38:17,528 --> 00:38:20,031
I see. It must require lots of power.

1066
00:38:20,097 --> 00:38:22,533
It looks a bit too thick
for her to roll out later.

1067
00:38:23,367 --> 00:38:25,036
Is it too thick?

1068
00:38:25,269 --> 00:38:26,737
WETTING HER HAND AT HIS WORDS

1069
00:38:26,804 --> 00:38:28,172
She returns after wetting her hand.

1070
00:38:28,239 --> 00:38:30,441
It was too thick, so she wet her hand.

1071
00:38:30,508 --> 00:38:31,642
9 MINUTES AND A HALF LEFT

1072
00:38:31,709 --> 00:38:32,910
When will you cook the sole?

1073
00:38:32,977 --> 00:38:34,712
It won't take long over high heat.

1074
00:38:35,179 --> 00:38:36,714
OH… OKAY…

1075
00:38:37,381 --> 00:38:39,250
PUTS THE RAGU OFF THE HEAT

1076
00:38:39,317 --> 00:38:41,052
Wait, the ragu is already done?

1077
00:38:41,118 --> 00:38:42,586
It's done.

1078
00:38:42,653 --> 00:38:44,455
-It's done?
-It's done?

1079
00:38:44,522 --> 00:38:46,290
She already finished making ragu.

1080
00:38:46,357 --> 00:38:48,759
-You have to simmer it for four hours.
-And she did it in five.

1081
00:38:48,826 --> 00:38:50,661
DOESN'T LISTEN,
GETS READY TO GRILL SOLE

1082
00:38:50,728 --> 00:38:52,363
Are you not going to season it?

1083
00:38:52,430 --> 00:38:54,131
Don't you have to season it?

1084
00:38:54,198 --> 00:38:56,067
-The sauce is strong, so no.
-No!

1085
00:38:56,534 --> 00:38:57,935
HER AND HER CONFIDENCE…

1086
00:38:58,002 --> 00:38:59,670
You don't do that in Western food.

1087
00:38:59,737 --> 00:39:01,238
You have to follow the steps.

1088
00:39:01,305 --> 00:39:03,841
I appreciate her confidence, though.

1089
00:39:03,908 --> 00:39:06,177
You have to season it first,
and then add some sauce.

1090
00:39:06,644 --> 00:39:08,145
POURING OLIVE OIL

1091
00:39:08,212 --> 00:39:12,116
We don't use extra virgin olive oil
to grill fish.

1092
00:39:12,183 --> 00:39:13,551
The scent is too strong.

1093
00:39:13,617 --> 00:39:14,618
AMY PARK, ON HER OWN JOURNEY

1094
00:39:15,186 --> 00:39:17,922
-The chili oil is ready.
-The chili oil.

1095
00:39:17,988 --> 00:39:20,124
-Is the chili oil ready?
-It is.

1096
00:39:20,858 --> 00:39:22,560
That was quick.

1097
00:39:23,227 --> 00:39:25,963
4. CHOP ONION, GREEN ONION,
AND STIR-FRY IN CHILI OIL

1098
00:39:26,030 --> 00:39:27,965
-He's using ketchup.
-Ketchup?

1099
00:39:28,032 --> 00:39:29,133
-Hey.
-Ketchup?

1100
00:39:29,200 --> 00:39:32,103
Yes! I always tell you to use ketchup!

1101
00:39:32,803 --> 00:39:33,838
I love that guy!

1102
00:39:33,904 --> 00:39:36,040
-And vinegar.
-Hey!

1103
00:39:36,107 --> 00:39:38,209
That's it! Pour it in!

1104
00:39:38,275 --> 00:39:39,577
-Vinegar.
-Sam can do that?

1105
00:39:39,643 --> 00:39:41,412
<i>-Doubanjiang.</i>
<i>-Doubanjiang.</i>

1106
00:39:41,479 --> 00:39:43,047
Salty, sweet, and sour!

1107
00:39:43,114 --> 00:39:44,615
Wipe your drool off.

1108
00:39:45,383 --> 00:39:46,917
I'm already drooling.

1109
00:39:46,984 --> 00:39:51,622
So far, it seems like Sam,
aka Hui-tae, is adapting better.

1110
00:39:52,490 --> 00:39:54,458
STARTING TO ROLL THE PASTA DOUGH

1111
00:39:55,659 --> 00:39:56,927
Why is it so hard to roll out?

1112
00:39:56,994 --> 00:39:59,196
"Why is it hard to roll out?"

1113
00:39:59,263 --> 00:40:00,431
That's pasta dough for you.

1114
00:40:00,498 --> 00:40:02,333
-That's how it is.
-More flour.

1115
00:40:02,400 --> 00:40:04,769
ADDING MORE FLOUR AND TRIES AGAIN!

1116
00:40:04,835 --> 00:40:06,937
It looks like
she doesn't have enough strength.

1117
00:40:07,004 --> 00:40:10,040
You need a lot of power to roll that out.

1118
00:40:10,107 --> 00:40:12,042
-It's not easy.
-No.

1119
00:40:12,443 --> 00:40:14,044
PUSHING DOWN AGAIN

1120
00:40:14,645 --> 00:40:15,846
You need to roll it some more.

1121
00:40:15,913 --> 00:40:17,047
It's good enough.

1122
00:40:17,848 --> 00:40:19,250
She has to start cooking the pasta.

1123
00:40:19,316 --> 00:40:20,518
That thick?

1124
00:40:21,118 --> 00:40:22,720
She made <i>jjajangmyeon</i> noodles.

1125
00:40:23,187 --> 00:40:24,989
WHAT'S WITH THAT THICKNESS?

1126
00:40:25,055 --> 00:40:26,857
It's like Chinese knife-cut noodles.

1127
00:40:27,792 --> 00:40:29,226
Yes, it's Chinese knife-cut noodles.

1128
00:40:30,227 --> 00:40:31,562
It's pasta.

1129
00:40:31,629 --> 00:40:33,764
-Is that Chinese knife-cut noodles?
-It's too thick.

1130
00:40:33,831 --> 00:40:35,332
-It's pasta.
-It's too thick.

1131
00:40:35,399 --> 00:40:36,901
-That's so not pasta.
-It's pasta.

1132
00:40:36,967 --> 00:40:38,402
Are you sure it's pasta?

1133
00:40:38,469 --> 00:40:40,271
-It's pasta.
-It's like old-style <i>jjajangmyeon.</i>

1134
00:40:40,337 --> 00:40:42,640
-The old-style <i>jjajangmyeon.</i>
-My gosh.

1135
00:40:42,706 --> 00:40:44,208
It's pasta.

1136
00:40:45,042 --> 00:40:46,243
THICK PASTA NOODLES

1137
00:40:46,877 --> 00:40:48,412
LOOSEN THEM UP

1138
00:40:48,479 --> 00:40:49,480
They're stuck.

1139
00:40:49,547 --> 00:40:51,615
-Chinese knife-cut noodles.
-Pasta.

1140
00:40:51,682 --> 00:40:53,184
-It's pasta.
-It looks like <i>kal-guksu.</i>

1141
00:40:53,250 --> 00:40:54,652
This pasta looks delicious.

1142
00:40:54,718 --> 00:40:56,120
-It's <i>jjajangmyeon.</i>
-<i>Jjajangmyeon </i>looks good.

1143
00:40:56,187 --> 00:40:57,688
Amy, you should start cooking them.

1144
00:40:57,755 --> 00:40:58,956
Right now?

1145
00:40:59,023 --> 00:41:00,925
-It'll take a while to cook.
-Yeah?

1146
00:41:00,991 --> 00:41:04,061
-Put them in quickly.
-You usually need two minutes,

1147
00:41:04,128 --> 00:41:05,796
but they'll take longer
because they're thick.

1148
00:41:05,863 --> 00:41:07,631
Did you salt the water?

1149
00:41:07,698 --> 00:41:10,468
Why would I do that?
The sauce is really strong.

1150
00:41:10,534 --> 00:41:12,837
You have to salt the water!

1151
00:41:13,137 --> 00:41:16,006
THE WESTERN CUISINE CHEFS
ARE DEEPLY FRUSTRATED

1152
00:41:16,073 --> 00:41:17,675
That's not a thing in Chinese food.

1153
00:41:17,741 --> 00:41:19,610
-No, there isn't.
-They don't salt the water.

1154
00:41:19,677 --> 00:41:21,011
It won't taste as good.

1155
00:41:21,579 --> 00:41:24,248
It'd be nice
if someone stirred the noodles.

1156
00:41:24,849 --> 00:41:26,484
TODAY'S "SOMEONE"

1157
00:41:26,550 --> 00:41:28,052
They look like dung loaches.

1158
00:41:28,118 --> 00:41:30,321
They're all stuck,
like <i>kal-jebi</i>, hand-pulled noodles.

1159
00:41:30,387 --> 00:41:31,655
Pull them apart.

1160
00:41:32,156 --> 00:41:33,524
TALKING LIKE THIS ISN'T HER DISH

1161
00:41:33,757 --> 00:41:34,959
WHAT ABOUT HUI-TAE?

1162
00:41:35,526 --> 00:41:38,462
Chinese cuisine rarely uses
eggs in the batter.

1163
00:41:38,529 --> 00:41:39,530
FRYING BATTER FOR SHRIMPS

1164
00:41:39,597 --> 00:41:41,198
It needs to turn out crunchy.

1165
00:41:41,265 --> 00:41:42,967
So is it not as crunchy that way?

1166
00:41:43,033 --> 00:41:45,169
I don't know. I'm sure he has a reason.

1167
00:41:45,236 --> 00:41:47,371
-He probably has a plan.
-I do.

1168
00:41:47,438 --> 00:41:51,509
5. COAT SEASONED SHRIMP WITH BATTER
AND DEEP-FRY

1169
00:41:51,575 --> 00:41:52,576
He's frying the shrimps.

1170
00:41:52,643 --> 00:41:54,478
They need to turn out crunchy.

1171
00:41:54,545 --> 00:41:55,813
It's too thin.

1172
00:41:55,880 --> 00:41:57,882
-The batter's too thin.
-People are worried.

1173
00:41:57,948 --> 00:41:59,483
The batter will peel off.

1174
00:41:59,550 --> 00:42:01,352
-I'll double-fry these.
-Double-frying.

1175
00:42:01,418 --> 00:42:02,486
-Twice?
-He'll double-fry.

1176
00:42:02,553 --> 00:42:04,188
The oil seems too hot too.

1177
00:42:04,255 --> 00:42:05,256
SCOOP OUT AFTER THE FIRST TIME

1178
00:42:05,322 --> 00:42:07,124
Do the shrimps look nice?

1179
00:42:07,191 --> 00:42:10,027
They clearly look more like shrimp bread.

1180
00:42:10,094 --> 00:42:12,963
Sam's deep-fried shrimps…
This is too funny.

1181
00:42:13,831 --> 00:42:15,032
SIGH

1182
00:42:15,099 --> 00:42:16,901
Is she using <i>siraegi</i>, dried radish greens?

1183
00:42:16,967 --> 00:42:17,801
Yes, it's <i>siraegi.</i>

1184
00:42:17,868 --> 00:42:21,038
I'll top it as the sole sauce.

1185
00:42:22,139 --> 00:42:24,542
That's also used in Italy.

1186
00:42:24,608 --> 00:42:25,743
Butter.

1187
00:42:25,809 --> 00:42:27,077
I need to use butter.

1188
00:42:27,144 --> 00:42:28,045
She's adding butter.

1189
00:42:28,112 --> 00:42:29,346
BUTTER IS A MUST!

1190
00:42:29,413 --> 00:42:30,648
Five minutes.

1191
00:42:30,714 --> 00:42:33,150
-Sung-ju, can you report from the kitchen?
-Yes.

1192
00:42:33,217 --> 00:42:35,286
They've exchanged their practices.

1193
00:42:35,352 --> 00:42:37,521
-It's burnt!
-It's not!

1194
00:42:37,588 --> 00:42:38,789
The sole is burnt!

1195
00:42:39,089 --> 00:42:41,659
IT'S AN EMERGENCY

1196
00:42:41,725 --> 00:42:42,993
-It's burnt.
-What's wrong?

1197
00:42:43,060 --> 00:42:45,529
-Where's water?
-The sole.

1198
00:42:45,596 --> 00:42:48,232
We never use high heat to cook fish.

1199
00:42:48,299 --> 00:42:51,035
Goodness, look at the sole fillets.

1200
00:42:51,101 --> 00:42:53,037
They seem a little burnt.

1201
00:42:53,103 --> 00:42:54,672
-It's okay. It's good.
-Is it?

1202
00:42:55,239 --> 00:42:56,373
A BUCKET OF WATER INTO THE POT

1203
00:42:56,440 --> 00:42:58,375
Don't you add more water like that
to make <i>jjajangmyeon?</i>

1204
00:42:58,442 --> 00:43:01,078
-Are those dung loaches?
-They're loaches.

1205
00:43:01,145 --> 00:43:02,379
They look like fried tofu.

1206
00:43:02,446 --> 00:43:04,348
-Four minutes. The ragu.
-The ragu.

1207
00:43:04,415 --> 00:43:06,450
Does the ragu taste like Eun-yeong's dish

1208
00:43:06,517 --> 00:43:08,152
or Amy Park's dish?

1209
00:43:08,218 --> 00:43:09,520
The three-minute ragu.

1210
00:43:09,587 --> 00:43:10,688
The three-minute ragu.

1211
00:43:10,754 --> 00:43:12,056
I'm not sure about this.

1212
00:43:12,523 --> 00:43:13,390
VAGUE RAGU

1213
00:43:13,457 --> 00:43:14,325
Was it Eun-yeong?

1214
00:43:14,391 --> 00:43:16,260
-I'd say Eun-yeong Park.
-Eun-yeong Park?

1215
00:43:16,327 --> 00:43:18,262
-I'm not sure about this.
-It must simmer for a while.

1216
00:43:18,329 --> 00:43:21,031
Was this made by Amy or Eun-yeong?
It's hard to say.

1217
00:43:22,132 --> 00:43:24,168
ADJUSTING THICKNESS WITH STARCH WATER

1218
00:43:24,234 --> 00:43:25,769
Try Hui-tae's dish too.

1219
00:43:25,836 --> 00:43:28,138
Let me try the chili sauce.

1220
00:43:28,205 --> 00:43:29,440
The color looks nice.

1221
00:43:29,506 --> 00:43:31,575
Does it taste like
Sam's dish or Hui-tae's?

1222
00:43:31,642 --> 00:43:33,477
This is Hui-tae's dish.

1223
00:43:33,544 --> 00:43:34,578
Is it Hui-tae's dish?

1224
00:43:34,645 --> 00:43:36,146
We're in China right now.

1225
00:43:36,213 --> 00:43:37,648
Is it sweet, salty, and sour?

1226
00:43:37,715 --> 00:43:38,682
It is.

1227
00:43:38,749 --> 00:43:39,850
It's SSS.

1228
00:43:39,917 --> 00:43:41,919
Yes, it's sweet, salty, and sour.

1229
00:43:41,986 --> 00:43:43,687
-I'm frying these again.
-Double-frying.

1230
00:43:44,588 --> 00:43:46,490
Why won't this get cooked?

1231
00:43:46,557 --> 00:43:48,959
-You said it'd be quick.
-It won't.

1232
00:43:49,026 --> 00:43:50,227
I mean, why won't it?

1233
00:43:50,294 --> 00:43:51,261
COMPLAINING AND MOVING ON

1234
00:43:51,829 --> 00:43:54,632
Wait, no. Are you serious?
Rethink the honey.

1235
00:43:54,698 --> 00:43:56,300
-Enough!
-No, I need the sweetness.

1236
00:43:56,367 --> 00:43:57,635
Is that honey butter sauce?

1237
00:43:57,701 --> 00:44:00,304
-Balsamic?
-It needs balsamic vinegar.

1238
00:44:00,371 --> 00:44:02,473
I've never seen anyone use honey
for an Italian dish.

1239
00:44:03,407 --> 00:44:05,476
Why are you suddenly setting it on fire?

1240
00:44:05,542 --> 00:44:07,044
She suddenly set it on fire.

1241
00:44:07,111 --> 00:44:09,113
-Simmer the ragu.
-That's too much honey!

1242
00:44:09,179 --> 00:44:11,415
Why are you adding so much honey?
You aren't making candy.

1243
00:44:11,482 --> 00:44:12,716
Was she supposed to cook like you?

1244
00:44:12,783 --> 00:44:13,917
That wasn't the theme.

1245
00:44:13,984 --> 00:44:16,520
-It's an emergency.
-The sole sauce.

1246
00:44:16,587 --> 00:44:18,255
It needs some sweetness.

1247
00:44:18,322 --> 00:44:19,890
The sauce is weird. It's an emergency.

1248
00:44:19,957 --> 00:44:22,326
Will this sole sauce taste Italian?

1249
00:44:22,393 --> 00:44:25,062
-It's probably too sweet.
-Does it taste Italian?

1250
00:44:25,129 --> 00:44:26,530
Or is she back in China?

1251
00:44:26,597 --> 00:44:28,165
-It's too sweet, right?
-This one…

1252
00:44:28,232 --> 00:44:29,967
tastes Italian.

1253
00:44:30,668 --> 00:44:31,769
UNEXPECTED

1254
00:44:31,835 --> 00:44:33,337
It was sweeter than I thought.

1255
00:44:33,404 --> 00:44:35,239
It does have some sweetness.

1256
00:44:35,305 --> 00:44:37,675
Why did you pick out this theme?

1257
00:44:37,741 --> 00:44:40,077
-But it's fun.
-It's fun.

1258
00:44:40,144 --> 00:44:41,912
Two minutes.

1259
00:44:42,446 --> 00:44:43,380
HUI-TAE RETRIEVES THE SHRIMPS

1260
00:44:43,447 --> 00:44:44,515
Two minutes left.

1261
00:44:44,581 --> 00:44:46,817
-It turned into delicious shrimp bread.
-He scoops out the shrimp.

1262
00:44:46,884 --> 00:44:48,786
-Is this scorched rice soup?
-You're right.

1263
00:44:48,852 --> 00:44:50,954
-It's the base for the soup.
-Yes.

1264
00:44:51,021 --> 00:44:53,323
The scorched rice won't puff up
because of the temperature.

1265
00:44:53,390 --> 00:44:54,825
It needs to puff up.

1266
00:44:54,892 --> 00:44:56,794
Why haven't you fried the scorched rice?

1267
00:44:56,860 --> 00:44:58,896
-The scorched rice?
-You need to raise the temperature.

1268
00:44:58,962 --> 00:45:01,165
-Raise the temperature!
-Dang it.

1269
00:45:01,231 --> 00:45:02,633
Everything is a mess.

1270
00:45:02,700 --> 00:45:04,268
The stove is on fire on this side,

1271
00:45:04,334 --> 00:45:06,270
and there's zero heat on this side.

1272
00:45:06,804 --> 00:45:08,772
ON FIRE

1273
00:45:09,339 --> 00:45:10,507
Time to <i>mantecare.</i>

1274
00:45:10,574 --> 00:45:12,309
-You have no time.
-Oh, no.

1275
00:45:13,343 --> 00:45:15,345
-Oh, no.
-What's going on?

1276
00:45:15,412 --> 00:45:16,380
THE VINEGAR DROPS

1277
00:45:16,447 --> 00:45:19,249
-There has been a huge accident!
-What's going on?

1278
00:45:19,316 --> 00:45:20,818
No! My vinegar!

1279
00:45:21,318 --> 00:45:22,219
TOSSES THE PASTA WATER

1280
00:45:22,286 --> 00:45:23,120
No!

1281
00:45:23,187 --> 00:45:25,622
The vinegar bottle fell down.

1282
00:45:25,689 --> 00:45:27,691
-That was Poong's sauce.
-His personal sauce.

1283
00:45:27,758 --> 00:45:29,126
-My vinegar.
-Oh, no.

1284
00:45:29,193 --> 00:45:30,861
Fifty seconds.

1285
00:45:30,928 --> 00:45:32,763
About 40 seconds now.

1286
00:45:32,830 --> 00:45:34,598
-You must finish up.
-Finish up.

1287
00:45:35,265 --> 00:45:37,301
I have to <i>mantecare!</i>

1288
00:45:37,367 --> 00:45:38,769
That's not how you do it!

1289
00:45:40,304 --> 00:45:41,705
RIDING A TAGADA?

1290
00:45:42,372 --> 00:45:44,241
SOMETHING…

1291
00:45:44,308 --> 00:45:46,877
HAS GONE TERRIBLY WRONG…

1292
00:45:48,312 --> 00:45:49,313
WOK-TECARE

1293
00:45:49,379 --> 00:45:50,614
That's stir-fried <i>jjamppong.</i>

1294
00:45:50,681 --> 00:45:51,815
No, stir-fried <i>jjajangmyeon.</i>

1295
00:45:51,882 --> 00:45:53,650
Stir-fried <i>jjajangmyeon?</i>

1296
00:45:54,118 --> 00:45:55,753
KEEP UP YOUR SPIRIT, EUN-YEONG!

1297
00:45:55,819 --> 00:45:57,921
-What is that?
-Stir-fried <i>jjajangmyeon.</i>

1298
00:45:57,988 --> 00:45:59,223
Or stir-fried squid.

1299
00:45:59,289 --> 00:46:01,825
-What was that?
-This side is blazing.

1300
00:46:02,392 --> 00:46:03,293
She's plating it.

1301
00:46:04,394 --> 00:46:06,730
IS THIS RAGU PASTA?

1302
00:46:06,797 --> 00:46:08,232
-Twenty seconds.
-Twenty-five seconds.

1303
00:46:08,298 --> 00:46:09,500
Time to finish up.

1304
00:46:09,967 --> 00:46:12,736
6. MIX FRIED SHRIMP WITH CHILI SAUCE

1305
00:46:12,803 --> 00:46:15,239
That's Poong's mayo creation.

1306
00:46:15,305 --> 00:46:16,507
More lemon juice.

1307
00:46:16,974 --> 00:46:18,041
MIXING THE SAUCE WITH SHRIMP

1308
00:46:18,108 --> 00:46:20,110
He's using that sauce?

1309
00:46:20,844 --> 00:46:22,846
-Are you making two flavors?
-I am.

1310
00:46:22,913 --> 00:46:24,014
That looks like

1311
00:46:24,081 --> 00:46:25,349
something Poong made.

1312
00:46:25,916 --> 00:46:27,684
TRIGGERED

1313
00:46:28,152 --> 00:46:29,720
IT LOOKS LIKE A POONG DISH

1314
00:46:29,787 --> 00:46:31,889
-This is so much fun.
-What is that?

1315
00:46:31,955 --> 00:46:34,158
-Ten. Nine.
-Ten. Nine.

1316
00:46:34,224 --> 00:46:35,893
Eight. Seven.

1317
00:46:36,360 --> 00:46:37,861
TOPPING WITH PARMESAN

1318
00:46:38,529 --> 00:46:40,831
HUI-TAE IS DONE
WITH THE SCORCHED RICE SOUP TOO!

1319
00:46:40,898 --> 00:46:42,666
-Just pour it!
-Four.

1320
00:46:42,733 --> 00:46:44,735
-Three. Two.
-Butter!

1321
00:46:44,802 --> 00:46:45,702
One!

1322
00:46:45,769 --> 00:46:49,072
Time's up.

1323
00:46:49,139 --> 00:46:50,407
Sam finished first,

1324
00:46:50,474 --> 00:46:53,310
-followed by Chef Eun-yeong.
-What about the fish?

1325
00:46:53,377 --> 00:46:55,712
It's here. I just need to plate it.

1326
00:46:55,779 --> 00:46:58,215
Or do it like Poong

1327
00:46:58,282 --> 00:46:59,917
-and serve it on the pan.
-No.

1328
00:46:59,983 --> 00:47:01,451
I'll eat it off the pan.

1329
00:47:01,518 --> 00:47:02,920
Just keep it on the pan.

1330
00:47:02,986 --> 00:47:05,389
May I plate this?

1331
00:47:05,455 --> 00:47:06,623
Let me just put this here.

1332
00:47:06,690 --> 00:47:09,359
-I'll take the pan.
-I wanted to make it look Italian.

1333
00:47:09,426 --> 00:47:11,495
-Doing that doesn't make it look Italian.
-No.

1334
00:47:11,562 --> 00:47:13,697
Is she topping it with black bean sauce?

1335
00:47:13,764 --> 00:47:15,299
Is that black bean sauce?

1336
00:47:15,766 --> 00:47:17,868
WHAT IS THAT?

1337
00:47:17,935 --> 00:47:19,336
When they switched the food genre,

1338
00:47:19,903 --> 00:47:21,405
they all became Poong.

1339
00:47:23,507 --> 00:47:27,177
-Things have never been this hectic.
-What is that?

1340
00:47:27,244 --> 00:47:29,313
It's not easy to cook something
outside your practice.

1341
00:47:29,379 --> 00:47:30,848
It must be really hard.

1342
00:47:30,914 --> 00:47:33,750
Both dishes were made
for "Culinary Darkness Wars: Genre Hell,"

1343
00:47:33,817 --> 00:47:35,485
-just for Poong.
-It looks good.

1344
00:47:35,953 --> 00:47:38,121
DEEPLY GRATEFUL

1345
00:47:38,188 --> 00:47:39,690
It was so hectic.

1346
00:47:39,756 --> 00:47:43,861
I felt a little bad
for giving them this kind of burden,

1347
00:47:45,128 --> 00:47:47,231
but it was as fun as I expected.

1348
00:47:47,297 --> 00:47:49,099
-It was fun.
-Over there, I noticed

1349
00:47:49,166 --> 00:47:51,568
that they couldn't turn away
from their years of habits.

1350
00:47:51,635 --> 00:47:52,903
-No.
-Right?

1351
00:47:53,503 --> 00:47:55,038
Have you two missed anything?

1352
00:47:55,105 --> 00:47:56,940
May I top it with some dill?

1353
00:47:57,007 --> 00:47:58,809
-I see. Dill?
-Dill.

1354
00:47:58,876 --> 00:48:00,911
-Amy Park, did you forget some dill?
-Yes.

1355
00:48:00,978 --> 00:48:03,480
-What about Sam?
-I had crushed some Sichuan pepper.

1356
00:48:03,547 --> 00:48:05,415
-That's important.
-May I add some on the top?

1357
00:48:05,482 --> 00:48:07,117
Okay. That sounds fair.

1358
00:48:07,184 --> 00:48:08,252
All right, then.

1359
00:48:08,318 --> 00:48:11,722
They had to switch each other's cuisines.

1360
00:48:11,788 --> 00:48:14,291
-You could've come this way.
-Why did you go there?

1361
00:48:14,358 --> 00:48:16,159
That's not yours. This one is.

1362
00:48:16,727 --> 00:48:18,262
HAHAHA

1363
00:48:18,328 --> 00:48:19,696
-He thought this was it.
-So smooth.

1364
00:48:19,763 --> 00:48:20,998
THE PASTA CALLED FOR ME…

1365
00:48:21,064 --> 00:48:23,600
Why did you try
to add Sichuan pepper in her dish?

1366
00:48:23,667 --> 00:48:24,668
DROOPY

1367
00:48:24,735 --> 00:48:26,336
Is that how you use dill?

1368
00:48:26,403 --> 00:48:28,605
-It doesn't magically make it Italian.
-We don't make them

1369
00:48:28,672 --> 00:48:31,108
-look droopy like a willow.
-What is that?

1370
00:48:31,174 --> 00:48:33,110
She's topping it like cilantro.

1371
00:48:33,176 --> 00:48:35,512
Like she's using cooked greens.

1372
00:48:35,579 --> 00:48:38,048
Now, please try Chef Hui-tae's dish first.

1373
00:48:38,115 --> 00:48:39,283
It's his Chinese dish.

1374
00:48:39,349 --> 00:48:43,253
SSS
CHILI SHRIMP AND CREAMY SHRIMP

1375
00:48:44,087 --> 00:48:47,291
SCORCHED RICE SOUP WITH LOTS OF SEAFOOD

1376
00:48:48,258 --> 00:48:52,029
CHEF KIM HUI-TAE'S DARKNESS RESTAURANT

1377
00:48:52,796 --> 00:48:53,630
Darkness Restaurant.

1378
00:48:53,697 --> 00:48:57,367
It definitely looks like
something in Chinese cuisine.

1379
00:48:57,434 --> 00:48:58,502
Right?

1380
00:48:58,568 --> 00:49:00,637
-Gotta take pictures.
-Is it worth taking pictures of it?

1381
00:49:00,704 --> 00:49:04,274
Of course.
I'm sure he'll never do this again.

1382
00:49:04,341 --> 00:49:07,678
-It's a rare occasion.
-The first and the last time.

1383
00:49:07,744 --> 00:49:08,879
How should I eat this?

1384
00:49:08,946 --> 00:49:11,782
First, try the chili shrimp.

1385
00:49:11,848 --> 00:49:15,218
The creamy one made with mayo
is for your son.

1386
00:49:15,285 --> 00:49:17,554
-For my son? Oh, I see.
-And then,

1387
00:49:17,621 --> 00:49:21,024
scoop out a big spoonful
of the soup and try that.

1388
00:49:21,091 --> 00:49:23,093
Thank you for the food.

1389
00:49:23,694 --> 00:49:26,496
-Creamy shrimp and chili shrimp.
-Yes.

1390
00:49:26,563 --> 00:49:29,099
It needs to be salty, sweet, and sour.

1391
00:49:29,166 --> 00:49:30,634
It seems mushy.

1392
00:49:31,335 --> 00:49:33,370
Chef Eun-yeong, how does this look?

1393
00:49:33,437 --> 00:49:35,138
-It looks mushy.
-I can tell

1394
00:49:35,205 --> 00:49:37,541
by the way he holds it up
with his chopsticks.

1395
00:49:37,607 --> 00:49:39,242
That hasn't been fried properly.

1396
00:49:40,644 --> 00:49:42,446
-The fritter turned out bad?
-Yes.

1397
00:49:42,512 --> 00:49:44,581
-The coat turned mushy.
-It's mushy.

1398
00:49:44,648 --> 00:49:47,284
-It looks mushy.
-And it's about to peel off.

1399
00:49:47,351 --> 00:49:48,852
It could be intentional.

1400
00:49:49,853 --> 00:49:52,589
A BITE OF CHILI SHRIMP

1401
00:49:52,656 --> 00:49:54,691
-Chili shrimp.
-It looks good.

1402
00:49:55,792 --> 00:49:57,127
MMM!!

1403
00:49:57,661 --> 00:49:59,162
The sauce looks good.

1404
00:49:59,229 --> 00:50:01,098
-Are we in China?
-Or Italy?

1405
00:50:01,264 --> 00:50:02,099
MMM

1406
00:50:02,366 --> 00:50:04,167
Does the chili shrimp taste okay?

1407
00:50:04,234 --> 00:50:05,335
NEXT, JUST THE SAUCE

1408
00:50:05,402 --> 00:50:06,236
MMM

1409
00:50:06,970 --> 00:50:09,272
-It must be nice.
-It must taste good.

1410
00:50:09,339 --> 00:50:11,508
QUIETLY TAKES ANOTHER BITE

1411
00:50:11,575 --> 00:50:13,276
Is it fried all right?

1412
00:50:13,844 --> 00:50:15,679
-Oh.
-What is it?

1413
00:50:15,746 --> 00:50:17,581
-It's good.
-Is it?

1414
00:50:18,682 --> 00:50:22,886
I expected the shrimp
to have a crunch to it,

1415
00:50:22,953 --> 00:50:25,822
but it was mushy
and drenched in the sauce.

1416
00:50:26,523 --> 00:50:29,826
It feels like I'm eating bread
dipped in broth or sauce,

1417
00:50:29,893 --> 00:50:31,795
and I honestly love that texture.

1418
00:50:31,862 --> 00:50:34,131
I like that kind of texture.

1419
00:50:34,197 --> 00:50:35,465
Instead of something too crunchy?

1420
00:50:35,532 --> 00:50:37,100
Also, the sauce

1421
00:50:37,167 --> 00:50:39,336
isn't too strong.

1422
00:50:39,403 --> 00:50:40,637
The balance is great.

1423
00:50:42,939 --> 00:50:44,241
The creamy shrimp.

1424
00:50:44,841 --> 00:50:48,011
-This one came right off.
-The batter came off.

1425
00:50:48,078 --> 00:50:49,813
The batter peeled off?

1426
00:50:49,880 --> 00:50:51,648
It took off its shirt.

1427
00:50:51,715 --> 00:50:54,785
-Deep-frying seems tough.
-It is.

1428
00:50:55,285 --> 00:50:57,254
BOLDLY EATS IT IN ONE BITE

1429
00:50:57,554 --> 00:50:58,889
CURIOUS

1430
00:50:58,955 --> 00:51:01,525
-Come to think of it, it's Chinese.
-It is.

1431
00:51:01,591 --> 00:51:02,726
It has to taste Chinese.

1432
00:51:02,793 --> 00:51:05,429
Yet I can sense Chef Sam's touch

1433
00:51:05,495 --> 00:51:07,564
as I chew on this.

1434
00:51:07,631 --> 00:51:09,633
It tastes healthy.

1435
00:51:10,100 --> 00:51:11,334
CAN'T HIDE HIS NATURALIST SIDE

1436
00:51:11,401 --> 00:51:12,769
It wasn't overdone.

1437
00:51:12,836 --> 00:51:16,640
If this were a club,
it'd be made of cotton.

1438
00:51:16,706 --> 00:51:18,608
-The scorched rice soup.
-The seafood scorched rice soup.

1439
00:51:18,675 --> 00:51:21,211
-The thickness didn't seem…
-The thickness.

1440
00:51:21,278 --> 00:51:22,679
I don't think it is…

1441
00:51:22,746 --> 00:51:26,416
It's about as thick as minestrone,
an Italian vegetable soup.

1442
00:51:26,483 --> 00:51:29,219
-It should be much thicker.
-It's okay.

1443
00:51:29,286 --> 00:51:31,621
-It's more like soup, I guess.
-Minestrone?

1444
00:51:31,688 --> 00:51:34,558
A chef's DNA cannot be changed.

1445
00:51:34,624 --> 00:51:36,259
-It's impossible.
-I guess not.

1446
00:51:36,326 --> 00:51:37,427
Let me try some.

1447
00:51:37,494 --> 00:51:38,762
-It smells great.
-Does it?

1448
00:51:38,829 --> 00:51:41,765
-It smells fantastic.
-The seafood rice soup.

1449
00:51:42,332 --> 00:51:43,934
SLURP

1450
00:51:44,568 --> 00:51:47,471
-It looks hot.
-Does it taste like the Chinese soup?

1451
00:51:47,537 --> 00:51:48,672
Is it hot?

1452
00:51:49,339 --> 00:51:50,273
HEHEHEHE

1453
00:51:50,340 --> 00:51:51,508
It must taste Italian.

1454
00:51:51,575 --> 00:51:53,677
I think Poong is laughing at the dish.

1455
00:51:54,945 --> 00:51:56,480
This is so fascinating.

1456
00:51:57,180 --> 00:52:00,183
-We get it, so tell us.
-What's so fascinating?

1457
00:52:00,250 --> 00:52:02,052
Tell us what's fascinating.

1458
00:52:02,119 --> 00:52:04,421
It doesn't taste like
the scorched rice soup I know.

1459
00:52:04,488 --> 00:52:05,722
-No?
-No.

1460
00:52:05,789 --> 00:52:09,126
The thickness and the flavor
make me feel very relaxed,

1461
00:52:09,192 --> 00:52:11,394
like a hearty bowl
of Italian home-cooked soup.

1462
00:52:11,461 --> 00:52:13,096
-Italian soup.
-It tastes like

1463
00:52:13,163 --> 00:52:17,134
a very hearty Italian soup.

1464
00:52:17,200 --> 00:52:19,302
But it's really good.

1465
00:52:19,369 --> 00:52:21,104
It was a bit bland when I had it.

1466
00:52:21,171 --> 00:52:22,639
-It's seasoned perfectly.
-Is it?

1467
00:52:22,706 --> 00:52:24,541
It turned out as soup…

1468
00:52:24,608 --> 00:52:26,543
-Without any thickness.
-…so it tastes perfect.

1469
00:52:26,610 --> 00:52:28,912
It turned out like thin soup.

1470
00:52:28,979 --> 00:52:30,313
What about the scorched rice?

1471
00:52:30,380 --> 00:52:33,383
-It's just scorched rice.
-I see.

1472
00:52:33,450 --> 00:52:34,818
Regular scorched rice, not deep-fried.

1473
00:52:34,885 --> 00:52:35,886
Regular scorched rice.

1474
00:52:35,952 --> 00:52:38,388
Usually, it's served
with sizzling hot deep-fried rice.

1475
00:52:38,455 --> 00:52:39,823
It has to be crunchy.

1476
00:52:39,890 --> 00:52:42,325
Isn't that made with sticky rice?

1477
00:52:42,392 --> 00:52:44,728
It's usually made with sticky rice,

1478
00:52:44,794 --> 00:52:48,665
but non-glutinous rice
does puff up in high temperature.

1479
00:52:48,732 --> 00:52:51,701
<i>-The oil was too cold.</i>
<i>-It should've been fried in high heat.</i>

1480
00:52:51,768 --> 00:52:53,203
The thing is, it's not easy

1481
00:52:53,270 --> 00:52:55,739
for Western cuisine chefs
to go over the temperature limit.

1482
00:52:55,805 --> 00:52:57,007
That's true.

1483
00:52:57,073 --> 00:53:00,343
It feels like it'll burn.

1484
00:53:00,410 --> 00:53:02,345
Despite everything,

1485
00:53:02,412 --> 00:53:05,148
both dishes are hearty,
something you can keep eating.

1486
00:53:05,215 --> 00:53:07,817
Was it Hearty Restaurant,
not Darkness Restaurant?

1487
00:53:07,884 --> 00:53:10,453
-That's it. Hearty Restaurant.
-Hearty Restaurant.

1488
00:53:10,520 --> 00:53:13,623
Next, Amy Park's dish,
Western Food Queen? Got-Ragu Be Me.

1489
00:53:14,024 --> 00:53:16,860
RAGU PASTA WITH THE THICKEST PASTA

1490
00:53:18,128 --> 00:53:21,264
GRILLED SOLE TOPPED WITH SIRAEGI SAUCE,
NOT BLACK BEAN SAUCE

1491
00:53:22,032 --> 00:53:23,099
CHEF AMY PARK'S
WESTERN FOOD QUEEN? GOT-RAGU BE ME

1492
00:53:23,166 --> 00:53:24,834
<i>Western Food Queen? Got-Ragu Be Me.</i>

1493
00:53:25,335 --> 00:53:27,604
Overall, the ingredients she used

1494
00:53:27,671 --> 00:53:30,407
-reminded me of <i>jjajangmyeon </i>in Gunsan.
-<i>Mul-jjajangmyeon.</i>

1495
00:53:30,473 --> 00:53:32,242
Yes, like <i>mul-jjajangmyeon.</i>

1496
00:53:32,309 --> 00:53:35,345
I've never seen pasta that thick.

1497
00:53:35,412 --> 00:53:37,214
It's as thick as <i>kal-guksu</i> noodles.

1498
00:53:37,280 --> 00:53:40,183
But there are
many different types of pasta in Italy,

1499
00:53:40,250 --> 00:53:43,486
so a region somewhere in Italy
may have this kind of pasta.

1500
00:53:44,888 --> 00:53:46,389
-But…
-If there is, I've never seen it.

1501
00:53:46,723 --> 00:53:48,258
BOO! PFFT!

1502
00:53:48,325 --> 00:53:49,426
Thank you.

1503
00:53:49,492 --> 00:53:51,228
-It looks good.
-You can play tug-of-war with that.

1504
00:53:51,294 --> 00:53:52,963
CAN PLAY TUG-OF-WAR WITH THE PASTA

1505
00:53:53,029 --> 00:53:56,132
-You can use it as a rope.
-Yes, and play tug-of-war.

1506
00:53:56,199 --> 00:53:57,567
The flavor is what's important.

1507
00:53:57,634 --> 00:54:00,670
There must be a reason
why it shouldn't be thick.

1508
00:54:00,737 --> 00:54:03,273
A HEAD TILT?

1509
00:54:03,607 --> 00:54:05,642
But Amy Park made thick pasta.

1510
00:54:06,409 --> 00:54:08,111
-What is that?
-What's that?

1511
00:54:08,178 --> 00:54:09,613
Is that a bone?

1512
00:54:09,679 --> 00:54:12,015
-That's a loach.
-That looks so…

1513
00:54:12,082 --> 00:54:15,619
EATING A WHOLE LOACH(?)

1514
00:54:15,685 --> 00:54:17,420
-Something like that.
-You know,

1515
00:54:17,487 --> 00:54:18,855
the pasta…

1516
00:54:18,922 --> 00:54:20,523
CHEWING

1517
00:54:20,590 --> 00:54:22,158
Is it hard?

1518
00:54:22,225 --> 00:54:24,227
-Was it undercooked?
-He's still chewing.

1519
00:54:24,294 --> 00:54:26,896
-Is it like a rope?
-There's a nice chew to it.

1520
00:54:26,963 --> 00:54:29,332
-Was it undercooked?
-The pasta comes with a chew.

1521
00:54:29,399 --> 00:54:31,801
That's what we call al dente.

1522
00:54:31,868 --> 00:54:34,904
Yes, there's a chew to it
because it was cooked to al dante.

1523
00:54:34,971 --> 00:54:37,507
-Al dante.
-It's "al dente."

1524
00:54:37,574 --> 00:54:40,377
-Al dente.
-Al dente. It's not al dante.

1525
00:54:40,443 --> 00:54:43,513
Al dente.
I wanted you to enjoy the texture.

1526
00:54:44,080 --> 00:54:45,048
I can taste

1527
00:54:45,115 --> 00:54:46,216
her effort in this.

1528
00:54:46,283 --> 00:54:48,285
-Did she put in an effort?
-It's over.

1529
00:54:48,351 --> 00:54:49,853
Nice try.

1530
00:54:49,919 --> 00:54:51,755
-Yes, nice try.
-In a good way, though.

1531
00:54:51,821 --> 00:54:55,825
She must've wanted to throw in
so many more ingredients in here.

1532
00:54:55,892 --> 00:54:58,862
I can taste that she tried hard
to hold herself back.

1533
00:54:58,928 --> 00:55:01,364
-She has one more dish, the sole.
-The fish.

1534
00:55:01,431 --> 00:55:03,733
Did you make a heart shape on purpose?

1535
00:55:03,800 --> 00:55:06,202
-You're right.
-I knew it.

1536
00:55:06,269 --> 00:55:08,705
She made such a pretty heart shape.

1537
00:55:08,772 --> 00:55:11,374
I spread it out into that shape
while grilling it.

1538
00:55:11,441 --> 00:55:13,476
Yes, I saw you do that.

1539
00:55:14,044 --> 00:55:15,679
This should be an Italian dish.

1540
00:55:15,745 --> 00:55:18,281
It's grilled perfectly
as a nice side dish for rice.

1541
00:55:18,348 --> 00:55:19,382
It looks good.

1542
00:55:19,449 --> 00:55:20,317
SHH!

1543
00:55:20,383 --> 00:55:21,584
I'll try a bite.

1544
00:55:22,252 --> 00:55:23,486
That's like cilantro.

1545
00:55:24,321 --> 00:55:26,122
LAUGHING

1546
00:55:26,189 --> 00:55:27,457
-What is it?
-He's bursting out laughing.

1547
00:55:27,524 --> 00:55:29,626
-It had a crunch.
-A crunch?

1548
00:55:29,693 --> 00:55:31,861
-It's crispy.
-Crispy?

1549
00:55:33,096 --> 00:55:35,031
Well, that's Chinese food.

1550
00:55:35,098 --> 00:55:36,833
Of course, it has to be crispy.

1551
00:55:36,900 --> 00:55:39,569
How does this taste like fritter?

1552
00:55:39,636 --> 00:55:42,706
<i>She grilled it with a bit of oil.</i>

1553
00:55:42,772 --> 00:55:46,409
Meunière is a dish
grilled over low heat with lots of oil,

1554
00:55:46,476 --> 00:55:48,611
but she did it over high heat.

1555
00:55:48,678 --> 00:55:50,447
I feel anxious when the heat

1556
00:55:50,513 --> 00:55:51,715
drops below a certain point.

1557
00:55:53,149 --> 00:55:55,151
-They're opposites.
-They are.

1558
00:55:55,218 --> 00:55:57,087
-That's Chef Amy.
-Polar opposites.

1559
00:55:57,153 --> 00:55:59,189
-Of course.
-What's the sauce like?

1560
00:55:59,255 --> 00:56:00,957
It was made with <i>siraegi</i>, right?

1561
00:56:01,024 --> 00:56:04,561
Siraegi, <i>olives, capers, and jalapeño.</i>

1562
00:56:04,627 --> 00:56:06,930
-Balsamic vinegar, and honey too.
-And honey.

1563
00:56:06,996 --> 00:56:09,065
It's so delicious

1564
00:56:09,132 --> 00:56:11,534
that she could sell this
at her restaurant.

1565
00:56:11,601 --> 00:56:14,304
-That means it tastes Chinese.
-It's Chinese, then.

1566
00:56:14,371 --> 00:56:18,475
That's not what I mean.
I keep craving for more.

1567
00:56:18,541 --> 00:56:19,909
He's beating around the bush.

1568
00:56:19,976 --> 00:56:21,378
It's more like Chinese food.

1569
00:56:21,444 --> 00:56:24,013
Let's try Chef Hui-tae's dish first.

1570
00:56:24,080 --> 00:56:25,782
-The shrimp is…
-This one.

1571
00:56:25,849 --> 00:56:28,685
-The batter peels off right away.
-Let's try some.

1572
00:56:28,752 --> 00:56:31,921
-Goodness.
-The shrimps must've been hot.

1573
00:56:31,988 --> 00:56:34,057
They all took off their coating.

1574
00:56:34,124 --> 00:56:35,759
They're already in summer.

1575
00:56:35,825 --> 00:56:37,694
This soup is quite thin.

1576
00:56:37,761 --> 00:56:40,196
It tastes like soup in Western cuisine.

1577
00:56:40,263 --> 00:56:42,499
He couldn't abandon his Italian chef DNA.

1578
00:56:43,266 --> 00:56:45,101
Ho-young seems to enjoy it.

1579
00:56:45,168 --> 00:56:47,203
-This is so good.
-It's good.

1580
00:56:47,270 --> 00:56:48,438
What do you think, Chef Jong-won?

1581
00:56:48,505 --> 00:56:50,473
When I was in America,

1582
00:56:50,540 --> 00:56:54,244
most of the cooks
at small local Chinese restaurants

1583
00:56:54,310 --> 00:56:56,146
weren't Chinese a lot of the time.

1584
00:56:56,212 --> 00:56:59,215
-That's true.
-Often, they were Latin Americans.

1585
00:56:59,282 --> 00:57:02,519
Despite that, everything was good,
though it wasn't my idea of Chinese food.

1586
00:57:02,585 --> 00:57:04,821
-It's good.
-I keep craving it.

1587
00:57:04,888 --> 00:57:09,826
I think this also stemmed
from his days in America.

1588
00:57:09,893 --> 00:57:13,296
I think Chef Eun-yeong will provide
a more accurate evaluation.

1589
00:57:13,363 --> 00:57:15,932
It tastes like Chinese scorched rice soup,

1590
00:57:15,999 --> 00:57:17,500
<i>but because it's too thin,</i>

1591
00:57:17,567 --> 00:57:20,336
<i>it feels like I'm sipping on Western soup.</i>

1592
00:57:20,403 --> 00:57:23,973
-He should've added more starch.
-He needed more starch.

1593
00:57:24,040 --> 00:57:26,042
It'll turn into oyster <i>jjamppong</i>
with some oysters.

1594
00:57:26,609 --> 00:57:28,378
-Yes, oyster <i>jjamppong.</i>
-You're right.

1595
00:57:28,445 --> 00:57:30,013
-You're right.
-Yes.

1596
00:57:30,079 --> 00:57:31,381
You should've called it that.

1597
00:57:31,448 --> 00:57:34,117
-It's the soup for oyster <i>jjamppong.</i>
-Something like that.

1598
00:57:34,184 --> 00:57:37,287
Next, please try Amy Park's dish.

1599
00:57:37,353 --> 00:57:38,555
What is this?

1600
00:57:39,989 --> 00:57:41,424
Look at the pasta noodles.

1601
00:57:41,925 --> 00:57:44,060
THEY CAN'T HELP BUT LAUGH

1602
00:57:44,127 --> 00:57:45,695
You could tie a person with this.

1603
00:57:46,262 --> 00:57:49,399
TIED UP WITH A NOODLE ROPE

1604
00:57:50,467 --> 00:57:52,502
-It's good.
-There's a nice chew to it.

1605
00:57:52,569 --> 00:57:53,937
-There is.
-Yes.

1606
00:57:54,904 --> 00:57:57,006
We have many Italian chefs here.

1607
00:57:57,073 --> 00:57:58,374
Any thoughts, Sung-jun?

1608
00:57:59,342 --> 00:58:00,176
One second.

1609
00:58:00,243 --> 00:58:01,377
ENJOYING THE CHEW

1610
00:58:01,444 --> 00:58:02,545
I have to chew for a while.

1611
00:58:02,846 --> 00:58:04,013
HAHA

1612
00:58:04,080 --> 00:58:05,215
Is it pasta, though?

1613
00:58:06,249 --> 00:58:09,519
Pasta…

1614
00:58:10,820 --> 00:58:12,555
-Are you okay?
-Pasta…

1615
00:58:12,622 --> 00:58:15,024
-Are you calling it? "Hey, Pasta."
-It seems like pasta.

1616
00:58:15,091 --> 00:58:18,061
I believe the biggest difference
between Chinese and Italian food is this.

1617
00:58:18,127 --> 00:58:21,397
I believe you don't use salt
when you cook the noodles, right?

1618
00:58:21,464 --> 00:58:23,132
-We don't use salt.
-No, right?

1619
00:58:23,199 --> 00:58:27,303
But for pasta, the water must be seasoned
before cooking pasta.

1620
00:58:28,304 --> 00:58:31,841
Without that, the pasta
doesn't mix with the sauce.

1621
00:58:32,275 --> 00:58:33,376
WHY DOES HE KEEP CHUCKLING?

1622
00:58:33,443 --> 00:58:34,878
-I think that's it.
-That's his take.

1623
00:58:34,944 --> 00:58:36,412
Why are you smiling, Hyun-suk?

1624
00:58:36,479 --> 00:58:37,514
It's the sole.

1625
00:58:38,948 --> 00:58:39,782
CHUCKLE

1626
00:58:40,517 --> 00:58:43,553
Was it made with a half-dried sole?

1627
00:58:43,620 --> 00:58:44,721
But it's good.

1628
00:58:44,787 --> 00:58:46,222
-It somehow tastes good.
-Half-dried?

1629
00:58:46,289 --> 00:58:48,625
Lastly, let's get Sam's take.

1630
00:58:48,691 --> 00:58:49,692
The pasta?

1631
00:58:50,493 --> 00:58:51,761
First of all…

1632
00:58:52,095 --> 00:58:53,296
NERVOUS

1633
00:58:53,363 --> 00:58:54,864
It was good.

1634
00:58:54,931 --> 00:58:55,832
But then,

1635
00:58:56,933 --> 00:58:58,434
the noodles reminded me

1636
00:58:58,501 --> 00:59:01,838
of those thin <i>tteokbokki</i> noodles.

1637
00:59:01,905 --> 00:59:04,908
-Yes, the noodle-shaped rice cake.
-The <i>tteokbokki</i> noodles.

1638
00:59:04,974 --> 00:59:07,143
She failed to adjust the thickness.

1639
00:59:07,210 --> 00:59:09,245
If it were thinner,

1640
00:59:09,312 --> 00:59:11,314
-it would've been nice and chewy.
-The texture is nice.

1641
00:59:11,381 --> 00:59:12,649
This one was too thick.

1642
00:59:12,715 --> 00:59:14,717
It's your turn to choose.

1643
00:59:14,784 --> 00:59:16,185
I've decided.

1644
00:59:16,252 --> 00:59:17,887
-What?
-He already pressed a button.

1645
00:59:17,954 --> 00:59:19,322
That was fast.

1646
00:59:19,389 --> 00:59:22,392
-I've already decided.
-You've made your decision? Okay.

1647
00:59:22,458 --> 00:59:23,993
Show us the result!

1648
00:59:24,861 --> 00:59:26,229
Culinary Darkness Wars.

1649
00:59:26,296 --> 00:59:29,999
Webtoon Artist Kim Poong suggested
they cook in the Genre Hell.

1650
00:59:30,066 --> 00:59:32,835
Did he choose Chef Hui-tae's Chinese food?

1651
00:59:32,902 --> 00:59:35,438
Or will it be Amy Park's Italian food?

1652
00:59:35,505 --> 00:59:38,541
Which one did he choose?

1653
00:59:38,608 --> 00:59:41,177
Show us the result!

1654
00:59:41,244 --> 00:59:42,412
WHO DID POONG CHOOSE?

1655
00:59:42,478 --> 00:59:43,713
Who won?

1656
00:59:43,780 --> 00:59:45,348
SAM KIM WINS

1657
00:59:45,415 --> 00:59:46,649
DARKNESS RESTAURANT WINS

1658
00:59:46,716 --> 00:59:48,217
Sam Kim wins.

1659
00:59:48,284 --> 00:59:49,552
-Great work.
-Hui-tae wins.

1660
00:59:49,619 --> 00:59:51,020
-Great work.
-Kim Hui-tae.

1661
00:59:52,155 --> 00:59:54,657
-The decisive factor was this.
-The decisive factor.

1662
00:59:54,724 --> 00:59:56,659
The pasta noodles

1663
00:59:56,726 --> 00:59:58,661
weren't seasoned properly.

1664
00:59:58,728 --> 01:00:00,530
I like to enjoy

1665
01:00:00,597 --> 01:00:04,867
the saltiness in the noodles
when I chew on pasta,

1666
01:00:04,934 --> 01:00:07,003
-but it didn't have that.
-The umami.

1667
01:00:07,070 --> 01:00:08,338
Also, Chef Sam's dish

1668
01:00:08,404 --> 01:00:10,773
was seasoned perfectly.

1669
01:00:10,840 --> 01:00:15,244
It wasn't too strong,
keeping the balance in the middle.

1670
01:00:15,311 --> 01:00:18,114
-It had a perfect balance.
-The balance in the middle.

1671
01:00:18,181 --> 01:00:21,417
Chef Sam wins their first cook-off.

1672
01:00:21,484 --> 01:00:24,053
Why don't we hear a word
from Chef Kim Hui-tae?

1673
01:00:24,120 --> 01:00:26,189
Whenever Poong cooked,

1674
01:00:26,255 --> 01:00:28,191
<i>I always told him off</i>

1675
01:00:28,257 --> 01:00:30,226
<i>for always deep-frying</i>
<i>and making chili oil.</i>

1676
01:00:30,293 --> 01:00:31,461
But now that I tried it,

1677
01:00:31,527 --> 01:00:33,329
I realized it wasn't easy.

1678
01:00:33,396 --> 01:00:37,634
It was a great opportunity
to appreciate what he does.

1679
01:00:38,201 --> 01:00:39,202
PLEASED

1680
01:00:39,268 --> 01:00:42,839
Sam Kim, aka Kim Hui-tae,
wins their first cook-off!

1681
01:00:42,905 --> 01:00:44,440
Please put a star on him.

1682
01:00:44,507 --> 01:00:46,009
-That was delicious.
-It was great.

1683
01:00:46,075 --> 01:00:46,943
After the first cook-off,

1684
01:00:47,543 --> 01:00:50,947
Chef Sam takes a star.

1685
01:00:51,014 --> 01:00:52,048
His second star.

1686
01:00:52,115 --> 01:00:54,083
-That wasn't easy.
-Congratulations!

1687
01:00:54,150 --> 01:00:55,752
-Congratulations!
-All right!

1688
01:00:55,818 --> 01:00:58,621
-Deep-frying really wasn't easy.
-That's a hard one.

1689
01:00:58,688 --> 01:01:02,592
<i>Let us begin the second cook-off</i>
<i>with Poong's ingredients.</i>

1690
01:01:02,659 --> 01:01:06,596
The good vibes chef of the show,
Son Jong-won,

1691
01:01:06,663 --> 01:01:09,098
versus the old vibes chef of the show,

1692
01:01:09,165 --> 01:01:11,234
-Choi Hyun-suk.
-Oh, man.

1693
01:01:11,300 --> 01:01:12,235
How unfortunate.

1694
01:01:12,301 --> 01:01:14,203
I get what good vibes mean, but old vibes?

1695
01:01:14,270 --> 01:01:15,371
WHAT DO YOU MEAN BY OLD VIBES?

1696
01:01:15,438 --> 01:01:17,407
-What is it?
-It's not "bad vibes,"

1697
01:01:17,473 --> 01:01:18,641
but "The old can still vibe."

1698
01:01:18,708 --> 01:01:21,177
-The old can still vibe.
-The old can still vibe.

1699
01:01:21,244 --> 01:01:24,013
<i>He had gone through</i>
<i>many adversities and trials</i>

1700
01:01:24,080 --> 01:01:26,749
<i>from his days as Tank Boy until this day.</i>

1701
01:01:26,816 --> 01:01:29,218
He got this far
while chomping on barley porridge.

1702
01:01:29,285 --> 01:01:31,754
-Barley porridge.
-"Do not run, kid. You'll get hungry."

1703
01:01:31,821 --> 01:01:35,324
That's how experienced he is.

1704
01:01:35,391 --> 01:01:38,227
These two great chefs are here
for a cook-off,

1705
01:01:38,294 --> 01:01:42,098
but the theme is quite poor and defective.

1706
01:01:42,165 --> 01:01:44,033
In this wonderful holiday,

1707
01:01:44,100 --> 01:01:47,537
why must they reinterpret
Poong's bizarre dishes?

1708
01:01:47,603 --> 01:01:49,272
RESUMMONING POONG'S BIZARRE DISHES

1709
01:01:49,338 --> 01:01:51,240
One thing we're thinking is this.

1710
01:01:51,307 --> 01:01:54,277
You and Chef Jong-won
just received the Best Couple Award,

1711
01:01:54,343 --> 01:01:58,614
so wouldn't he have the upper hand?
Any take on that?

1712
01:01:58,681 --> 01:02:03,619
I don't think there's anyone else
who value his dishes and admire them

1713
01:02:03,686 --> 01:02:06,055
-more than I do.
-No.

1714
01:02:06,122 --> 01:02:08,925
You laughed with him,
appreciated his food, and encouraged him.

1715
01:02:08,991 --> 01:02:11,494
<i>He's Poong's biggest fan.</i>

1716
01:02:11,561 --> 01:02:13,763
I can always see his intentions.

1717
01:02:13,830 --> 01:02:14,731
That's true.

1718
01:02:14,797 --> 01:02:18,000
-He was the only one who understood.
-I thought

1719
01:02:18,067 --> 01:02:21,170
I could probably add my techniques

1720
01:02:21,237 --> 01:02:23,940
and give life
to his great ideas and intentions.

1721
01:02:24,006 --> 01:02:26,175
-I'm going to be moved.
-I'll try to do that.

1722
01:02:26,242 --> 01:02:28,211
However, Chef Hyun-suk
spent many long years

1723
01:02:28,277 --> 01:02:30,980
watching Poong grow into a cook.

1724
01:02:31,047 --> 01:02:35,284
I know Chef Jong-won's affection
and respect for Poong

1725
01:02:35,351 --> 01:02:37,887
-are growing bigger and bigger.
-Yes?

1726
01:02:37,954 --> 01:02:41,557
But we've seen each other's dishes
throughout many long years.

1727
01:02:41,624 --> 01:02:44,627
He cooks so half-heartedly,
yet it tastes like my mom's food.

1728
01:02:46,095 --> 01:02:47,063
HE ALWAYS APPROVED OF HIM

1729
01:02:47,130 --> 01:02:48,831
Kim Poong's magic is real.

1730
01:02:49,599 --> 01:02:53,269
I'm sure I have a better understanding

1731
01:02:53,336 --> 01:02:56,105
of his expression through food.

1732
01:02:56,272 --> 01:02:57,206
THAT'S TRUE

1733
01:02:57,273 --> 01:02:59,876
He can probably tell
what Poong's intention is…

1734
01:02:59,942 --> 01:03:01,677
-Yes.
-…just by looking at his eyes.

1735
01:03:01,744 --> 01:03:03,379
He sees right through me.

1736
01:03:03,446 --> 01:03:05,114
No, I'm not that interested.

1737
01:03:07,650 --> 01:03:09,552
CHEF JONG-WON'S INGREDIENTS:
MELON, BREAD, MELON COOKIE SPREAD

1738
01:03:09,619 --> 01:03:11,721
PROSCIUTTO, CREAM CHEESE, PECORINO,
CUCUMBER, CHERRY TOMATO, AND MORE

1739
01:03:11,788 --> 01:03:14,490
Chef Jong-won, what are you making?

1740
01:03:14,557 --> 01:03:17,126
Today I prepared

1741
01:03:17,193 --> 01:03:19,462
this sunflower-shaped bowl.

1742
01:03:19,529 --> 01:03:20,897
A SUNFLOWER BOWL?

1743
01:03:20,963 --> 01:03:22,465
Because the name of my dish is…

1744
01:03:23,332 --> 01:03:26,169
-Poong Stan.
-Poong Stan, like a sunflower to the sun.

1745
01:03:26,235 --> 01:03:28,037
-Poong Stan.
-That was very direct.

1746
01:03:28,104 --> 01:03:29,205
How sweet of him.

1747
01:03:29,272 --> 01:03:30,573
He's so sweet.

1748
01:03:30,640 --> 01:03:32,241
What a sweet man!

1749
01:03:33,176 --> 01:03:36,646
I already love the name.

1750
01:03:37,079 --> 01:03:38,047
PROUD

1751
01:03:38,114 --> 01:03:40,950
I thought I was the type
who didn't like this kind of blatancy.

1752
01:03:41,017 --> 01:03:43,519
But I like it. I do.

1753
01:03:43,586 --> 01:03:45,655
What's the dish you want to reinterpret?

1754
01:03:45,721 --> 01:03:48,491
Dubai chewy cookies may have gone viral,
but Poong's melon fritters are better.

1755
01:03:48,558 --> 01:03:50,226
Poong's melon fritters.

1756
01:03:50,293 --> 01:03:51,327
-The melon fritters.
-The melon fritters?

1757
01:03:51,394 --> 01:03:53,596
-Poong's melon fritters.
-Poong's melon fritters.

1758
01:03:53,663 --> 01:03:55,698
I'll try to reinterpret
his melon fritters.

1759
01:03:56,098 --> 01:03:57,200
WOW

1760
01:03:57,266 --> 01:03:59,268
-They were already pretty nice.
-They were.

1761
01:03:59,335 --> 01:04:01,170
That was pretty much

1762
01:04:01,237 --> 01:04:03,172
-as best as I could do.
-Right?

1763
01:04:03,239 --> 01:04:06,008
But is he going to make it even better?

1764
01:04:06,075 --> 01:04:08,211
IT EVEN SURPRISED JONG-WON

1765
01:04:08,277 --> 01:04:10,513
Is it a melon dish worthy of fine dining?

1766
01:04:10,580 --> 01:04:14,116
Back then, he served melon sauce

1767
01:04:14,183 --> 01:04:17,420
-along with deep-fried meat and melon.
-Right.

1768
01:04:17,486 --> 01:04:19,856
As for the sauce,

1769
01:04:19,922 --> 01:04:23,793
I thought it'd be nice
if it were cool, sweet, yet savory,

1770
01:04:23,860 --> 01:04:26,329
-so I'll make gazpacho.
-Gazpacho.

1771
01:04:26,395 --> 01:04:28,164
-A Spanish soup.
-It's a Spanish dish.

1772
01:04:28,231 --> 01:04:29,799
Gazpacho and melon.

1773
01:04:29,866 --> 01:04:32,068
I'll add prosciutto
instead of deep-fried meat

1774
01:04:32,134 --> 01:04:34,003
and throw in some mint he had

1775
01:04:34,070 --> 01:04:35,638
to make the gazpacho.

1776
01:04:35,705 --> 01:04:40,042
Also, I'll use melon spread,
plain bread, and melon

1777
01:04:40,109 --> 01:04:42,445
to make melon fritters
without deep-frying.

1778
01:04:42,511 --> 01:04:44,614
-Melon fritters without deep-frying?
-Melon fritters without deep-frying?

1779
01:04:44,680 --> 01:04:47,416
Chef Jong-won's dish is called Poong Stan.

1780
01:04:48,251 --> 01:04:50,653
CHEF HYUN-SUK'S INGREDIENTS:
ABALONE, BACON, BUTTON MUSHROOM

1781
01:04:50,720 --> 01:04:52,421
BONE BROTH, PARMESAN,
DARK SOY SAUCE, TSUYU

1782
01:04:52,488 --> 01:04:54,790
I'm looking forward
to hearing what Hyun-suk will make.

1783
01:04:54,857 --> 01:04:57,193
The name of my dish is this.

1784
01:04:58,261 --> 01:05:00,329
Choi Loach.

1785
01:05:00,396 --> 01:05:01,597
-Choi Loach?
-Choi Loach?

1786
01:05:01,664 --> 01:05:02,832
He's going for the dung loach.

1787
01:05:04,100 --> 01:05:06,369
-Is he going there?
-The dung loaches?

1788
01:05:06,435 --> 01:05:07,436
It won't be easy.

1789
01:05:07,503 --> 01:05:09,205
-This is huge.
-The dung loach.

1790
01:05:09,772 --> 01:05:11,207
It was his dish called

1791
01:05:11,274 --> 01:05:14,610
-C-C-C-C-C-C-C-Crazy Soup.
-That's right.

1792
01:05:14,677 --> 01:05:17,213
The key to this dish wasn't the soup.

1793
01:05:17,280 --> 01:05:19,415
It was the loaches he made.

1794
01:05:19,482 --> 01:05:21,817
-Yes.
-People didn't think they were loaches.

1795
01:05:21,884 --> 01:05:23,986
They remember it as dung.

1796
01:05:24,053 --> 01:05:27,023
Someone kept saying
that we have to flush the pan,

1797
01:05:27,089 --> 01:05:28,891
-so it became dung loaches.
-That was rough.

1798
01:05:28,958 --> 01:05:32,161
I think that guy
wanted to make it look like loaches.

1799
01:05:32,228 --> 01:05:34,563
So I'll make perfect loaches

1800
01:05:34,630 --> 01:05:37,566
into pasta with perfect texture.

1801
01:05:37,633 --> 01:05:40,336
Then, I'll serve it
with the simplest carbonara sauce

1802
01:05:40,403 --> 01:05:43,706
and turn them into loaches, not dung.

1803
01:05:43,773 --> 01:05:46,809
I want to reinterpret it
as carbonara pasta.

1804
01:05:46,876 --> 01:05:50,846
He'll upgrade the dung loaches
into carbonara pasta.

1805
01:05:50,913 --> 01:05:55,217
Let's begin the next round,
"Kim Poong Paradise."

1806
01:05:55,284 --> 01:05:56,986
-I'm excited.
-In this New Year's holiday,

1807
01:05:57,053 --> 01:05:59,755
he does not want to miss out
on Poong's star.

1808
01:05:59,822 --> 01:06:02,091
Poong's biggest stan, Chef Son Jong-won.

1809
01:06:02,158 --> 01:06:05,094
But this guy does not want
to miss a chance to win a star, period.

1810
01:06:05,161 --> 01:06:08,164
The biggest star hunter,
Chef Choi Hyun-suk.

1811
01:06:08,230 --> 01:06:11,434
Which one of them
will lead Poong into paradise?

1812
01:06:11,500 --> 01:06:14,370
Let the 15-minute cook-off begin!

1813
01:06:14,971 --> 01:06:16,672
OFF TO PARADISE

1814
01:06:16,739 --> 01:06:17,807
You got this!

1815
01:06:17,873 --> 01:06:21,377
This is a huge battle for the holidays.

1816
01:06:21,444 --> 01:06:22,645
The freezer.

1817
01:06:22,712 --> 01:06:23,546
HE GRABS ICE!

1818
01:06:24,413 --> 01:06:28,150
<i>He looks way too cool</i>
<i>when his hair flutters.</i>

1819
01:06:29,652 --> 01:06:30,920
My gosh.

1820
01:06:30,987 --> 01:06:34,256
-Abalone?
-First, Hyun-suk grabs abalones.

1821
01:06:34,323 --> 01:06:36,325
-Oh, abalone innards.
-Yes.

1822
01:06:36,392 --> 01:06:40,029
I created the color of the loach
with abalone innards.

1823
01:06:40,096 --> 01:06:41,664
-I used the innards.
-I see.

1824
01:06:41,731 --> 01:06:43,833
-You added it into the dough.
-I did.

1825
01:06:43,899 --> 01:06:46,035
I think that's <i>tsuyu.</i>

1826
01:06:46,102 --> 01:06:47,770
That's dark soy sauce.

1827
01:06:47,837 --> 01:06:50,506
Dark soy sauce. Chinese dark soy sauce.

1828
01:06:50,573 --> 01:06:52,975
That color was the cause
of the huge misunderstanding.

1829
01:06:53,042 --> 01:06:55,244
That color is coming out.

1830
01:06:55,311 --> 01:06:57,413
-Just like that?
-Without the innards?

1831
01:06:57,480 --> 01:07:00,116
It's in there.
You can't make that color without it.

1832
01:07:01,117 --> 01:07:03,652
-He knows exactly what needs to be done.
-Yes.

1833
01:07:03,719 --> 01:07:05,654
He's getting the color right.

1834
01:07:05,721 --> 01:07:08,257
He's going for the perfect color.

1835
01:07:08,324 --> 01:07:11,427
If he's going to make dung loaches,
he'll make sure it's in the right color.

1836
01:07:11,494 --> 01:07:12,828
THE C-C-C-C-C-CRAZY COLOR

1837
01:07:12,895 --> 01:07:13,796
GREAT!

1838
01:07:13,863 --> 01:07:15,197
The color is already…

1839
01:07:15,264 --> 01:07:16,832
IT'S DEFINITELY "THAT" COLOR

1840
01:07:16,899 --> 01:07:18,968
-Goodness.
-Whoa.

1841
01:07:19,035 --> 01:07:20,636
I like it. Nice color.

1842
01:07:20,703 --> 01:07:22,671
-Just like soybean blocks.
-It looks the same.

1843
01:07:22,838 --> 01:07:24,507
MELON FRITTERS PITTED AGAINST "IT"!

1844
01:07:24,573 --> 01:07:27,276
I want to see how he peels the melon.

1845
01:07:27,343 --> 01:07:31,213
-Melon fritters that aren't deep-fried.
-I see.

1846
01:07:31,280 --> 01:07:33,983
-Quite different, isn't it?
-That's how you peel a melon?

1847
01:07:34,050 --> 01:07:36,419
-That's how you peel it?
-It's much easier.

1848
01:07:36,485 --> 01:07:37,686
You didn't do that, right?

1849
01:07:37,753 --> 01:07:40,523
No, I didn't know how to do it.

1850
01:07:40,990 --> 01:07:42,124
Didn't you cut it in half?

1851
01:07:42,191 --> 01:07:44,560
Yes, I cut it in half and stuff.

1852
01:07:44,627 --> 01:07:46,529
Who cuts a melon like that?

1853
01:07:46,595 --> 01:07:48,764
Then how do you do it?
I don't know. Tell me.

1854
01:07:48,831 --> 01:07:51,634
-That's how you peel it?
-It's much easier.

1855
01:07:51,700 --> 01:07:53,602
-That was quick.
-That seems so easy.

1856
01:07:53,669 --> 01:07:55,304
That was so easy to peel.

1857
01:07:55,371 --> 01:07:56,705
REMOVING THE SKIN AND SEEDS

1858
01:07:56,772 --> 01:07:59,241
He just removed the seeds.

1859
01:07:59,308 --> 01:08:02,344
He just tried some melon. What's it like?

1860
01:08:02,411 --> 01:08:04,880
It isn't as sweet as I thought,
so I'm a bit troubled.

1861
01:08:04,947 --> 01:08:05,915
-It's not sweet?
-It's not.

1862
01:08:05,981 --> 01:08:07,349
-It's an emergency.
-It's an emergency.

1863
01:08:07,416 --> 01:08:08,384
It's an emergency.

1864
01:08:08,451 --> 01:08:09,785
Turn on the light.

1865
01:08:09,852 --> 01:08:11,554
-What?
-Turn the beacon light on.

1866
01:08:11,620 --> 01:08:12,888
He wants the beacon light on.

1867
01:08:12,955 --> 01:08:14,056
Not yet.

1868
01:08:14,390 --> 01:08:15,458
ROLLING

1869
01:08:15,524 --> 01:08:17,193
What's he doing?

1870
01:08:17,259 --> 01:08:18,727
He's making the loaches!

1871
01:08:18,794 --> 01:08:21,330
-The loaches.
-Just like that?

1872
01:08:21,397 --> 01:08:23,466
He's shaping them into loaches.

1873
01:08:24,166 --> 01:08:26,669
I had made thinner batter,

1874
01:08:26,735 --> 01:08:28,237
but he made pasta dough.

1875
01:08:28,304 --> 01:08:30,539
-It's drier.
-It is.

1876
01:08:30,606 --> 01:08:33,642
Aren't they too thin, though?
They look like worms.

1877
01:08:33,709 --> 01:08:34,577
Those are worms.

1878
01:08:34,643 --> 01:08:36,879
He's shaping their heads.

1879
01:08:36,946 --> 01:08:38,114
Wait, the loaches…

1880
01:08:38,180 --> 01:08:40,416
These are baby loaches.

1881
01:08:40,983 --> 01:08:42,651
-The head.
-They look like real loaches.

1882
01:08:42,718 --> 01:08:44,286
THE TAILS BECOME SHARPER!

1883
01:08:44,353 --> 01:08:46,655
He's shaping them into loaches.

1884
01:08:46,722 --> 01:08:48,691
-It's detailed.
-Yes.

1885
01:08:48,757 --> 01:08:50,926
Hyun-suk begins to shape the noodles.

1886
01:08:50,993 --> 01:08:52,194
That's a loach soup.

1887
01:08:52,261 --> 01:08:53,696
Are those planarians?

1888
01:08:53,996 --> 01:08:56,031
THE ORIGINAL CREATOR IS PLEASED

1889
01:08:56,098 --> 01:08:57,733
He puts in detailed work.

1890
01:08:57,800 --> 01:09:00,069
PINCHING TO MAKE FINS!

1891
01:09:00,136 --> 01:09:02,471
-I guess his hands aren't trembling.
-They aren't.

1892
01:09:02,538 --> 01:09:03,539
-He's not trembling.
-He's fine.

1893
01:09:03,606 --> 01:09:05,708
I think he created the fins on the loach.

1894
01:09:05,774 --> 01:09:07,009
-Wow.
-I see.

1895
01:09:07,243 --> 01:09:09,345
FINISHED MAKING THE LOACHES!

1896
01:09:09,411 --> 01:09:11,247
You have 11 minutes left.

1897
01:09:11,514 --> 01:09:14,116
JONG-WON MUST MAKE FRITTER BATTER

1898
01:09:14,183 --> 01:09:17,319
That's one of his signature moves.
The flower mold.

1899
01:09:17,386 --> 01:09:19,421
I want to bring out
the texture of this bread.

1900
01:09:19,488 --> 01:09:20,890
Are you going to deep-fry that?

1901
01:09:20,956 --> 01:09:22,658
-Is that butter?
-Cream cheese.

1902
01:09:22,725 --> 01:09:25,561
He's spreading cream cheese on bread.

1903
01:09:25,628 --> 01:09:27,863
It's for a mix of sweet and salty.

1904
01:09:27,930 --> 01:09:30,966
He's going to top it with melon
and deep-fry the whole thing.

1905
01:09:31,033 --> 01:09:32,201
He puts melon on top.

1906
01:09:32,268 --> 01:09:34,537
-I'll grate some cheese on it.
-Cheese.

1907
01:09:34,603 --> 01:09:35,638
He tops it with cheese.

1908
01:09:35,704 --> 01:09:36,772
Cheese on top?

1909
01:09:36,839 --> 01:09:38,040
MUCH MORE LAYERS
THAN POONG'S MELON FRITTERS

1910
01:09:38,107 --> 01:09:40,743
Nothing is as addictive
as something sweet and salty.

1911
01:09:40,809 --> 01:09:42,278
A bit of salt.

1912
01:09:42,344 --> 01:09:44,480
And he's going to cover it.

1913
01:09:45,714 --> 01:09:49,118
Jong-won is working hard
on the shape of the fritter.

1914
01:09:49,185 --> 01:09:51,520
He just put the melon
between two pieces of bread.

1915
01:09:51,587 --> 01:09:53,522
<i>-Menbosha?</i>
<i>-Menbosha?</i>

1916
01:09:53,589 --> 01:09:56,258
<i>-Menbosha?</i>
-It's just like <i>menbosha.</i>

1917
01:09:56,325 --> 01:09:58,127
He's using bread.

1918
01:09:58,194 --> 01:09:59,528
He's applying something on top.

1919
01:09:59,595 --> 01:10:01,964
-That's one of my favorites.
-What is it?

1920
01:10:02,031 --> 01:10:05,234
-It's the melon cookie spread.
-The melon spread.

1921
01:10:05,301 --> 01:10:07,136
-It's the melon spread.
-Is that good?

1922
01:10:07,203 --> 01:10:08,671
-It must taste like melons too.
-It's good.

1923
01:10:09,572 --> 01:10:11,240
He's coating it generously.

1924
01:10:11,307 --> 01:10:13,776
I'll brush it with some egg wash.

1925
01:10:13,842 --> 01:10:15,644
I told you that I wouldn't deep-fry it

1926
01:10:15,711 --> 01:10:18,447
-because I'm using an air fryer.
-I see!

1927
01:10:18,514 --> 01:10:20,449
-He's using an air fryer.
-Using the air fryer!

1928
01:10:20,516 --> 01:10:23,219
That'll make the bread crispy
and melt the cheese.

1929
01:10:23,285 --> 01:10:26,889
But wouldn't the melon inside
give off some juice?

1930
01:10:26,956 --> 01:10:28,924
Is that okay?
Wouldn't it make the bread soggy?

1931
01:10:28,991 --> 01:10:30,859
Melons are more delicious when grilled,

1932
01:10:30,926 --> 01:10:34,763
-and it becomes sweeter with some salt.
-I see.

1933
01:10:34,830 --> 01:10:37,333
If that turns out nicely,
viewers can copy the recipe too.

1934
01:10:37,399 --> 01:10:39,168
SET AT 180°C FOR 6 MINUTES

1935
01:10:39,802 --> 01:10:41,604
Let me borrow the cheese grater.

1936
01:10:41,670 --> 01:10:43,105
-Cheese.
-Cheese.

1937
01:10:43,172 --> 01:10:45,140
-Cheese.
-He'll grate a huge pile.

1938
01:10:45,207 --> 01:10:46,308
He's making carbonara.

1939
01:10:46,609 --> 01:10:47,943
EGGS

1940
01:10:48,877 --> 01:10:52,481
2. MIX PARMESAN, EGG YOLK, GROUND PEPPER,
AND BONE BROTH TO MAKE THE SAUCE

1941
01:10:53,782 --> 01:10:57,253
Chef Hyun-suk makes carbonara sauce.

1942
01:10:58,654 --> 01:10:59,588
What's that?

1943
01:10:59,655 --> 01:11:01,156
-Bacon, I think.
-Is that bacon?

1944
01:11:01,223 --> 01:11:02,691
-A bacon slab.
-A slab of bacon.

1945
01:11:02,758 --> 01:11:05,327
A bacon slab, not ham.
He needs it to make carbonara

1946
01:11:05,394 --> 01:11:06,895
-instead of using ham.
-Instead of ham.

1947
01:11:07,363 --> 01:11:08,564
BUTTER

1948
01:11:08,631 --> 01:11:12,635
He said he'd upgrade the dung loaches
into carbonara pasta.

1949
01:11:12,701 --> 01:11:13,936
-Onions?
-Eight minutes.

1950
01:11:14,003 --> 01:11:16,572
This is quite moving.

1951
01:11:16,639 --> 01:11:18,874
I can't believe
they're working with my recipe.

1952
01:11:18,941 --> 01:11:21,744
I mean, my dishes aren't a big deal,
but they're putting in lots of work.

1953
01:11:21,810 --> 01:11:23,078
JONG-WON DICES AN ONION

1954
01:11:23,145 --> 01:11:24,313
Onion? Right.

1955
01:11:24,380 --> 01:11:26,048
-Why does he need that?
-Onion? Why?

1956
01:11:26,115 --> 01:11:27,249
The onion is…

1957
01:11:27,316 --> 01:11:29,118
Jong-won dices the onion.

1958
01:11:29,184 --> 01:11:31,520
-It's for the gazpacho.
-Gazpacho.

1959
01:11:32,254 --> 01:11:33,722
He grabs a cucumber.

1960
01:11:33,789 --> 01:11:36,392
Gazpacho is mostly made with cucumbers,

1961
01:11:36,458 --> 01:11:39,928
and cucumbers have
a similar flavor note to melons.

1962
01:11:39,995 --> 01:11:42,798
I think he saw through
my deepest intentions.

1963
01:11:42,865 --> 01:11:44,066
NODS

1964
01:11:44,133 --> 01:11:46,135
He removes the skin and the seeds.

1965
01:11:46,902 --> 01:11:49,672
You're right. He removes the cucumber skin

1966
01:11:50,239 --> 01:11:51,373
and the seeds too.

1967
01:11:51,440 --> 01:11:52,941
ALSO DICED JUST LIKE THE ONION

1968
01:11:53,409 --> 01:11:55,511
HE UNDERSTOOD WHAT I HAD INTENDED…

1969
01:11:55,577 --> 01:11:57,379
ENOUGH IS ENOUGH, BOYS!

1970
01:11:57,746 --> 01:11:59,214
SALTING THE PASTA WATER!

1971
01:11:59,481 --> 01:12:00,582
OH, THAT'S HOW IT'S DONE!

1972
01:12:03,152 --> 01:12:05,387
-The dung loaches went in.
-The dung loaches are in?

1973
01:12:05,854 --> 01:12:07,056
DUNG LOACHES?

1974
01:12:07,122 --> 01:12:08,424
-Choi Loach.
-Choi Loach.

1975
01:12:08,490 --> 01:12:10,492
-Yes, those are Choi Loaches.
-Choi Loach.

1976
01:12:10,559 --> 01:12:14,396
At a quick glance,
it seems like there are fish inside.

1977
01:12:14,463 --> 01:12:16,365
-My gosh.
-It's like a fish bowl.

1978
01:12:16,999 --> 01:12:19,902
I can kind of see the loaches.

1979
01:12:20,169 --> 01:12:22,404
DRIPPING ON THE SIDE!

1980
01:12:22,471 --> 01:12:23,939
A loach is getting out of the pan.

1981
01:12:24,006 --> 01:12:25,607
He should flush now.

1982
01:12:25,674 --> 01:12:27,242
THE MEMORIES WE WANT TO FLUSH AWAY

1983
01:12:27,309 --> 01:12:28,577
Chef Jong-won, are you crying?

1984
01:12:28,644 --> 01:12:30,179
A SHOCKING VISUAL THAT BROUGHT TEARS!

1985
01:12:30,245 --> 01:12:32,648
There's a clear distinction
from what you made.

1986
01:12:32,715 --> 01:12:34,650
-It's different.
-It's a different dish.

1987
01:12:34,717 --> 01:12:38,420
Last time, we wanted to flush the pan
as soon as the loaches went in.

1988
01:12:38,487 --> 01:12:41,423
-But this one looks like a fish bowl.
-You're right.

1989
01:12:41,490 --> 01:12:43,025
It's like Americanized carbonara.

1990
01:12:43,092 --> 01:12:44,827
BUTTER, BACON, ONION

1991
01:12:45,227 --> 01:12:47,963
JONG-WON STARTS MAKING GAZPACHO

1992
01:12:48,964 --> 01:12:51,700
Six minutes. Six minutes and ten seconds.

1993
01:12:51,767 --> 01:12:54,570
I'll make the gazpacho thicker
by adding some bread.

1994
01:12:54,636 --> 01:12:56,505
-Bread?
-I want to give it some texture.

1995
01:12:56,572 --> 01:12:58,374
In the gazpacho?

1996
01:12:58,440 --> 01:12:59,742
Oh, it's melon gazpacho.

1997
01:12:59,808 --> 01:13:02,044
It's usually made with tomatoes

1998
01:13:02,111 --> 01:13:03,412
and red wine vinegar.

1999
01:13:03,479 --> 01:13:05,781
He's adding savory ingredients,
such as tomatoes.

2000
01:13:05,848 --> 01:13:08,951
I'm a bit worried about the color.

2001
01:13:09,017 --> 01:13:10,953
Honey. And Tabasco.

2002
01:13:11,019 --> 01:13:12,621
He's adding honey too.

2003
01:13:12,688 --> 01:13:13,856
Will he blend everything?

2004
01:13:13,922 --> 01:13:15,023
I will.

2005
01:13:15,090 --> 01:13:18,227
I wonder what it'll taste like.
He's using a melon.

2006
01:13:20,095 --> 01:13:21,130
-What?
-It's not working.

2007
01:13:21,196 --> 01:13:22,865
-It's not working.
-It's not working.

2008
01:13:23,098 --> 01:13:23,932
OH, NO

2009
01:13:23,999 --> 01:13:26,034
It's an emergency. You have to check.

2010
01:13:26,101 --> 01:13:28,904
Five minutes!
Please go to the kitchen, Jung-hwan.

2011
01:13:30,038 --> 01:13:31,340
It's an emergency.

2012
01:13:31,407 --> 01:13:32,674
RETRY

2013
01:13:32,741 --> 01:13:34,376
IT WORKS!

2014
01:13:34,443 --> 01:13:35,944
-It's working.
-It's working.

2015
01:13:36,011 --> 01:13:37,413
THAT'S GOOD

2016
01:13:38,347 --> 01:13:39,448
-It's blending nicely.
-It worked.

2017
01:13:39,515 --> 01:13:41,083
EMERGENCY ALERT DISABLED

2018
01:13:41,150 --> 01:13:44,720
It looks like Choi Loaches
are slowly floating.

2019
01:13:44,787 --> 01:13:46,422
They're floating.

2020
01:13:46,488 --> 01:13:48,290
-They're on the surface.
-They're rising up.

2021
01:13:48,690 --> 01:13:49,925
HORRIFIED

2022
01:13:49,992 --> 01:13:51,593
It's starting to look odd.

2023
01:13:51,660 --> 01:13:53,729
They remind me of tadpoles.

2024
01:13:54,062 --> 01:13:55,464
GRABS ONE!

2025
01:13:56,265 --> 01:13:58,434
Jung-hwan, do you want to try one?

2026
01:13:58,500 --> 01:14:00,436
No, he doesn't have too many of them.

2027
01:14:00,502 --> 01:14:02,504
-No?
-No, Poong needs all these.

2028
01:14:02,571 --> 01:14:03,439
They're cute.

2029
01:14:03,505 --> 01:14:05,140
-Yes.
-They look cute.

2030
01:14:05,207 --> 01:14:08,777
-Compared to back then…
-It's different when a chef does it.

2031
01:14:08,844 --> 01:14:12,347
It looks like
tiny little geckos are swimming.

2032
01:14:12,414 --> 01:14:14,716
He takes out the loaches.

2033
01:14:14,783 --> 01:14:18,053
-He's now stir-frying those with bacon.
-Yes.

2034
01:14:18,120 --> 01:14:21,056
I think those loaches
are supposed to be the noodles.

2035
01:14:21,123 --> 01:14:22,991
The loaches turned into pasta.

2036
01:14:23,058 --> 01:14:24,693
Carbonara.

2037
01:14:24,760 --> 01:14:26,128
It's becoming carbonara pasta.

2038
01:14:27,529 --> 01:14:28,497
What about him?

2039
01:14:28,564 --> 01:14:30,732
I want to add some mint to the gazpacho.

2040
01:14:30,799 --> 01:14:33,202
Jong-won adds more details, as always.

2041
01:14:33,769 --> 01:14:37,239
5. ADD APPLE MINT TO MELON GAZPACHO
AND CONTINUE TO BLEND

2042
01:14:37,739 --> 01:14:39,341
WHAT WILL IT TASTE LIKE?

2043
01:14:39,408 --> 01:14:40,442
TASTING

2044
01:14:40,509 --> 01:14:41,844
SOMETHING IS MISSING

2045
01:14:41,910 --> 01:14:44,446
-He's adding more honey.
-Honey.

2046
01:14:44,513 --> 01:14:45,881
The melon I have isn't too sweet.

2047
01:14:45,948 --> 01:14:47,783
Because the melon isn't sweet?

2048
01:14:47,850 --> 01:14:49,051
It was still hard.

2049
01:14:49,117 --> 01:14:52,154
-It hadn't ripened yet.
-No.

2050
01:14:53,021 --> 01:14:55,290
GROUND PEPPER, OLIVE OIL

2051
01:14:56,291 --> 01:14:58,260
MELON GAZPACHO!

2052
01:14:58,327 --> 01:15:00,362
Three minutes.

2053
01:15:01,897 --> 01:15:03,465
-What's that?
-Button mushrooms.

2054
01:15:03,532 --> 01:15:05,734
-Those slices look pretty.
-They do.

2055
01:15:05,801 --> 01:15:07,736
Is he making that with button mushrooms?

2056
01:15:07,803 --> 01:15:11,907
He did that with button mushrooms?
My gosh. With mushrooms?

2057
01:15:12,674 --> 01:15:15,377
Hyun-suk begins to plate his dish.

2058
01:15:16,979 --> 01:15:18,247
Just like that.

2059
01:15:18,313 --> 01:15:19,982
He's now plating his pasta.

2060
01:15:20,048 --> 01:15:22,851
I can't believe these two chefs

2061
01:15:22,918 --> 01:15:25,721
are moving about busily
trying to reinterpret Poong's dishes.

2062
01:15:25,787 --> 01:15:27,923
We're wasting their talent.

2063
01:15:27,990 --> 01:15:29,291
-It's funny.
-Two minutes and a half.

2064
01:15:29,358 --> 01:15:30,325
I'm moved.

2065
01:15:30,826 --> 01:15:33,662
Do you need something else?

2066
01:15:33,729 --> 01:15:35,831
The sauce became too thick.

2067
01:15:35,898 --> 01:15:37,933
The thickness isn't quite there.

2068
01:15:38,433 --> 01:15:40,269
THE AIR FRYER BEEPS AFTER 6 MINUTES

2069
01:15:40,335 --> 01:15:41,403
What was that?

2070
01:15:41,470 --> 01:15:42,304
HOW DID THEY TURN OUT?

2071
01:15:42,371 --> 01:15:44,339
-The fritters are done.
-The air fryer.

2072
01:15:44,406 --> 01:15:46,141
-It looks good.
-That looks good.

2073
01:15:46,208 --> 01:15:48,343
-It's like melon bread.
-It's melon bread.

2074
01:15:48,410 --> 01:15:49,745
It's melon bread.

2075
01:15:50,112 --> 01:15:51,380
JONG-WON'S MELON FRITTERS ARE DONE!

2076
01:15:51,446 --> 01:15:52,948
They look deliciously golden.

2077
01:15:53,015 --> 01:15:55,250
It smells like a bakery.

2078
01:15:55,317 --> 01:15:57,019
I can smell the melon.

2079
01:15:57,219 --> 01:15:58,687
UPGRADE COMPLETE!

2080
01:15:59,221 --> 01:16:00,455
DICED ONION AND CUCUMBER

2081
01:16:00,923 --> 01:16:02,925
6. MIX IT WITH BALSAMIC VINEGAR,
OLIVE OIL, SALT, PEPPER, HONEY

2082
01:16:03,759 --> 01:16:04,793
SALT, PEPPER

2083
01:16:05,827 --> 01:16:08,230
The melon bread looks deliciously golden.

2084
01:16:08,730 --> 01:16:10,332
LASTLY, WHAT ELSE DOES HE NEED?

2085
01:16:10,399 --> 01:16:13,936
-He needs the bowl. Under two minutes.
-Jong-won begins to plate it too.

2086
01:16:14,002 --> 01:16:15,304
You have under two minutes.

2087
01:16:16,505 --> 01:16:18,941
Is that the sunflower bowl?

2088
01:16:19,007 --> 01:16:21,109
-The Poong Stan bowl.
-The Poong Stan bowl.

2089
01:16:21,176 --> 01:16:22,311
It's ready.

2090
01:16:22,377 --> 01:16:23,879
-Should I try that melon soup?
-Okay.

2091
01:16:23,946 --> 01:16:26,315
Look at the time.

2092
01:16:26,381 --> 01:16:27,282
A minute and 20 seconds.

2093
01:16:27,349 --> 01:16:30,686
Two minutes left.
I think Chef Hyun-suk is almost done.

2094
01:16:30,752 --> 01:16:32,087
He's moving quickly.

2095
01:16:32,154 --> 01:16:33,589
I wonder what it's like.

2096
01:16:33,655 --> 01:16:34,489
What's this like?

2097
01:16:34,556 --> 01:16:37,693
Can we eat button mushrooms raw?

2098
01:16:37,759 --> 01:16:39,361
-You can.
-I can?

2099
01:16:39,428 --> 01:16:42,331
-Button mushrooms.
-He decorates it with mushrooms.

2100
01:16:42,397 --> 01:16:44,366
These are thin button mushroom slices.

2101
01:16:44,433 --> 01:16:46,201
Look at them go.

2102
01:16:47,369 --> 01:16:49,237
-Chef Hyun-suk finishes!
-You're done already?

2103
01:16:49,304 --> 01:16:51,740
He finishes
with a minute and ten seconds left.

2104
01:16:51,807 --> 01:16:53,075
Let me try this one.

2105
01:16:53,141 --> 01:16:54,977
PROSCIUTTO

2106
01:16:55,377 --> 01:16:57,145
CHECKING THE MELON GAZPACHO

2107
01:16:57,212 --> 01:16:58,113
FLINCHES

2108
01:16:58,180 --> 01:16:59,781
-Huh?
-What's it like?

2109
01:16:59,848 --> 01:17:01,516
It's tough to imagine what it's like.

2110
01:17:01,583 --> 01:17:03,018
Yes, it's unimaginable.

2111
01:17:03,085 --> 01:17:04,820
-Why?
-What's it like?

2112
01:17:04,886 --> 01:17:06,922
It was sweet, but toward the end,

2113
01:17:06,989 --> 01:17:08,123
it's kind of spicy.

2114
01:17:08,190 --> 01:17:09,191
Tabasco.

2115
01:17:09,257 --> 01:17:11,093
-Really?
-It must be the Tabasco.

2116
01:17:11,159 --> 01:17:12,427
Must be.

2117
01:17:12,494 --> 01:17:13,996
It's odd. I've never had anything like it.

2118
01:17:14,062 --> 01:17:15,764
I see. He has never had anything like it.

2119
01:17:15,831 --> 01:17:17,466
-Forty seconds.
-Yes.

2120
01:17:17,532 --> 01:17:18,934
It's very artistic.

2121
01:17:19,001 --> 01:17:20,502
8. TOP GAZPACHO WITH PROSCIUTTO AND MINT

2122
01:17:20,569 --> 01:17:22,170
Hyun-suk is done.

2123
01:17:22,237 --> 01:17:23,839
We're waiting for Jong-won to finish.

2124
01:17:23,905 --> 01:17:24,806
GROUND PEPPER ON THE BOARD

2125
01:17:25,307 --> 01:17:28,010
A SPRINKLE WITH HIS FINGERS!

2126
01:17:28,644 --> 01:17:30,979
ALL HE NEEDS ARE THE MELON FRITTERS!

2127
01:17:32,481 --> 01:17:34,716
Ten seconds.

2128
01:17:34,783 --> 01:17:36,218
-Eight. Seven.
-Seven.

2129
01:17:36,284 --> 01:17:38,253
-Six. Five.
-Six. Five.

2130
01:17:38,320 --> 01:17:40,455
THE LAST KICK?

2131
01:17:40,522 --> 01:17:42,924
9. TOP IT OFF WITH PROSCIUTTO

2132
01:17:42,991 --> 01:17:44,026
Time's up.

2133
01:17:44,092 --> 01:17:45,527
Jong-won finishes too.

2134
01:17:46,094 --> 01:17:47,796
Goodness. Until the last second.

2135
01:17:49,364 --> 01:17:51,433
Both dishes are ready.

2136
01:17:51,500 --> 01:17:53,902
UPGRADED FROM BIZARRE TO MASTERPIECES

2137
01:17:55,137 --> 01:17:59,541
Both dishes are finished for Poong,

2138
01:17:59,608 --> 01:18:02,044
the reinterpretations of his dishes.

2139
01:18:02,110 --> 01:18:04,046
-Chef Hyun-suk finished first.
-Yes.

2140
01:18:04,112 --> 01:18:05,647
-Choi Loach.
-Please stay seated.

2141
01:18:05,714 --> 01:18:07,182
Yes, right.

2142
01:18:07,983 --> 01:18:10,919
CHOI HYUN-SUK'S REINTERPRETATION
OF C-C-C-C-C-C-C-CRAZY SOUP

2143
01:18:11,853 --> 01:18:14,990
HIDDEN UNDERNEATH BUTTON MUSHROOM SLICES

2144
01:18:15,691 --> 01:18:18,860
CHEF CHOI HYUN-SUK'S CHOI LOACH

2145
01:18:19,194 --> 01:18:20,028
SERVER SAM

2146
01:18:20,095 --> 01:18:21,329
Choi Loach.

2147
01:18:21,396 --> 01:18:26,601
I remember how shocked
Jun-hwan was back then.

2148
01:18:26,668 --> 01:18:27,836
-He was shocked.
-Right?

2149
01:18:27,903 --> 01:18:29,871
After seeing this,

2150
01:18:29,938 --> 01:18:33,408
I feel even worse for what I made for him.

2151
01:18:33,475 --> 01:18:36,545
-Right?
-He should've had this,

2152
01:18:36,611 --> 01:18:39,448
and I probably should've had mine.

2153
01:18:39,514 --> 01:18:40,482
How's the presentation?

2154
01:18:41,149 --> 01:18:43,618
When you go to a stream
where loaches live,

2155
01:18:43,685 --> 01:18:47,022
-you can see water lilies on the surface.
-Or lotuses.

2156
01:18:47,089 --> 01:18:49,758
And you can see loaches playing
beneath the flowers.

2157
01:18:49,825 --> 01:18:50,692
Lots of loaches.

2158
01:18:50,759 --> 01:18:53,695
I think that was your intention.

2159
01:18:53,762 --> 01:18:56,431
My artistic ability must have led the dish

2160
01:18:56,498 --> 01:18:57,799
in that direction.

2161
01:18:57,866 --> 01:18:59,134
That might be the case.

2162
01:18:59,201 --> 01:19:01,570
He won't deny it.

2163
01:19:01,636 --> 01:19:03,672
-He must've liked it.
-Scoop one up.

2164
01:19:03,739 --> 01:19:06,541
I'll try it. Where are you, loaches?

2165
01:19:07,275 --> 01:19:08,677
A HUGE CATCH

2166
01:19:08,744 --> 01:19:10,946
-They were hiding underneath.
-It looks so firm.

2167
01:19:11,012 --> 01:19:13,582
Look at this loach.

2168
01:19:13,648 --> 01:19:15,584
-It's in season.
-So fresh.

2169
01:19:15,650 --> 01:19:17,586
You must've caught it just now.

2170
01:19:17,652 --> 01:19:19,087
Let me see your face.

2171
01:19:19,154 --> 01:19:20,689
I caught two, actually.

2172
01:19:20,756 --> 01:19:22,657
-You caught two?
-They must be an item.

2173
01:19:22,724 --> 01:19:23,892
Double loach.

2174
01:19:23,959 --> 01:19:26,595
It reminds me of loach soup too.

2175
01:19:26,661 --> 01:19:28,797
-Try the double loach.
-Let me try the double loach.

2176
01:19:28,864 --> 01:19:29,831
Two loaches.

2177
01:19:29,898 --> 01:19:30,999
IN ONE BITE

2178
01:19:31,066 --> 01:19:32,467
-Whole loaches.
-Yes.

2179
01:19:33,668 --> 01:19:35,737
It's all about the flavor.

2180
01:19:36,972 --> 01:19:38,273
BANG!

2181
01:19:38,573 --> 01:19:39,508
NERVOUS

2182
01:19:39,574 --> 01:19:41,443
He just banged the table with his spoon.

2183
01:19:42,210 --> 01:19:44,112
Does it move around in your mouth?

2184
01:19:44,179 --> 01:19:46,148
It's like they're alive.

2185
01:19:46,214 --> 01:19:49,484
-The tails began to flop.
-Did they flounder?

2186
01:19:49,551 --> 01:19:50,619
Wow.

2187
01:19:50,685 --> 01:19:51,787
The pasta is amazing.

2188
01:19:55,090 --> 01:19:56,291
What is it?

2189
01:19:56,358 --> 01:19:57,292
IT'S SO CHEWY

2190
01:19:57,359 --> 01:19:59,327
-The texture?
-Is it chewy?

2191
01:19:59,394 --> 01:20:00,996
I'm sorry.

2192
01:20:01,062 --> 01:20:03,398
I was just reminded of the pasta

2193
01:20:03,465 --> 01:20:05,233
I had before this one.

2194
01:20:05,300 --> 01:20:07,903
The pasta was seasoned perfectly.

2195
01:20:07,969 --> 01:20:10,605
Really? Were the noodles seasoned well?

2196
01:20:10,672 --> 01:20:12,707
-You have to season the pasta.
-If you take a look,

2197
01:20:12,774 --> 01:20:14,810
this guy… Whoa!

2198
01:20:14,876 --> 01:20:16,545
-It's alive.
-It's alive.

2199
01:20:18,113 --> 01:20:21,249
-It might escape! Catch it! Whoa!
-Whoa!

2200
01:20:21,316 --> 01:20:23,418
You're all ridiculous.

2201
01:20:23,752 --> 01:20:24,986
IT'S THE HOLIDAYS

2202
01:20:25,487 --> 01:20:26,354
ENCORE

2203
01:20:26,421 --> 01:20:27,556
It's alive!

2204
01:20:27,622 --> 01:20:29,791
Hey, it might bite you!

2205
01:20:29,858 --> 01:20:31,793
That loach might bite you.

2206
01:20:31,860 --> 01:20:33,528
It'll run away if you drop it.

2207
01:20:33,595 --> 01:20:35,697
But the color

2208
01:20:35,764 --> 01:20:39,701
of the carbonara is different
from what I know.

2209
01:20:40,235 --> 01:20:42,571
It's more yellow than I thought.

2210
01:20:42,637 --> 01:20:45,240
What was your intention behind this?

2211
01:20:45,307 --> 01:20:48,977
Because loaches do not live
in clear water.

2212
01:20:50,512 --> 01:20:53,014
He recreated muddy water.

2213
01:20:53,081 --> 01:20:54,749
UNDERSTOOD THE ORIGINAL CREATOR PERFECTLY

2214
01:20:54,816 --> 01:20:57,319
Because Poong's loaches…

2215
01:20:57,385 --> 01:20:58,553
His dung loaches

2216
01:20:58,620 --> 01:21:00,989
were made with soy sauce,

2217
01:21:01,056 --> 01:21:02,824
<i>which turned the water brown.</i>

2218
01:21:02,891 --> 01:21:04,626
It's just as how one loach

2219
01:21:04,693 --> 01:21:07,362
can muddy the entire pond.

2220
01:21:07,429 --> 01:21:09,898
-He captured it perfectly.
-Choi Loach?

2221
01:21:09,965 --> 01:21:11,466
The water became muddy.

2222
01:21:11,533 --> 01:21:13,535
That was what he captured.

2223
01:21:13,602 --> 01:21:14,803
And the button mushroom.

2224
01:21:14,870 --> 01:21:17,172
When the fresh mushroom hits,

2225
01:21:17,239 --> 01:21:18,573
it refreshes the flavor fatigue.

2226
01:21:18,640 --> 01:21:21,610
-It's immaculate.
-He says it's immaculate.

2227
01:21:21,676 --> 01:21:23,578
VERY PLEASED

2228
01:21:23,645 --> 01:21:25,513
Are you happy with the reinterpretation?

2229
01:21:25,580 --> 01:21:27,649
It's absolutely delicious,

2230
01:21:27,716 --> 01:21:28,950
it also captured my spirit,

2231
01:21:29,017 --> 01:21:32,520
and this direct presentation
makes the dish perfect.

2232
01:21:32,587 --> 01:21:34,222
-You know…
-He's an artist.

2233
01:21:34,289 --> 01:21:37,659
-…this is probably worthy of full marks.
-Is it?

2234
01:21:37,726 --> 01:21:39,928
That's bad news for Chef Jong-won.

2235
01:21:39,995 --> 01:21:42,564
Next, please try Poong Stan.

2236
01:21:42,631 --> 01:21:45,934
JONG-WON'S REINTERPRETATION
OF I AM DEEP-FRYING MELON

2237
01:21:46,735 --> 01:21:50,505
SERVED WITH MELON GAZPACHO
IN A SUNFLOWER BOWL

2238
01:21:51,273 --> 01:21:55,043
CHEF SON JONG-WON'S POONG STAN

2239
01:21:55,110 --> 01:21:56,678
That's melon gazpacho.

2240
01:21:56,745 --> 01:21:59,214
-Should I start with the soup?
-Have a couple sips of gazpacho,

2241
01:21:59,281 --> 01:22:01,249
-and then try the melon.
-Okay.

2242
01:22:01,316 --> 01:22:02,717
Try the fritter later.

2243
01:22:02,784 --> 01:22:04,552
I wonder what it's like.

2244
01:22:04,619 --> 01:22:06,021
It smells…

2245
01:22:06,755 --> 01:22:08,823
I can smell melon,

2246
01:22:08,890 --> 01:22:11,126
but I can oddly smell bread too.

2247
01:22:11,192 --> 01:22:12,527
What was your intention?

2248
01:22:12,594 --> 01:22:15,630
Gazpacho is a soup
with many different flavors,

2249
01:22:15,697 --> 01:22:17,165
including spiciness.

2250
01:22:17,232 --> 01:22:18,800
I wanted to add various flavors

2251
01:22:18,867 --> 01:22:20,969
to depict the ups and downs of life.

2252
01:22:21,036 --> 01:22:22,203
Many different flavors.

2253
01:22:22,270 --> 01:22:24,539
He wanted to add many flavors
to that dish.

2254
01:22:24,606 --> 01:22:27,008
It had lots of flavors when I tried it.

2255
01:22:27,075 --> 01:22:28,410
WHEN POONG EATS JONG-WON'S DISH

2256
01:22:28,476 --> 01:22:30,512
He wanted Poong to taste various flavors.

2257
01:22:30,578 --> 01:22:32,247
<i>-Poong's eyes widened.</i>
<i>-His eyes widened.</i>

2258
01:22:32,314 --> 01:22:33,715
PREVIOUSLY, WHEN JONG-WON HAD POONG'S DISH

2259
01:22:35,317 --> 01:22:39,054
This kind of flavor isn't in his database.

2260
01:22:39,654 --> 01:22:41,189
EYES WIDENED

2261
01:22:41,256 --> 01:22:42,324
So?

2262
01:22:42,390 --> 01:22:44,926
-What is it?
-Something in my mouth

2263
01:22:45,694 --> 01:22:48,330
-tasted like I was panning for gold dust.
-Gold dust?

2264
01:22:48,396 --> 01:22:49,397
At first,

2265
01:22:49,464 --> 01:22:53,101
the melon hits me
with its cool and sweet flavors.

2266
01:22:53,168 --> 01:22:56,037
But it's the flavors of prosciutto
and other ingredients

2267
01:22:56,104 --> 01:22:58,106
that remain until the end.

2268
01:22:58,173 --> 01:23:00,175
-Is there a chew to it?
-There is.

2269
01:23:01,176 --> 01:23:02,110
Gold is pricey these days.

2270
01:23:03,845 --> 01:23:05,146
Does it taste like gold?

2271
01:23:05,213 --> 01:23:06,214
But you know,

2272
01:23:06,281 --> 01:23:08,950
I didn't know melon gazpacho
could be this good.

2273
01:23:09,017 --> 01:23:10,752
It tasted like many different things.

2274
01:23:10,819 --> 01:23:12,487
Anyway, this was delicious.

2275
01:23:12,554 --> 01:23:13,855
That's the main dish,

2276
01:23:13,922 --> 01:23:16,691
-the ones you made last time.
-The melon fritters.

2277
01:23:16,758 --> 01:23:18,827
Those are the melon fritters,

2278
01:23:18,893 --> 01:23:20,428
which Jong-won upgraded.

2279
01:23:20,495 --> 01:23:22,931
I saw him spread the ingredients on this.

2280
01:23:22,998 --> 01:23:25,467
<i>-There's melon inside, right?</i>
<i>-Yes.</i>

2281
01:23:25,533 --> 01:23:28,303
-Let me try it.
-These weren't deep-fried.

2282
01:23:29,037 --> 01:23:30,805
What's it like?
I wonder what the melon is like.

2283
01:23:30,872 --> 01:23:33,041
Yes, I wonder.

2284
01:23:35,610 --> 01:23:37,212
What is it?

2285
01:23:37,278 --> 01:23:38,313
I can't see.

2286
01:23:38,880 --> 01:23:40,048
A PIECE OF MELON BETWEEN THE BREAD

2287
01:23:40,115 --> 01:23:41,616
-The melon.
-It's in there.

2288
01:23:41,683 --> 01:23:43,551
That's a big piece.

2289
01:23:43,618 --> 01:23:46,955
It must have more texture
than the ones you made.

2290
01:23:47,489 --> 01:23:48,323
MMM

2291
01:23:48,390 --> 01:23:50,792
It was heartbreaking to see
the batter come off the melon.

2292
01:23:52,227 --> 01:23:53,762
<i>I didn't want the melon to escape,</i>

2293
01:23:53,828 --> 01:23:56,331
<i>so I secured it with bread</i>
<i>and the melon spread.</i>

2294
01:23:56,398 --> 01:23:59,200
That difference
is why he's a professional.

2295
01:23:59,267 --> 01:24:01,469
Poong didn't know that technique.

2296
01:24:02,203 --> 01:24:04,305
-My gosh.
-That technique.

2297
01:24:04,372 --> 01:24:07,409
-This is marvelous.
-Back then, the batter came off.

2298
01:24:07,475 --> 01:24:09,744
This could be a new trend.
People will say things like,

2299
01:24:09,811 --> 01:24:11,279
"Have you had the melon bread?"

2300
01:24:11,346 --> 01:24:13,581
-Just like the old Gookjini Bread?
-Yes.

2301
01:24:13,648 --> 01:24:15,250
-Gookjini Bread?
-Gookjini Bread.

2302
01:24:15,316 --> 01:24:17,685
-Dubai chewy cookie.
-Dubai chewy cookie is viral now.

2303
01:24:17,752 --> 01:24:19,888
It's perfect. There's nothing to improve.

2304
01:24:19,954 --> 01:24:22,357
It doesn't feel like an attempt
to recreate a recipe.

2305
01:24:22,424 --> 01:24:25,894
It tastes like something
that's already being sold somewhere.

2306
01:24:25,960 --> 01:24:28,630
Chef Jong-won,
why don't you sign a contract with me?

2307
01:24:28,696 --> 01:24:30,265
Jongwoni Bread.

2308
01:24:30,331 --> 01:24:34,135
-Jongwoni Bread.
-So you think you can sell this, right?

2309
01:24:34,202 --> 01:24:36,438
Nam-no would find everything good.

2310
01:24:36,871 --> 01:24:37,939
YUM

2311
01:24:39,074 --> 01:24:41,142
-Nice.
-Can he sell this right away?

2312
01:24:42,510 --> 01:24:45,847
-Is it good enough to…
-It must be good.

2313
01:24:46,614 --> 01:24:48,016
-I'm curious.
-There is a difference

2314
01:24:48,083 --> 01:24:50,652
between persimmons
and dried persimmons, right?

2315
01:24:50,718 --> 01:24:52,954
The melon inside tastes half-dried.

2316
01:24:53,021 --> 01:24:54,823
Yes, you're right.

2317
01:24:54,889 --> 01:24:56,624
-It's chewy too.
-Half-dried melon.

2318
01:24:56,691 --> 01:24:58,226
It lost its juice,

2319
01:24:58,293 --> 01:25:01,963
which seeped into the bread
with its aroma,

2320
01:25:02,030 --> 01:25:05,066
so the melon inside
is left with a chewy texture.

2321
01:25:05,767 --> 01:25:06,935
Is it that good?

2322
01:25:07,001 --> 01:25:09,337
-Do you want to try this too?
-It must be hard.

2323
01:25:09,404 --> 01:25:10,905
-I'm in trouble.
-Why?

2324
01:25:10,972 --> 01:25:13,741
You said Chef Hyun-suk's dish
was near full marks.

2325
01:25:16,244 --> 01:25:19,447
You're eating that
like a bear devouring salmon.

2326
01:25:19,514 --> 01:25:22,650
He's devouring the loaches right now.

2327
01:25:22,717 --> 01:25:24,018
I want a bite too.

2328
01:25:24,085 --> 01:25:26,154
The twins are so eager to try.

2329
01:25:26,554 --> 01:25:27,922
A BITE

2330
01:25:27,989 --> 01:25:30,892
It's as if they're scooping out fish.

2331
01:25:30,959 --> 01:25:32,360
PASSES OVER

2332
01:25:32,427 --> 01:25:34,896
-You're the pasta expert.
-Was it seasoned perfectly?

2333
01:25:34,963 --> 01:25:36,231
The pasta is alive.

2334
01:25:36,297 --> 01:25:37,732
It would still taste good cold.

2335
01:25:37,799 --> 01:25:39,601
Does the loach shape bother you?

2336
01:25:40,201 --> 01:25:41,936
Not at all. It's deliciously chewy.

2337
01:25:42,003 --> 01:25:44,405
He used <i>tsuyu</i> and abalone innards
to make the pasta,

2338
01:25:44,472 --> 01:25:46,774
<i>so compared to regular pasta,</i>

2339
01:25:46,841 --> 01:25:50,712
you can taste more umami
as you continue to chew.

2340
01:25:50,778 --> 01:25:54,616
It makes me wonder why we haven't been
making pasta like this before.

2341
01:25:54,682 --> 01:25:56,918
LITTLE NAM-NO KEEPS MUNCHING
AS THE ADULTS CHAT…

2342
01:25:56,985 --> 01:25:58,353
Sam's unable to put his spoon down.

2343
01:25:58,419 --> 01:26:00,288
-It's good.
-Is it?

2344
01:26:00,355 --> 01:26:01,422
YUM

2345
01:26:01,489 --> 01:26:03,992
Poong is torn.

2346
01:26:04,058 --> 01:26:06,427
-Which reinterpretation…
-I knew this would happen.

2347
01:26:06,494 --> 01:26:08,897
…captured his heart?

2348
01:26:08,963 --> 01:26:11,399
Will it be Jong-won's Poong Stan?

2349
01:26:11,466 --> 01:26:13,434
Or will it be Choi Loach?

2350
01:26:14,802 --> 01:26:18,473
He just fell into a trap
he set out for himself.

2351
01:26:19,707 --> 01:26:21,609
SELECTION INFERNO

2352
01:26:21,676 --> 01:26:22,911
You know…

2353
01:26:24,045 --> 01:26:27,315
-This is hard. This one is so hard.
-How will he decide?

2354
01:26:28,149 --> 01:26:30,351
Which chef's intention

2355
01:26:30,418 --> 01:26:32,220
and reinterpretation

2356
01:26:32,287 --> 01:26:34,756
-I shouldn't have made them fight.
-did you like better?

2357
01:26:34,822 --> 01:26:36,457
<i>Press one to choose Jong-won</i>

2358
01:26:36,524 --> 01:26:38,126
<i>and two to choose Hyun-suk.</i>

2359
01:26:38,193 --> 01:26:40,662
Will it be the melon fritter?
Or the dung loach?

2360
01:26:40,728 --> 01:26:42,397
HIS CURRENT OTHER HALF
VS. A FRIEND OF 10 YEARS

2361
01:26:42,463 --> 01:26:44,799
I've never seen him this stressed out.

2362
01:26:44,866 --> 01:26:47,835
-Don't put any personal feelings in.
-I won't.

2363
01:26:47,902 --> 01:26:50,505
-Forget the relationships.
-I will.

2364
01:26:50,572 --> 01:26:52,907
You chose so quickly
in the previous round.

2365
01:26:52,974 --> 01:26:54,742
Yes, he was so quick before.

2366
01:26:54,809 --> 01:26:57,478
Amy Park looks rather sullen.

2367
01:26:57,545 --> 01:27:00,215
-I'm sorry.
-He made his choice so quickly earlier.

2368
01:27:00,281 --> 01:27:01,816
It's time to decide.

2369
01:27:01,883 --> 01:27:03,518
Press one for Jong-won

2370
01:27:03,585 --> 01:27:05,086
and two for Hyun-suk.

2371
01:27:07,455 --> 01:27:10,258
He pressed the button.

2372
01:27:10,725 --> 01:27:12,560
HE MADE HIS DECISION

2373
01:27:12,627 --> 01:27:14,529
He's still torn even after deciding.

2374
01:27:15,430 --> 01:27:16,364
No regrets?

2375
01:27:16,431 --> 01:27:19,033
It truly just was

2376
01:27:19,867 --> 01:27:21,903
by a hair's breadth.

2377
01:27:21,970 --> 01:27:25,506
That kind of talk
means nothing to the loser.

2378
01:27:25,573 --> 01:27:27,609
Everyone says the same thing.

2379
01:27:27,675 --> 01:27:29,544
Yes, I know that too!

2380
01:27:29,611 --> 01:27:30,878
I know that too!

2381
01:27:30,945 --> 01:27:32,313
That's the worst to hear.

2382
01:27:32,380 --> 01:27:34,983
I know that these words mean nothing.

2383
01:27:35,049 --> 01:27:37,185
But what can I do? It's true.

2384
01:27:37,252 --> 01:27:38,186
The result is in.

2385
01:27:38,253 --> 01:27:41,923
Let's find out who Poong chose. Show us!

2386
01:27:41,990 --> 01:27:44,692
Which one of them
will take Poong to paradise?

2387
01:27:44,759 --> 01:27:48,162
Was it Hyun-suk's reinterpretation
of the dung loaches?

2388
01:27:48,229 --> 01:27:51,099
Or was it Jong-won's reinterpretation
of the melon fritters?

2389
01:27:51,165 --> 01:27:52,900
Poong's choice.

2390
01:27:52,967 --> 01:27:54,936
Who did he choose?

2391
01:27:55,637 --> 01:27:57,939
Which chef is it?

2392
01:27:58,873 --> 01:28:00,775
Who did he choose?

2393
01:28:00,842 --> 01:28:02,343
The difference was a hair's breadth!

2394
01:28:05,246 --> 01:28:06,681
The difference was a hair's breadth!

2395
01:28:06,748 --> 01:28:08,149
CHOI HYUN-SUK WINS

2396
01:28:08,216 --> 01:28:09,050
Hyun-suk wins.

2397
01:28:09,117 --> 01:28:11,185
CHEF CHOI HYUN-SUK'S CHOI LOACH WINS

2398
01:28:12,153 --> 01:28:13,521
POONG DINES AND DASHES

2399
01:28:13,588 --> 01:28:16,291
-It was him!
-Hyun-suk wins.

2400
01:28:16,357 --> 01:28:17,392
Poong flees.

2401
01:28:19,060 --> 01:28:21,529
He gives a star to Choi Loach.

2402
01:28:21,596 --> 01:28:25,099
This is it. Tank Boy wins.

2403
01:28:26,100 --> 01:28:27,969
IT WAS GOOD

2404
01:28:28,036 --> 01:28:29,370
Good grief.

2405
01:28:29,437 --> 01:28:32,707
I'll release my reasons later
in a written document.

2406
01:28:32,774 --> 01:28:34,542
There must've been a difference.

2407
01:28:34,609 --> 01:28:37,278
The melon fritter I had made me realize

2408
01:28:37,345 --> 01:28:39,347
that there are no limits,

2409
01:28:39,414 --> 01:28:42,784
that in the culinary world,
there are no limitations.

2410
01:28:42,850 --> 01:28:44,185
It hit me in a new way

2411
01:28:44,252 --> 01:28:46,888
with a new kind of flavor in the melon.

2412
01:28:46,954 --> 01:28:47,822
Yes, but?

2413
01:28:48,189 --> 01:28:49,023
SIGH…

2414
01:28:49,090 --> 01:28:50,124
But really,

2415
01:28:50,191 --> 01:28:52,560
I don't feel so happy about this.

2416
01:28:52,627 --> 01:28:56,864
Deep in my heart,
I didn't want to give him high points.

2417
01:28:56,931 --> 01:28:58,666
The moment I saw the shapes,

2418
01:28:58,733 --> 01:29:01,436
I thought, "I wanted to make
something like those!"

2419
01:29:01,502 --> 01:29:05,039
He came right across with that intention.

2420
01:29:05,106 --> 01:29:06,908
It rubbed something in me,

2421
01:29:06,974 --> 01:29:10,578
-that envy and jealousy. I was jealous.
-Jealousy.

2422
01:29:10,645 --> 01:29:12,146
Like, "How did he do this?"

2423
01:29:12,213 --> 01:29:14,816
I had to admit my defeat.

2424
01:29:14,882 --> 01:29:17,952
I'm sorry, Chef Jong-won.

2425
01:29:18,019 --> 01:29:21,556
Chef Hyun-suk puts the brakes on
Chef Jong-won's winning streak.

2426
01:29:21,622 --> 01:29:23,725
Can we get a word from you?

2427
01:29:23,791 --> 01:29:26,527
-I've lived for quite a while now.
-Yes.

2428
01:29:26,594 --> 01:29:28,796
But I didn't know I had this side in me.

2429
01:29:28,863 --> 01:29:31,966
I have cooked for many different guests,

2430
01:29:32,033 --> 01:29:36,738
but I have never been this desperate
to win a star from a guest.

2431
01:29:36,804 --> 01:29:39,207
I began to wonder

2432
01:29:39,273 --> 01:29:42,043
why I longed for his star this much.

2433
01:29:42,110 --> 01:29:43,878
I lived many years off of barley porridge

2434
01:29:44,712 --> 01:29:46,381
and pushed through difficulties
after the war.

2435
01:29:46,447 --> 01:29:47,849
And taking pictures on a tank.

2436
01:29:47,915 --> 01:29:51,986
I even had to get on a tank
as I continuously walked down my road,

2437
01:29:52,053 --> 01:29:54,188
and I will finally be content
with Poong's star.

2438
01:29:55,790 --> 01:29:58,426
It must be comforting.

2439
01:29:58,493 --> 01:30:02,096
Chef Jong-won,
you might be a little disappointed.

2440
01:30:02,163 --> 01:30:05,333
I did my best to send him to paradise,

2441
01:30:05,400 --> 01:30:06,234
but it was all in vain.

2442
01:30:07,568 --> 01:30:10,938
It's all in vain.
Who cares about the Best Couple Award?

2443
01:30:11,005 --> 01:30:14,308
-I mean, right?
-They're hardly a couple now.

2444
01:30:14,375 --> 01:30:16,944
-They were so good together.
-That was that.

2445
01:30:17,011 --> 01:30:19,180
-He'll just leave.
-He said he loved your dessert.

2446
01:30:19,247 --> 01:30:20,681
-Come on.
-Everyone feels awkward now.

2447
01:30:20,748 --> 01:30:22,750
-He said it was really good.
-Forget the couple.

2448
01:30:22,817 --> 01:30:24,986
Enough! Please stop!

2449
01:30:25,052 --> 01:30:26,220
All right.

2450
01:30:26,287 --> 01:30:29,657
It looks like they won't be wearing
the matching T-shirt anytime soon.

2451
01:30:29,724 --> 01:30:32,693
Have a great holiday

2452
01:30:32,760 --> 01:30:34,762
and Happy Lunar New Year.

2453
01:30:34,829 --> 01:30:37,298
Please put a star on Chef Hyun-suk!

2454
01:30:37,799 --> 01:30:38,733
Great work.

2455
01:30:40,368 --> 01:30:43,538
He still has his game.

2456
01:30:43,604 --> 01:30:45,840
This is his second star!

2457
01:30:45,907 --> 01:30:47,041
STAY TUNED FOR THE PREVIEW

2458
01:30:47,708 --> 01:30:48,843
And a hug!

2459
01:30:48,910 --> 01:30:49,811
We get to see this?

2460
01:30:49,877 --> 01:30:51,479
Are we watching <i>EXchange?</i>

2461
01:30:51,546 --> 01:30:52,847
A love-hate relationship.

2462
01:30:55,116 --> 01:30:57,452
As I mentioned previously,
it's an emergency.

2463
01:30:57,518 --> 01:30:58,553
Is there an emergency?

2464
01:30:58,619 --> 01:30:59,687
Too many are after this.

2465
01:30:59,754 --> 01:31:01,088
Rawr.

2466
01:31:01,155 --> 01:31:03,191
LITTLE TIGER, CHEF KIM SI-HYEON

2467
01:31:03,257 --> 01:31:04,225
Rawr.

2468
01:31:05,193 --> 01:31:07,762
TWO POPULAR STARS AMONG GEN Z,
AN YU-JIN AND PARK JIN-YOUNG

2469
01:31:07,829 --> 01:31:09,964
You aren't supposed to call her An Yu-jin.

2470
01:31:10,031 --> 01:31:12,099
Please call me Yu-jin
to feel more friendly.

2471
01:31:12,166 --> 01:31:13,768
-Yu-jin.
-Yu-jin.

2472
01:31:14,235 --> 01:31:15,102
HAPPY YU-JIN

2473
01:31:15,169 --> 01:31:17,038
Hey, Yu-jin. Do you like <i>malatang?</i>

2474
01:31:17,605 --> 01:31:19,207
ERROR IN THE PERFORMANCE

2475
01:31:19,273 --> 01:31:21,309
<i>I spent the last decade dancing.</i>

2476
01:31:21,375 --> 01:31:23,211
<i>I began to think</i>
<i>more about the performance.</i>

2477
01:31:23,277 --> 01:31:25,079
THE RIVAL DANCERS FACE EACH OTHER

2478
01:31:26,614 --> 01:31:28,449
DON'T FORGET TO PERFORM AS YOU COOK

2479
01:31:28,516 --> 01:31:29,784
WOW

2480
01:31:29,851 --> 01:31:31,419
Gen-Z snacks for Yu-jin.

2481
01:31:31,486 --> 01:31:33,087
CHEFS MORE VIRAL THAN DUBAI CHEWY COOKIES

2482
01:31:33,154 --> 01:31:34,589
MAKE DESSERTS RIGHT UP HER ALLEY

2483
01:31:34,989 --> 01:31:37,058
HE'S MAKING KADAYIF?

2484
01:31:37,258 --> 01:31:39,193
HE ACTUALLY DID THAT?

2485
01:31:39,494 --> 01:31:42,163
AN EXPLOSIVE RESPONSE

2486
01:31:42,563 --> 01:31:44,565
WHO WILL POPULAR GEN Z STAR YU-JIN CHOOSE?

2487
01:31:48,269 --> 01:31:50,771
My favorite member of IVE,
An Yu-jin, is here today, so…

2488
01:31:50,838 --> 01:31:53,541
-Just "Yu-jin."
-Come on!

2489
01:31:53,608 --> 01:31:54,842
-Please!
-She had made it clear.

2490
01:31:54,909 --> 01:31:55,977
I missed that.

2491
01:32:05,953 --> 01:32:10,758
Subtitle translation by: Eunsook Youn
